    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\AKCLOUD-PRD-SDG-001.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\AKCLOUD-PRD-SDG-001.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AKCloud — SDG / Digital Inclusion Expansion\n2: ## Product Requirements Document (PRD)\n3: \n4: **Reference:** AKCLOUD-PRD-SDG-001\n5: **Status:** DRAFT — Strategic exploration, not committed roadmap\n6: **Date:** 13 June 2026\n7: **Author:** Andie Enning, compiled in collaboration with Claude (Anthropic)\n8: **Scope:** Extension of AKCloud's sovereign cloud thesis to digital-inclusion / SDG-aligned markets\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. Context and Problem Statement\n13: \n14: AKCloud's core thesis — established across prior ADRs — is: **sovereign, self-hosted, open-source infrastructure that gives regulated organisations data residency, compliance, and freedom from hyperscaler lock-in, delivered as a managed service on top of free or near-free compute (OCI Always Free ARM).**\n15: \n16: The thesis was developed for UK/EU regulated SMEs facing GDPR Article 44, NIS2, DORA, the EU Data Act, and the EU AI Act. This PRD asks: **does the same underlying architecture solve a structurally similar problem in markets where the constraint isn't regulatory compliance but cost and connectivity?**\n17: \n18: The hypothesis: organisations in low-resource settings — schools, NGOs, small businesses, local government — in markets with expensive or unreliable cloud access face their own version of \"you cannot legally/affordably use the hyperscaler default.\" AKCloud's BYOC, low-operator-overhead, open-source-first model may transfer.\n19: \n20: This is explicitly **not** a pivot. It is a parallel-market exploration that reuses the same technical core (Cozystack/Talos on OCI Always Free, Odoo/LAMPForge/BigBlueButton catalogue) under a different value proposition framing.\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## 2. Why Now — Evidence Base\n25: \n26: - The Nairobi \"Sr Odoo Consultant, Solution Architect\" listing (Advance Insight, June 2026) demonstrates live demand for Odoo implementation expertise in East Africa, independent of AKCloud.\n27: - Lagos's announced data centre expansion (146MW+ pipeline, target 2030) signals growing African cloud infrastructure investment — but infrastructure investment at the hyperscale level does not automatically translate to affordable access for small organisations, which is precisely the gap AKCloud's model addresses in the UK.\n28: - LAMPForge (AKCloud catalogue item 002) was already designed for a resource-constrained education context (Welsh secondary schools) — the architecture (Student Workspace Manager, code-server, local LLM Teacher Demonstration Engine) was built assuming limited budgets and infrastructure, which is directly portable.\n29: - BigBlueButton (AKCLOUD-CAT-003) running on a free OCI ARM tier already demonstrates that AKCloud's stack delivers genuinely useful collaboration infrastructure (video conferencing) at £0/month marginal cost — a capability with obvious value in connectivity-constrained settings.\n30: - The develoPPP Ventures programme (BMZ-backed, SDG-aligned, non-dilutive capital, currently covering Ghana, Kenya, Rwanda, South Africa, Tanzania) was identified as currently ineligible (AKCloud is pre-revenue, UK-registered, no matching funds) — but it establishes that **funders explicitly looking for SDG-aligned digital infrastructure exist and have capital allocated**, which validates the framing even if this specific instrument doesn't fit today.\n31: \n32: **Honest framing:** this section identifies that the *category* of opportunity is real and funded. It does not establish that AKCloud is currently positioned to capture it. Section 7 (Gaps) is explicit about what would need to be true first.\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## 3. SDG Alignment — Mapped Explicitly\n37: \n38: Funders and procurement processes in this space score against the UN Sustainable Development Goals. AKCloud's existing architecture maps to:\n39: \n40: | SDG | How AKCloud's stack contributes |\n41: |---|---|\n42: | **SDG 4 — Quality Education** | LAMPForge: AI-assisted LAMP stack learning platform, code-server in-browser dev environments, local LLM tutoring (no per-seat SaaS cost) |\n43: | **SDG 9 — Industry, Innovation and Infrastructure** | Sovereign, self-hosted PaaS (Cozystack/Talos) deployable on free-tier ARM compute — lowers the capital barrier to running modern infrastructure |\n44: | **SDG 10 — Reduced Inequalities** | Removes dependency on hyperscaler pricing and US-jurisdiction terms; gives small organisations the same infrastructure quality as large ones |\n45: | **SDG 17 — Partnerships for the Goals** | Open-source foundation (Cozystack/Talos/Odoo, all Apache-2.0/LGPL) means local technical communities can fork, extend, and self-support rather than depend on AKCloud indefinitely |\n46: \n47: This mapping is **descriptive, not aspirational** — every component listed already exists in AKCloud's catalogue or has a working runbook (BBB on OCI ARM, LAMPForge Helm chart).\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ## 4. Proposed Product Scope\n52: \n53: ### 4.1 What this PRD is NOT proposing\n54: - A new product. The technical catalogue (Odoo, LAMPForge, BigBlueButton, the Cozystack/Talos PaaS layer) is unchanged.\n55: - A geographic pivot away from UK/EU sovereign-cloud work, which remains the primary near-term focus.\n56: - Direct AKCloud operations in any African market in the near term.\n57: \n58: ### 4.2 What this PRD IS proposing\n59: A **second framing and packaging** of the existing AKCloud catalogue, targeted at:\n60: - NGOs and education non-profits operating in low-connectivity/low-budget settings\n61: - Local government and civic-tech initiatives in markets with data-sovereignty concerns of their own (many African nations have, or are developing, data protection frameworks analogous to GDPR)\n62: - Diaspora-led organisations (a natural fit given Andie's own Afro-Italian/Ghanaian background and existing FirstGens UK / Afro-Italian archive networks) who want to deploy infrastructure \"back home\" without recurring hyperscaler billing in foreign currency\n63: \n64: ### 4.3 The \"Diaspora Bridge\" framing\n65: A specific, differentiated angle: AKCloud-as-deployed-by-diaspora-technologists for organisations connected to diaspora networks. This is not a generic \"AKCloud goes to Africa\" play — it leverages Andie's existing relationships (FirstGens UK, Afro-Italian cultural archive contacts, Enprise Network) as the initial distribution channel, the same way the UK accountant-referral channel was identified for the Odoo/SME play. The differentiation is relational, not technical.\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## 5. Success Criteria (what \"working\" looks like)\n70: \n71: This is explicitly exploratory, so success criteria are about **validating the hypothesis cheaply**, not hitting revenue targets:\n72: \n73: 1. **Validation conversation count:** Speak to 3-5 people in Andie's existing diaspora/NGO networks about whether \"self-hosted infrastructure deployed on free-tier cloud, managed remotely\" is a recognisable pain point for organisations they know.\n74: 2. **Technical portability check:** Confirm the LAMPForge / BBB / Cozystack stack genuinely runs on OCI Always Free ARM tiers available in regions relevant to target markets (or via the same global OCI Always Free allocation, which is region-selectable at signup).\n75: 3. **One pilot deployment:** If validation conversations surface a real candidate organisation (e.g., through FirstGens UK's network or an Afro-Italian archive contact), deploy one instance of LAMPForge or BBB for them at zero cost, as a proof-of-concept and case study.\n76: 4. **Funder mapping:** Identify 2-3 specific grant/non-dilutive programmes (beyond develoPPP, which is currently ineligible) that fund SDG-aligned digital infrastructure for diaspora or NGO-led organisations, and check their eligibility criteria against AKCloud's actual status before investing further time.\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## 6. Non-Goals / Explicit Exclusions\n81: \n82: - This PRD does not propose incorporating any new legal entity.\n83: - This PRD does not propose AKCloud taking on hosting liability for organisations outside UK/EU jurisdiction in the near term — the BYOC model (client owns the infrastructure account) is the only viable structure here, exactly as in the UK Odoo play, and is *more* important in this context because AKCloud cannot reasonably take on data-protection liability for jurisdictions it doesn't operate in.\n84: - This PRD does not propose diverting effort from the three unmade UK moves (Odoo Referral Partner application, accountant DMs, MTD sovereignty article) — those remain higher priority and lower effort.\n85: \n86: ---\n87: \n88: ## 7. Gaps and Open Questions\n89: \n90: - **No revenue model has been specified.** The UK play has a clear commission/management-fee structure tied to Odoo. The diaspora/NGO play may need to be grant-funded, donation-supported, or pro-bono/case-study in its first instance — this needs honest acknowledgement that it may not be a revenue line for a long time, if ever, and may instead be a goodwill/network/case-study activity that strengthens AKCloud's broader narrative (including for fellowship/grant applications like EWOR).\n91: - **Jurisdictional data-protection frameworks** in candidate markets (Ghana, Kenya, Nigeria, etc.) have not been researched. BYOC mitigates AKCloud's direct liability, but a credible pitch to any organisation still requires understanding what compliance story matters to them locally.\n92: - **No named candidate organisation exists yet.** Step 1 (validation conversations) must happen before any further product work.\n93: \n94: ---\n95: \n96: ## 8. Relationship to Existing AKCloud ADRs\n97: \n98: This PRD does not supersede or contradict any existing AKCloud ADR. It proposes a **second value-proposition lens** on the same ADR-defined technical architecture (see AKCLOUD-ARD-SDG-001, companion document). If validation in Section 5 fails to surface genuine interest within a reasonable timeframe (suggested: one quarter of opportunistic, low-effort conversations — not a dedicated sprint), this PRD should be archived without further investment, having cost only a handful of conversations.\n99: \n100: ---\n101: \n102: *End of AKCLOUD-PRD-SDG-001.*\n\n(End of file - total 102 lines)\n</content>",
