      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\granite_oracle_articles.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # IBM Granite — Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) Articles with Abstracts\n2: \n3: Oracle's relationship with IBM Granite spans two tracks: (1) the **Oracle AI & Data Science Blog** with hands-on technical deployment guides for specific Granite model families on OCI Data Science / AI Quick Actions, and (2) a **strategic partnership** layer announced at IBM THINK 2025 (May 2025) covering full watsonx stack + Granite model integration across OCI. Both tracks are documented below.\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## TRACK A: Oracle Technical / Engineering Blog (OCI Data Science)\n8: \n9: ---\n10: \n11: **1. Introducing IBM Granite 3.3 Model on OCI Data Science**\n12: https://blogs.oracle.com/ai-and-datascience/introducing-ibm-granite-33\n13: *Published: May 6, 2025 | Oracle AI & Data Science Blog*\n14: \n15: **Abstract:** Oracle's own engineering blog formally introducing Granite 3.3 (the 8B and 2B instruct variants) on OCI Data Science, timed to coincide with the THINK 2025 IBM-Oracle partnership announcement. Explains the Granite 3.3 architecture: 12T token training across 12 languages and 116 programming languages, improved reasoning, Fill-in-the-Middle (FIM) code completion, 128K context window, RAG, function calling, and safety benchmarks. Walks through the two deployment paths available to OCI users: (a) pull directly from Hugging Face via AI Quick Actions Model Explorer, or (b) download artifacts and store in OCI Object Storage before registering as a model. Once registered, models can be deployed or fine-tuned using service-managed containers — no underlying infrastructure management required. Specifically targets regulated industries (financial services, healthcare, public sector, defence) where Apache 2.0 licensing, transparency, and IBM's IP indemnity are critical to AI adoption.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: **2. Zero-Shot Time Series Forecasting Using Granite TTM on OCI Data Science**\n20: https://blogs.oracle.com/ai-and-datascience/zeroshot-time-series-forecasting-granite-ttm-oci\n21: *Published: August 14, 2025 | Oracle AI & Data Science Blog*\n22: \n23: **Abstract:** Oracle's dedicated technical blog post announcing native support for IBM's TinyTimeMixer (Granite TTM-R1) in Oracle AI Quick Actions — the first pretrained time series model integrated into the OCI Data Science platform. Explains the zero-shot deployment flow: open AI Quick Actions from the Data Science Notebook → navigate to Model Explorer → select granite-timeseries-ttm-r1 → deploy → stream multivariate time series data via API endpoint and receive forecasts with no training code required. Notes TTM's key enterprise advantages for OCI customers: sub-1M parameter footprint runs on CPU-only machines (no GPU cost), outperforms multi-billion-parameter benchmarks in zero-shot and few-shot settings, and can forecast across diverse domains (energy, finance, supply chain, IoT) without domain-specific retraining. This is the most technically specific Oracle article on any individual Granite model family.\n24: \n25: ---\n26: \n27: ## TRACK B: IBM–Oracle Strategic Partnership (THINK 2025)\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: **3. IBM and Oracle Expand Partnership to Advance Agentic AI and Hybrid Cloud (Official IBM Press Release)**\n32: https://newsroom.ibm.com/2025-05-06-ibm-and-oracle-expand-partnership-to-advance-agentic-ai-and-hybrid-cloud\n33: *Published: May 6, 2025 | IBM Newsroom / PRNewswire*\n34: \n35: **Abstract:** The master announcement from IBM THINK 2025 laying out the full scope of the IBM-Oracle OCI expansion. Three Granite-specific commitments: (1) Oracle will make the entire IBM Granite model family available through OCI Data Science via AI Quick Actions as a cached LLM in H2 2025; (2) watsonx Orchestrate (July 2025) will run natively on OCI using Red Hat OpenShift on OCI, including public, sovereign, government, and Oracle Alloy regions for regulatory/data residency requirements; (3) watsonx.ai is certified to run on OCI bare metal and virtual machine instances. IBM Consulting is expanding Oracle-specific consulting services covering AI agent orchestration, legacy workload migration to Red Hat OpenShift Virtualization on OCI, and end-to-end business process transformation. First use case announced is HR automation. Quotes Oracle Cloud EVP Greg Pavlik: \"IBM and Oracle have been collaborating to drive customer success for decades, and our expanded partnership will provide customers new ways to help transform their businesses with AI.\"\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: **4. IBM and Oracle Expand Agentic AI and Hybrid Cloud Partnership**\n40: https://insideainews.com/2025/05/07/ibm-and-oracle-expand-agentic-ai-and-hybrid-cloud-partnership/\n41: *Published: May 7–12, 2025 | insideAI News*\n42: \n43: **Abstract:** AI-specialist trade press coverage of the IBM-Oracle partnership, focusing on the technical architecture of watsonx Orchestrate running on Red Hat OpenShift on OCI and what that means for enterprise AI workloads. Notes the significance of Oracle Alloy regions (partner-operated OCI regions) and sovereign cloud availability — allowing Granite-powered agents to run within national data sovereignty boundaries, a key requirement for European and government customers. Covers watsonx.ai OCI certification, Granite model availability via AI Quick Actions, IBM Envizi ESG Suite on OCI, and IBM Consulting services expansion. Includes IDC analyst Ritu Jyoti quote: \"The Agentic AI approach IBM is taking with Oracle is a leading example of how the ability to orchestrate agentic workflows across systems can drive significant advantages.\"\n44: \n45: ---\n46: \n47: **5. IBM & Oracle Debut watsonx Agentic AI on OCI**\n48: https://www.aiacceleratorinstitute.com/ibm-oracle-debut-watsonx-agentic-ai-on-oci/\n49: *Published: May 9, 2025 | AI Accelerator Institute*\n50: \n51: **Abstract:** AI-focused analysis positioning the IBM-Oracle partnership as a milestone in the shift from AI experimentation to production agentic AI. Notes IBM CEO Arvind Krishna's THINK 2025 declaration that \"the era of AI experimentation is over,\" and frames the Granite models on OCI as a key enabler of out-of-the-box enterprise AI: Granite models pre-trained on finance, supply chain, and customer service datasets mean OCI customers can deploy a Granite model for invoice processing or customer-support triage immediately, then customise with proprietary data. Describes watsonx Orchestrate's drag-and-drop \"action blocks\" interface for building no-code AI agent pipelines on OCI. Covers data privacy challenges (regulatory constraints on autonomous decisions, need for human oversight) and the technical integration path for legacy system connectivity.\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: **6. OCI and IBM Expand Partnership, Customer Wins Incoming**\n56: https://cloudwars.com/ai/oci-and-ibm-expand-partnership-customer-wins-incoming/\n57: *Published: May 21, 2025 | Cloud Wars*\n58: \n59: **Abstract:** Cloud Wars analyst Bob Evans covers the IBM-Oracle deal with focus on commercial implications and customer wins. Details the three-layer IBM commitment to OCI: watsonx Orchestrate (from July 2025) for multi-agent workflow management across Oracle AI Agent Studio for Fusion Applications and OCI Generative AI Agents; Granite model family access via OCI Data Science AI Quick Actions; and watsonx.ai OCI certification plus IBM Envizi ESG Suite. Analyses the strategic rationale: Oracle's enterprise customer base (large Fusion Applications footprints) is exactly the segment that benefits most from IBM Consulting + Granite + OCI combining legacy Oracle ERP with modern AI agents. Notes this is a pattern of hyperscaler partnerships IBM is executing in parallel (AWS, Azure, Google Cloud, OCI) to make Granite accessible wherever enterprise data already lives.\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: **7. IBM and Oracle Target Enterprise AI**\n64: https://hyperframeresearch.com/2025/05/13/ibm-and-oracle-target-enterprise-ai/\n65: *Published: May 13, 2025 | HyperFRAME Research*\n66: \n67: **Abstract:** Independent analyst research note from HyperFRAME assessing the strategic and technical merits of the IBM-Oracle partnership. Technical detail: watsonx Orchestrate agents perform AI inference directly on OCI (not cross-cloud), which is critical because Oracle customers typically co-locate their data and applications on OCI — eliminating data egress costs and latency. Confirms watsonx Orchestrate deployment on Red Hat OpenShift on OCI across public, sovereign, government, and Alloy regions. Notes HyperFRAME will monitor Granite 4.0 appearance in OCI Data Science AI Quick Actions (as flagged in the October 2025 Oracle Fusion Marketplace announcement) as the key technical benchmark for measuring partnership depth. Identifies complexity and legacy integration as the remaining adoption barriers, while positioning the partnership as IBM's most mature multi-system AI orchestration play across any hyperscaler.\n68: \n69: ---\n70: \n71: **8. IBM Announces New AI Agents on Oracle Fusion Applications AI Agent Marketplace**\n72: https://www.stocktitan.net/news/IBM/ibm-announces-new-ai-agents-on-oracle-fusion-applications-ai-agent-c6c7yilbb4a4.html\n73: *Published: October 16, 2025 | IBM Press Release via StockTitan*\n74: \n75: **Abstract:** The October 2025 follow-on announcement confirming IBM's delivery of three production AI agents on the Oracle Fusion Applications AI Agent Marketplace, built with Oracle AI Agent Studio: the **Intercompany Agent** (automated intercompany accounting), **Smart Sales Order Entry Agent** (intelligent order processing), and **Requisition to Contract Agent** (procurement automation). Also confirms IBM Granite 4.0 will be available in OCI Data Science via AI Quick Actions — the first mention of Granite 4.0 specifically in the Oracle context, following the May 2025 announcement that referenced the Granite family generically. IBM additionally plans complementary HR and supply chain agents built with watsonx Orchestrate. This is the most specific confirmation of Granite 4.0's OCI availability timeline.\n76: \n77: ---\n78: \n79: **9. IBM Brings watsonx AI Agents to Oracle Cloud in Major Enterprise AI Push**\n80: https://www.stocktitan.net/news/IBM/ibm-and-oracle-expand-partnership-to-advance-agentic-ai-and-hybrid-jqy4169cuv9k.html\n81: *Published: May 6, 2025 | StockTitan / IBM Newsroom*\n82: \n83: **Abstract:** Financial news syndication of the May 2025 IBM-Oracle press release, adding business context including IBM Envizi ESG Suite's planned initial OCI launch in Saudi Arabia within 12 months — indicating IBM's use of OCI sovereign regions for regulated sustainability reporting deployments. Confirms Granite AI model family as cached LLM in OCI Data Science (H2 2025), watsonx Orchestrate on OCI (July 2025), watsonx.ai OCI certification, and IBM Consulting services expansion. Provides multilingual syndication context (Italian, Spanish, Korean) suggesting the partnership is targeted at global enterprise markets beyond the US.\n84: \n85: ---\n86: \n87: **10. IBM's CEO: 'Era of AI Experimentation Is Over' at THINK 2025 — Oracle Partnership Section**\n88: https://www.techrepublic.com/article/news-ibm-think-2025-ai-oracle-partnership/\n89: *Published: May 7, 2025 | TechRepublic*\n90: \n91: **Abstract:** TechRepublic's comprehensive IBM THINK 2025 roundup, dedicating a significant section to the Oracle partnership and Granite's OCI availability. Notes IBM CEO Arvind Krishna's strategic framing: competitive advantage now requires \"purpose-built AI integration that drives measurable business outcomes\" — positioning Granite's domain-optimised small models as the right tool for Oracle Fusion workloads (finance, HR, supply chain) rather than large general-purpose frontier models. Covers the webMethods Hybrid Integration announcement (connecting APIs, apps, events, files, and mainframe data across hybrid cloud) as the integration layer enabling Granite-powered agents to access Oracle and non-Oracle data sources. IDC analyst Ritu Jyoti quoted on enterprise AI orchestration as a strategic differentiator.\n92: \n93: ---\n94: \n95: **11. IBM and Oracle Deepen Partnership to Advance Agentic AI and Hybrid Cloud**\n96: https://www.dbta.com/Editorial/News-Flashes/IBM-and-Oracle-Deepen-Partnership-to-Advance-Agentic-AI-and-Hybrid-Cloud-169492.aspx\n97: *Published: May 19, 2025 | Database Trends and Applications*\n98: \n99: **Abstract:** Database-specialist trade press coverage focusing on the data infrastructure dimensions of the IBM-Oracle partnership. Emphasises watsonx.ai OCI certification on bare metal and virtual machine instances with Red Hat OpenShift, enabling AI development services to run adjacent to enterprise data that already lives on OCI. Covers Oracle Fusion Cloud and IBM's deep expertise in business transformation as complementary capabilities: IBM Consulting services for Oracle ERP modernisation + Granite models for AI agent task execution within those ERP workflows. Notes IBM and Oracle's \"decades\" of collaboration history as the commercial foundation enabling rapid technical integration compared to partnerships built from scratch.\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: **12. IBM and Oracle Partnership: Era of Advanced AI and Cloud Services Developing**\n104: https://theusaleaders.com/news/ibm-and-oracle-partnership/\n105: *Published: May 8, 2025 | The USA Leaders*\n106: \n107: **Abstract:** Business press analysis covering all three commitment layers of the partnership in accessible terms: (1) Granite lightweight LLMs accessible via OCI Data Science AI Quick Actions for task-specific AI without large model costs; (2) watsonx Orchestrate native on OCI for HR automation (payroll analysis, recruitment) starting July 2025; (3) IBM Consulting using Red Hat OpenShift Virtualization on OCI bare metal to migrate legacy systems to hybrid-cloud architectures. Specifically frames Granite as the \"lightweight, purpose-built\" model choice for Oracle customers who need efficient AI for specific enterprise tasks rather than general-purpose frontier models. Covers IBM Envizi ESG Suite on OCI (starting Saudi Arabia) and IBM Consulting's expanded Oracle practice.\n108: \n109: ---\n110: \n111: ## Oracle Coverage Summary\n112: \n113: | Article | Source | Granite Focus |\n114: |---|---|---|\n115: | Granite 3.3 on OCI Data Science | Oracle Blog | Granite 3.3 deployment via AI Quick Actions |\n116: | Granite TTM Zero-Shot Forecasting on OCI | Oracle Blog | TinyTimeMixer R1 — only Granite TTM OCI article |\n117: | IBM-Oracle THINK 2025 Partnership (IBM Newsroom) | IBM | Full Granite family on OCI, watsonx.ai cert |\n118: | insideAI News Coverage | Trade Press | Sovereign/government regions, data residency |\n119: | AI Accelerator Institute Analysis | AI Press | Granite pre-trained domain models for OCI |\n120: | Cloud Wars Analysis | Analyst | Commercial implications, customer wins |\n121: | HyperFRAME Research Note | Analyst | Technical architecture, Granite 4.0 on OCI |\n122: | Oracle Fusion Marketplace Agents (Oct 2025) | IBM | **Granite 4.0** specifically confirmed on OCI |\n123: | StockTitan / IBM Newsroom | Financial News | ESG + Granite + OCI sovereign regions |\n124: | TechRepublic THINK 2025 Roundup | Tech Press | Strategy framing, CEO quotes |\n125: | Database Trends and Applications | DB Trade Press | Data infrastructure, bare metal OCI |\n126: | The USA Leaders | Business Press | Accessible overview, all partnership layers |\n127: \n128: ---\n129: \n130: ## Key Oracle-Specific Facts\n131: \n132: - **Granite 3.3** was the first Granite generation with a dedicated Oracle blog post (May 2025)\n133: - **Granite TTM-R1** was the first Granite model to get native AI Quick Actions support on OCI (August 2025)\n134: - **Granite 4.0** confirmed for OCI Data Science in the October 2025 Oracle Fusion Marketplace announcement\n135: - **Deployment method**: OCI users access Granite via **AI Quick Actions** in OCI Data Science Notebooks — either direct Hugging Face pull or OCI Object Storage artifact registration\n136: - **Sovereign/Alloy regions**: IBM agents (using Granite for inference) run on OCI across public, sovereign, government, and Oracle Alloy partner-operated regions — a key differentiator vs AWS and Azure sovereign cloud offerings\n137: - **watsonx.ai on OCI**: Certified on bare metal + VMs with Red Hat OpenShift, enabling enterprises to develop Granite-powered AI services adjacent to Oracle ERP/application data\n138: - **Oracle Fusion integration**: Granite models serve as the AI backbone for IBM-built agents on the Oracle Fusion Applications AI Agent Marketplace (Intercompany, Sales Order Entry, Requisition to Contract agents)\n\n(End of file - total 138 lines)\n</content>",
