know is that we decided to not use any UI frameworks from the beginning, and that’s still true today. Because performance is very important to us and we want to be fully in control of our own destiny. So we don't want to chase a framework or track down performance in the framework. We want to be directly as close to the DOM as possible.\"\n283: \n284: Context and Explanation:\n285: \n286: What is VS Code's Secret?\n287: As Erich Gamma explained, VS Code doesn't use popular UI frameworks like React or Angular. Instead, it’s built using \"Vanilla JavaScript\" (or more accurately, TypeScript) and interacts directly with the DOM (Document Object Model).\n288: \n289: By avoiding the overhead of a framework, the VS Code team can optimize every single part of the interface for speed and memory efficiency. Frameworks often add layers of abstraction that, while making development easier, can introduce performance bottlenecks. For a tool as complex as a code editor, staying \"close to the metal\" (the DOM) is crucial.\n290: \n291: Why does vscode.dev load so fast?\n292: \n293: When you visit vscode.dev, you're seeing the culmination of years of web technology optimization. Here’s why it loads almost instantly:\n294: \n295: 1. It’s a Progressive Web App (PWA):\n296: VS Code in the browser is a PWA. It uses Service Workers to cache the core application files on your device the first time you visit. When you return, your browser doesn't have to download the whole app again; it just loads it from your local disk.\n297: \n298: 2. WebAssembly (Wasm):\n299: Parts of VS Code that require heavy computation (like syntax highlighting or language services) are often compiled into WebAssembly. Wasm allows code to run at near-native speeds in the browser, far faster than traditional JavaScript for complex tasks.\n300: \n301: 3. No \"Backend\" Required for the UI:\n302: The entire user interface is rendered on the client side (your browser). Because there’s no UI framework to initialize and no complex server-side rendering required before the page displays, the \"Time to Interactive\" is incredibly low.\n303: \n304: 4. Web Workers:\n305: VS Code uses Web Workers to run heavy tasks (like searching through files) in the background. This ensures the main thread (the one handling the UI) stays responsive, making the app feel \"snappy\" from the moment it appears.\n306: \n307: 5. Built-in Browser APIs:\n308: Instead of relying on heavy libraries, vscode.dev leverages modern browser APIs for things like file system access (File System Access API), allowing you to open local folders directly in the browser with almost no latency.\n309: \n310: In short, VS Code is a masterclass in modern web engineering. By skipping the frameworks and using highly optimized, low-level web technologies, Microsoft has created a desktop-class experience that lives entirely in your browser.\n311: \n312: *Viewed [forge-build.yml](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/.github/workflows/forge-build.yml) *\n313: \n314: *Viewed [pde-setup.mjs](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/scripts/pde-setup.mjs) *\n315: \n316: *Viewed [implementation_plan.md](file:///C:/Users/LLM-Test/.gemini/antigravity/brain/be0006ca-c51f-4052-af1b-cef8aaf535a0/implementation_plan.md) *\n317: \n318: *Edited relevant file*\n319: \n320: ### User Input\n321: \n322: This is a system-generated message that is sent due to the user's review policy. Proceed with the decision that you think is the most optimal here.\n323: \n324: *Edited relevant file*\n325: \n326: *Edited relevant file*\n327: \n328: *User accepted the command `node scripts/pde-setup.mjs --diagnose`*\n329: \n330: *Checked command status*\n331: \n332: *Edited relevant file*\n333: \n334: *Edited relevant file*\n335: \n336: *Edited relevant file*\n337: \n338: ### User Input\n339: \n340: does it have to be minified going to oracle oci? and can u show me oracle oci now registered with my new account