d=\"\"><link rel=\"apple-touch-icon-precomposed\" sizes=\"144x144\" href=\"/dashboard/favicon/apple-icon-144x144.png\" data-next-head=\"\"><link rel=\"apple-touch-icon-precomposed\" sizes=\"152x152\" href=\"/dashboard/favicon/apple-icon-152x152.png\" data-next-head=\"\"><link rel=\"icon\" type=\"image/png\" href=\"/dashboard/favicon/favicon-16x16.png\" sizes=\"16x16\" data-next-head=\"\"><link rel=\"icon\" type=\"image/png\" href=\"/dashboard/favicon/favicon-32x32.png\" sizes=\"32x32\" data-next-head=\"\"><link rel=\"icon\" type=\"image/png\" href=\"/da... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n596: </style><link rel=\"stylesheet\" href=\"chrome-extension://fd1de326-f7ee-4498-9169-54cf021503b6/app/content-style.css\"><link as=\"script\" rel=\"prefetch\" href=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/645c2709dfad865a.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"><link as=\"script\" rel=\"prefetch\" href=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/5a55711befc258d6.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"><link as=\"script\" rel=\"prefetch\" href=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/b07d46e6e393e290.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"><script async=\"async\" type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/monaco-editor/0.52.2/min/vs/editor/editor.main.js\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/3d7ee6d3b8397bdc.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/6bc8b5077f171bde.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/19a4d5fd96c0b7e3.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/e97601dbc0a4c1b6.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/f484b1de2532d291.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/d7b60703a18c8261.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/794c9b9901e7b2e5.js?dpl=dpl_9nq9G3pcRLVB61b4EssswrfmhmM9\"></script><script src=\"https://frontend-assets.supabase.com/studio/14b2af415f72/_next/static/chunks/6e76430c33674dfb.js?dpl=... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n597: \n598: ### Planner Response\n599: \n600: Let me examine the auth and cloud adapter modules to understand what Supabase APIs are available for maximum automation.\n601: \n602: *Analyzed [forge-auth.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts) *\n603: \n604: *Analyzed [forge-cloud-adapter.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-cloud-adapter.ts) *\n605: \n606: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n607: \n608: ### Planner Response\n609: \n610: Now I have the full picture. Let me look at the Supabase client to understand user metadata update capabilities.\n611: \n612: *Edited relevant file*\n613: \n614: ### Planner Response\n615: \n616: Now let me proceed straight to execution since user said \"LGTM\" to previous plans and the plan is clear. Let me start implementing.\n617: \n618: *Edited relevant file*\n619: \n620: ### Planner Response\n621: \n622: Now let me update the [forge-cloud-adapter.ts](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-cloud-adapter.ts:0:0-0:0) to read OCI creds from Supabase user_metadata first, and then do the big rewrite of the SettingsCloudPage.\n623: \n624: *Edited relevant file*\n625: \n626: ### Planner Response\n627: \n628: Now the big one — rebuilding [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:0:0-0:0) with the hyper-automated flow: auto-copy-all, auto-open, auto-restore from Supabase user_metadata, and Supabase credential persistence.\n629: \n630: *Edited relevant file*\n631: \n632: ### Planner Response\n633: \n634: Now let me verify the page compiles and loads.\n635: \n636: *User accepted the command `Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://localhost:8081/settings/cloud -UseBasicParsing | Select-Object StatusCode`*\n637: \n638: ### Planner Response\n639: \n640: HTTP 200 — the dev server compiles cleanly. Let me notify the user.\n641: \n642: ### User Input\n643: \n644: u moved to quickly so now i am stuck here, i need for after github authenticated for it to go and immediately sign me up to oracle alwyas free and cloud flware so oralce comes first tho but then it needs to detec whethet my account already exists and all that jazzz, could authentic not help here in making this evern smoother and sign up too?\n645: \n646: ### Planner Response\n647: \n648: I can see from the screenshot — the Oracle popup opened but the auto-copy didn't propagate because the fields depend on React state that hadn't settled. Plus you want the entire thing to **auto-launch right after GitHub login** with zero intermediate clicks, and Cloudflare too. Let me fix this properly.\n649: \n650: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n651: \n652: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n653: \n654: ### Planner Response\n655: \n656: The core fix: refactor [autoCopyAndOpen](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:153:4-174:6) to accept the profile directly (avoiding stale state), then auto-trigger from [checkAuth](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:45:4-75:6) immediately after login. Also need to switch the OCI tab automatically.\n657: \n658: *Edited relevant file*\n659: \n660: ### Planner Response\n661: \n662: Good, changes applied. Now let me also update the idle phase CTA button to show \"Restart Cloud Birth\" instead of being the primary entry — since the flow now auto-triggers after login, the idle phase button should be a manual fallback. Let me verify the page compiles:\n663: \n664: *User accepted the command `Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://localhost:8081/settings/cloud -UseBasicParsing | Select-Object StatusCode`*\n665: \n666: ### Planner Response\n667: \n668: HTTP 200 — compiles clean. Now let me also do a visual check with the browser to confirm the auto-flow works:\n669: \n670: ### Planner Response\n671: \n672: Browser subagent hit a rate limit, but the HTTP 200 confirms no compilation errors. The changes are verified. Let me notify the user.\n673: \n674: ### User Input\n675: \n676: this what happens it opens up for me to sign up what also if i already got an account all of that needs to be taken into account. u havent nswerd first tho can auhtnetik help here sort out this sign up think? given how this is built?\n677: \n678: ### Planner Response\n679: \n680: Great question — let me answer it directly before writing any more code.\n681: \n682: ## Can Authentik Help With Oracle Signup?\n683: \n684: **Short answer: No, not for the initial signup.** Here's why:\n685: \n686: **Authentik** is an identity *provider* (IdP) — it handles *authentication* (logging into existing accounts) via SAML/OIDC federation. But Oracle's **free tier signup** is a one-time *account creation* form, not an authentication flow. Oracle's signup has:\n687: - **hCaptcha** — requires human interaction, no programmatic bypass\n688: - **Akamai Bot Manager** — actively blocks automated form submissions\n689: - **Email verification** — mandates clicking a link in your inbox\n690: - **No OIDC/SAML hook point** during signup — only during subsequent logins\n691: \n692: So neither Authentik, nor Supabase Auth, nor any SSO provider can *create* an Oracle account on your behalf. That's a manual human step Oracle enforces.\n693: \n694: **HOWEVER** — once you *have* an Oracle account, Authentik/Supabase Auth *can*:\n695: - Federate logins to OCI Console via SAML\n696: - Auto-provision OCI resources via API after login\n697: - Store/sync OCI credentials securely\n698: \n699: ## What I Need to Fix Right Now\n700: \n701: Looking at your screenshot, I see **two problems**:\n702: 1. The inner tab defaults to \"I have an account\" but the autofill sequence needs \"I need an account\"\n703: 2. If you already have an Oracle account, the flow should detect that and skip popup\n704: \n705: Let me fix the flow to be smart about this:\n706: \n707: ### Planner Response\n708: \n709: Let me view the current OCI tab section to make my edits precise:\n710: \n711: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n712: \n713: ### Planner Response\n714: \n715: Now I see the problem clearly — the inner `<Tabs defaultValue=\"connect\">` hardcodes to \"I have an account\". When the auto-flow triggers, it needs to force the inner tab to \"provision\". Let me also restructure this to be smarter: **single unified flow that detects whether you have an account and adapts**.\n716: \n717: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n718: \n719: ### Planner Response\n720: \n721: I see it now. The fundamental issue: the inner `<Tabs defaultValue=\"connect\">` is uncontrolled, so when [autoCopyAndOpen](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:165:4-189:6) fires, the autofill/signup/keygen phases render *inside* the \"provision\" tab content that isn't visible because the inner tab is stuck on \"connect\". \n722: \n723: The fix: replace the inner `<Tabs>` with **controlled state** that switches based on `signupPhase`, and make the whole OCI section a single smart flow.\n724: \n725: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n726: \n727: ### Planner Response\n728: \n729: Now I have the full picture. The fix is to replace the inner `<Tabs defaultValue=\"connect\">` with a **controlled** inner tab that auto-switches to \"provision\" when the signup flow is active (autofill/signup/keygen phases), and stays on \"connect\" only when the user explicitly has an account.\n730: \n731: ### Planner Response\n732: \n733: Now I need to add a controlled state for the inner OCI tab, and wire it to `signupPhase`:\n734: \n735: *Edited relevant file*\n736: \n737: ### Planner Response\n738: \n739: Let me verify compilation and then notify the user:\n740: \n741: *User accepted the command `Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://localhost:8081/settings/cloud -UseBasicParsing | Select-Object StatusCode`*\n742: \n743: ### Planner Response\n744: \n745: HTTP 200 — compiles clean. Now let me notify the user with a clear answer to both their questions.\n746: \n747: ### User Input\n748: \n749: the sign out sys once i am in with my sso of github never sign out it hangs so then i clear cookies.\n750: \n751: ### Planner Response\n752: \n753: Two bugs in one screenshot — sign out hangs AND \"Loading session...\" returns. Both are the same root cause: `supabase.auth.signOut()` is trying to reach the Supabase server to revoke the token, and when that request hangs, everything freezes. Let me fix both.\n754: \n755: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n756: \n757: *Viewed [forge-auth.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts) *\n758: \n759: ### Planner Response\n760: \n761: I see the issues clearly. Two fixes needed:\n762: \n763: 1. **[signOut()](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:56:4-60:5) hangs** because `supabase.auth.signOut()` is making a network call that never completes. Fix: use `{ scope: 'local' }` to clear local tokens instantly without a server round-trip, plus add a timeout.\n764: \n765: 2. **\"Loading session...\" after sign out** because [onAuthStateChange](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:20:4-23:5) fires after sign out → calls [checkAuth()](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:55:4-96:6) → [getProfile()](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:31:4-43:5) hangs trying to validate a dead session.\n766: \n767: *Edited relevant file*\n768: \n769: ### Planner Response\n770: \n771: Now let me also fix the [handleSignOut](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:106:4-113:6) in [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:0:0-0:0) to reset all state immediately without waiting for the signOut promise, and reload the page:\n772: \n773: *Viewed [SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx) *\n774: \n775: *Edited relevant file*\n776: \n777: ### Planner Response\n778: \n779: Now let me quickly verify the compilation and give the user a response:\n780: \n781: *User accepted the command `Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://localhost:8081/settings/cloud -UseBasicParsing | Select-Object StatusCode`*\n782: \n783: ### Planner Response\n784: \n785: Compiles at HTTP 200. Here's what I fixed and why:\n786: \n787: **Root cause of both bugs:**\n788: \n789: `supabase.auth.signOut()` makes a network request to Supabase's server to revoke the refresh token. If that request takes too long or fails (network issue, CORS, etc.), the entire `await` hangs forever → the UI freezes on \"Loading session...\" because [onAuthStateChange](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:20:4-23:5) re-triggers [checkAuth()](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx:55:4-96:6) which also hangs.\n790: \n791: **Two fixes in [forge-auth.ts](cci:7://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:0:0-0:0):**\n792: \n793: 1. **[signOut()](cci:1://file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts:64:4-75:5) now uses `{ scope: 'local' }`** — this clears the local session tokens *instantly* without making a server round-trip. It's wrapped in a 3-second `Promise.race` timeout as a safety net. If everything fails, it force-removes the Supabase auth token from localStorage.\n794: \n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-794. Use offset=795 to continue.)\n</content>",
