      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\Downloads\\\\edgeandcloudhyrd_walkthrough.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\edgeandcloudhyrd_walkthrough.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Final Walkthrough: AI Resilience & Deep Tech Inference\n2: \n3: We have successfully delivered the full \"Deep Tech\" browser-native AI server and a robust administrative diagnostic suite.\n4: \n5: ## Core Features Delivered\n6: \n7: ### 1. Direct WebNN & Pavone Persistence\n8: - **Direct WebNN Engine**: Uses `onnxruntime-web` to leverage Intel GPU/NPU hardware acceleration directly.\n9: - **Pavone Resilience**: Implements an IndexedDB-backed \"thought stream\" recovery system. The AI saves its internal KV-cache state and can resume context instantly after a browser crash.\n10: \n11: ### 2. Advanced Diagnostics & console.* Pipe\n12: We've implemented a full-spectrum diagnostic bridge for fallback troubleshooting.\n13: - **Console Monkey-Patching**: Every `console.log`, `console.warn`, and `console.error` from the browser is automatically piped to the Admin Panel's Inference Log. This ensures that hidden WASM errors or ONNX initialization failures are instantly visible.\n14: - **Developer Terminal (CLI)**: A new interactive console in the Admin Panel that allows executing JavaScript commands in the browser context with highest privileges. You can probe [ort](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-opfs-cache.ts#17-20), manually trigger `runOnnxInference`, or check hardware concurrency.\n15: - **System Health Probe**: A one-click diagnostic tool that audits your machine's hardware capabilities (NPU/GPU presence, memory limits, WebNN support).\n16: \n17: ### 3. Inference Cascade\n18: A 4-tier fault-tolerant chain: Foundry Local → Groq → Cerebras → WebNN/ONNX.\n19: \n20: ### 4. Native WebSocket Bridge (Extension-Free)\n21: To avoid the complexities of Manifest V3 browser extensions, we built a standalone Node.js proxy ([copilot-bridge.mjs](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/server/copilot-bridge.mjs)). This proxy listens on port 3000, accepts standard OpenAI-compatible `/v1/chat/completions` REST traffic from existing IDEs (like VS Code or OpenVSCode Server), and routes it via WebSocket directly into the active Browser tab. The browser executes the inference against the hardware-accelerated WebNN engine and streams the generated tokens back to the IDE.\n22: \n23: ### 5. LAMPForge Animated Agentic CLI (v1.0.0)\n24: A fully interactive, terminal-native CLI application ([src/cli/index.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/cli/index.tsx)) built using `ink` (React for the terminal).\n25: - **Animated Entrance:** Features a frame-animated, terminal-safe ASCII logo taking inspiration from GitHub Copilot's engineering standards (using semantic 4-bit ANSI colors to support accessibility overrides).\n26: - **Latent Token Sync:** The CLI reads [.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/vite.config.ts) and `.sql` files from the workspace upon boot. It syncs this data over the WebSocket bridge into the browser's IndexedDB, building a Latent Token 'KV-Cache'.\n27: - **Command Router:** Supports slash commands (e.g., `/model Groq`, `/foundry start`, `/help`), allowing the developer to dynamically alter the inference backend or trigger the local foundry server directly from the command line.\n28: \n29: ### 6. Portable Edge Launcher (Kasm-Style Zero-Config)\n30: A complete user-space deployment kit that requires **zero admin rights**:\n31: - **[launch-lampforge.cmd](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/launch-lampforge.cmd):** Single-click launcher that auto-detects Edge (portable or system), injects all WebNN/WebGPU/WASM/SharedArrayBuffer flags, and opens LAMPForge as a standalone PWA window.\n32: - **[config/initial_preferences](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/config/initial_preferences):** JSON that pre-enables all `chrome://flags` experiments so users never need to manually toggle anything.\n33: - **[setup-portable.ps1](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/setup-portable.ps1):** One-time bootstrap that creates the folder structure, injects preferences, checks for Edge/Node/ONNX model, and installs npm dependencies.\n34: \n35: **Execution Provider Priority (CPU-first for DfE):**\n36: 1. WebNN (CPU) — Intel AVX-512 / VNNI / DL Boost\n37: 2. WASM SIMD — Universal fallback\n38: 3. WebNN (GPU) — Intel Iris Xe (if available)\n39: \n40: ### 7. Dual-Browser Model Pre-Baking & Versioned Registry\n41: Cross-referenced **both** flag dumps (Edge 145.0.3800.82 + Chrome 145.0.7632.117) to build a complete dual-browser AI system:\n42: - **[launch-lampforge.cmd](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/launch-lampforge.cmd):** v3.0 — detects Edge vs Chrome, injects the correct LLM flags (Phi-mini for Edge, Gemini Nano for Chrome), and copies the matching preferences file automatically.\n43: - **[config/edge_initial_preferences](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/config/edge_initial_preferences):** Edge-specific JSON with Phi-mini Prompt/Summarizer/Writer/Rewriter API flags.\n44: - **[prebake-models.html](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/prebake-models.html):** Browser-hosted model pre-baker. Detects available APIs, force-triggers model downloads with progress monitoring, warms the model, and records versions in IndexedDB.\n45: - **[forge-model-registry.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-model-registry.ts):** TypeScript module with [probeCapabilities()](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-model-registry.ts#76-115), [prebakeModel()](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-model-registry.ts#116-198), ONNX blob caching, and version history queries.\n46: - **[prebake-models.mjs](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/prebake-models.mjs):** Bun/Node script that scans Edge & Chrome internal model cache directories, backs up to `user-data/model-backups/` with SHA256 checksums and versioned manifests.\n47: \n48: **Key flag discoveries:**\n49: \n50: | Browser | Built-in LLM | Flag ID | APIs |\n51: |:---|:---|:---|:---|\n52: | Edge 145 | **Phi-mini** | `#edge-llm-prompt-api-for-phi-mini` | prompt, summarize, write, rewrite |\n53: | Chrome 145 | **Gemini Nano** | `#prompt-api-for-gemini-nano` | prompt, summarize, write, rewrite |\n54: | Both | **ONNX Runtime** | `#webnn-onnxruntime` | WebNN CPU/GPU/NPU inference |\n55: | Both | **DirectML** | `#webnn-directml` | GPU/NPU hardware accel |\n56: \n57: ### 8. Kasm-Style PWA Workspace & Offline Edge Deployment\n58: Transformed the PDE into a **self-contained workspace OS** that runs like Kasm — but entirely in the browser, offline-capable, with pre-baked models:\n59: - **[manifest.json](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/public/manifest.json):** PWA manifest with `display_override: [\"tabbed\", \"window-controls-overlay\"]` for Kasm-style tabbed workspace, `tab_strip` config, [.forge](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/.forge) file handling, share target, and `web+forge://` protocol handler.\n60: - **[sw.js](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/public/sw.js):** Service Worker with 3 strategies: Cache-First (app shell), Network-First (API), Cache-Forever (ONNX models + WASM binaries ~190MB cached permanently). Background Sync for offline writes, Periodic Sync for model updates.\n61: - **[forge-storage-pool.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-storage-pool.ts):** File System Access API wrapper — mount any folder (local SSD or Rclone-mounted R2/S3 drive) as the workspace pool. FTP-style browse, read, write, delete. Offline writes queued for Background Sync.\n62: - **[index.html](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/index.html):** Updated with SW registration and periodic model update sync.\n63: \n64: **The \"Lab in a Box\" concept:** Models are pre-baked locally (like Amazon Snowball), preferences inject all workspace flags automatically, the service worker ensures everything works offline, and the File System Access API bridges to any mounted cloud storage pool.\n65: \n66: ### 9. Chaos-Resilient Cloud Chain & SSO Wizard\n67: Implemented a zero-dependency fault-tolerant cloud storage chain using existing tools:\n68: - **[forge-auth.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-auth.ts):** Supabase acts as the SSO HUB (GitHub + Google OAuth). The JWT gates access to all other cloud services. No new identity providers needed.\n69: - **[forge-opfs-cache.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-opfs-cache.ts):** High-performance Edge Hibernation layer using the Origin Private File System (`navigator.storage.getDirectory()`). Used for massive binary persistence (190MB ONNX blobs) without blowing up IndexedDB quotas.\n70: - **[forge-cloud-adapter.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-cloud-adapter.ts):** Hybrid adapter routing small files to Supabase Storage and large models to Cloudflare R2 via a Worker proxy (using Supabase JWT for auth).\n71: - **[SettingsCloudPage.tsx](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/pages/SettingsCloudPage.tsx):** A 4-step wizard at `/settings/cloud` letting users connect Supabase (auto), R2, and OCI, culminating in a \"Chaos Verification\" ping test.\n72: \n73: ## Quick Start\n74: ```\n75: 1. .\\setup-portable.cmd           # One-time setup\n76: 2. npm run dev                    # Start Vite dev server\n77: 3. .\\launch-lampforge.cmd         # Opens Edge/Chrome with correct AI flags\n78: 4. Open prebake-models.html       # Force-pull built-in models\n79: 5. bun prebake-models.mjs         # Back up models to user-space\n80: ```\n81: \n82: ## Verification Summary\n83: - **Type Check**: ✅ Build stable (`tsc` pass).\n84: - **Console Pipe**: ✅ Verified browser-to-admin logging.\n85: - **Node Bridge**: ✅ Proxy successfully multiplexing CLI, IDE, and Browser traffic.\n86: - **CLI App**: ✅ Animated Ink UI rendering correctly and dispatching `/commands`.\n87: - **Launcher**: ✅ Edge/Chrome opens with browser-specific AI flags pre-injected, no admin required.\n88: - **Model Registry**: ✅ IndexedDB versioning and user-space backup with SHA256 integrity.\n89: - **Resilience**: ✅ Latent Token state (KV-Cache) verified in IndexedDB.\n90: \n91: ---\n92: *Status: Architecture Complete. Dual-browser, zero-config, fault-tolerant AI workbench with model pre-baking.*\n93: \n94: ## Phase 17: Semantic FinOps Routing & Green Computing 🌍\n95: \n96: With the fundamental chaos-resilience verified, Phase 17 introduced the concept of **Intelligent \"Green\" Load Balancing**:\n97: \n98: - **Edge-Native Semantic Embedder**: Created [forge-embedder.ts](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/src/lib/forge-embedder.ts) to analyze [.forge](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/.forge) prompts directly on the user's local CPU. It calculates a `complexity_score` and `semantic_category` based on keyword density and token length, eliminating the need for a cloud-based routing LLM.\n99: - **Green Computing / Battery-Aware Routing**: Wired the Web Battery API into [FinOpsLedger](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/sdk/forge-finops.ts#50-215). If a student's laptop battery drops below 20% and the [.forge](file:///c:/Users/LLM-Test/LAMPForge_SDTP/forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821/.forge) intent is highly complex (score > 0.4), the load balancer dynamically shifts processing to the Cloud (OCI/Groq) to preserve device lifespan—but only if the FinOps budget permits.\n100: - **Strict Budget Fallback**: If the active Policy-as-Code is set to `$0.00` (like the pre-baked `wjec-zero-cloud` policy), the Green Load Balancer is overridden. All traffic is forced back to local WebNN processing, mathematically guaranteeing zero bill shock for educational deployments.\n\n(End of file - total 100 lines)\n</content>",
