      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\RandD\\\\terraform_iac_integration.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\RandD\\terraform_iac_integration.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Terraform / IaC Integration Vision for .forge\n2: \n3: **Document Version:** 1.0\n4: **Date:** 2026-03-06\n5: **Purpose:** R&D vision for Infrastructure as Code support in SDTP\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## Context\n10: \n11: Infrastructure as Code (IaC) - specifically **Terraform** - is the #1 most in-demand skill for cloud engineers in 2026 (source: analysis of 536 cloud job descriptions, March 2026). AWS re/Start graduates need practical IaC experience to be job-ready.\n12: \n13: ### The Problem\n14: \n15: 1. **Terraform has a learning curve** - HCL syntax, state management, providers, modules\n16: 2. **Students lack safe sandboxes** - real AWS accounts cost money, mistakes are costly\n17: 3. **No pedagogical scaffolding** - existing tools don't teach *why*, just *how*\n18: 4. **Disconnect from curriculum** - IaC labs don't map to awarding body requirements\n19: \n20: ### The .forge Opportunity\n21: \n22: .forge already solves this pattern for databases (SQL workbench + pedagogue commentor). The same approach applies to IaC:\n23: \n24: - **Declarative config** → `.forge` YAML already does this\n25: - **Pedagogical annotations** → commentor explains each resource\n26: - **Safe execution** → sandbox environments, budget controls\n27: - **Curriculum alignment** → map to AWS re/Start learning outcomes\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## Schema Relationships\n32: \n33: ### Do They Use Their Own Schemas?\n34: \n35: | Tool | Schema Format | Who Owns It |\n36: |------|---------------|-------------|\n37: | **Terraform** | HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language) | HashiCorp |\n38: | **AWS CloudFormation** | JSON/YAML with AWS-specific schema | AWS |\n39: | **Pulumi** | TypeScript/Python/Go (uses cloud SDKs) | Pulumi |\n40: | **Crossplane** | Kubernetes CRDs (YAML) | CNCF |\n41: | **Ansible** | YAML with Ansible module schema | Red Hat |\n42: | **.forge** | YAML with SDTP schema | LAMPForge (you) |\n43: \n44: **Key insight:** Each tool has its own schema. .forge is no different - it's an original schema for a different domain (pedagogical environments).\n45: \n46: ### How .forge Could Integrate\n47: \n48: ```mermaid\n49: flowchart TD\n50:     subgraph FORGE[\".forge Protocol\"]\n51:         F1[\"runtime.iac.provider\"] --> F2[\"terraform | cloudformation | pulumi\"]\n52:         F3[\"runtime.iac.template\"] --> F4[\"Path to .tf or .yaml files\"]\n53:         F5[\"pedagogy.iac_annotations\"] --> F6[\"true | false\"]\n54:     end\n55: \n56:     subgraph EXECUTION[\"Execution Options\"]\n57:         E1[\"Local: Terraform CLI<br/>(if installed)\"]\n58:         E2[\"Cloud: Managed sandbox<br/>(SDTP-hosted)\"]\n59:         E3[\"Simulated: Dry-run mode<br/>(no real resources)\"]\n60:     end\n61: \n62:     F2 --> E1\n63:     F2 --> E2\n64:     F2 --> E3\n65: \n66:     subgraph PEDAGOGY[\"Pedagogical Layer\"]\n67:         P1[\"Commentor annotates<br/>each resource block\"]\n68:         P2[\"Explains: what, why,<br/>cost implications\"]\n69:         P3[\"Maps to AWS re/Start<br/>learning outcomes\"]\n70:     end\n71: \n72:     E1 --> P1\n73:     E2 --> P1\n74:     E3 --> P1\n75: \n76:     style FORGE fill:#339af0,stroke:#1971c2,color:#fff\n77:     style EXECUTION fill:#e9ecef,stroke:#868e96\n78:     style PEDAGOGY fill:#51cf66,stroke:#2f9e44,color:#fff\n79: ```\n80: \n81: > **How to read:** .forge config specifies IaC provider and template path. Execution can happen locally, in cloud sandbox, or simulated (dry-run). All paths feed through the pedagogical layer where the commentor adds teaching annotations.\n82: \n83: ---\n84: \n85: ## \"I Do, You Do, We Do\" Methodology\n86: \n87: This is a proven teaching pattern:\n88: \n89: | Phase | Teacher | Student | .forge Support |\n90: |-------|---------|---------|----------------|\n91: | **I Do** | Demonstrates creating an EC2 instance | Watches | Commentor narrates each step, explains why |\n92: | **You Do** | Observes | Attempts same task independently | Scaffold hints available, errors explained |\n93: | **We Do** | Guides, answers questions | Works alongside | Commentor available but less intrusive |\n94: \n95: ### How .forge Enables This\n96: \n97: ```yaml\n98: # .forge example for AWS re/Start IaC module\n99: protocol: forge/1.0\n100: intent: \"Provision a VPC with public subnet using Terraform\"\n101: \n102: curriculum:\n103:   board: AWSReStart\n104:   unit: 3\n105:   level: L3\n106:   scaffold: exploratory  # High support for beginners\n107: \n108: runtime:\n109:   target: cloud          # Use managed sandbox\n110:   stack: custom\n111:   features:\n112:    - cli-terminal       # For terraform commands\n113:    - code-preview       # See generated plan\n114:    - evidence-capture   # Log for portfolio\n115: \n116:   iac:\n117:     provider: terraform\n118:     template: ./infra/vpc.tf\n119:     sandbox: true        # No real AWS charges\n120:     dry_run: false       # Actually create resources (in sandbox)\n121: \n122: pedagogy:\n123:   annotations:\n124:     style: inline\n125:     include_iac_explanations: true\n126:     include_cost_estimates: true\n127:     include_curriculum_refs: true\n128: \n129:   iac_scaffold:\n130:     level: guided        # \"I do\" phase - heavy annotation\n131:     # Options: guided | supported | independent\n132:     explain_resources: true\n133:     explain_dependencies: true\n134:     explain_state: true\n135:     warn_on_cost: true\n136: ```\n137: \n138: ---\n139: \n140: ## Pedagogical Commentor for Terraform\n141: \n142: ### What It Would Do\n143: \n144: When a student writes or views Terraform code, the commentor adds inline explanations:\n145: \n146: ```hcl\n147: # PEDAGOGY: A \"resource\" block creates something in AWS.\n148: # This one creates a Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) - your own\n149: # private network in the cloud. Think of it like setting up\n150: # your own private office building where you control who\n151: # can enter and what rooms exist.\n152: #\n153: # AWS re/Start Module 3.2: VPC Fundamentals\n154: # Estimated monthly cost: $0.00 (VPCs are free, resources inside cost money)\n155: \n156: resource \"aws_vpc\" \"main\" {\n157:   cidr_block = \"10.0.0.0/16\"  # PEDAGOGY: This is the IP address range.\n158:                                # /16 means ~65,000 addresses available.\n159:                                # Like saying \"our building has 65,000 room numbers\"\n160: \n161:   tags = {\n162:     Name = \"student-vpc\"       # PEDAGOGY: Always tag your resources!\n163:                                # This helps you find them later and track costs.\n164:   }\n165: }\n166: ```\n167: \n168: ### Scaffold Levels\n169: \n170: | Level | Annotation Density | When to Use |\n171: |-------|-------------------|-------------|\n172: | **Guided** | Every line explained | First exposure, \"I do\" phase |\n173: | **Supported** | Key concepts only | \"You do\" phase, student attempts |\n174: | **Independent** | On-demand hints | \"We do\" phase, building confidence |\n175: | **Expert** | None (raw Terraform) | Assessment, portfolio work |\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## Deployment Without Docker\n180: \n181: Just like .forge features work without Docker, IaC support would too:\n182: \n183: ```mermaid\n184: flowchart LR\n185:     subgraph OPTIONS[\"IaC Execution Options\"]\n186:         O1[\"Student machine<br/>has Terraform CLI\"] --> R1[\"Execute locally\"]\n187:         O2[\"No Terraform installed\"] --> R2[\"Use SDTP cloud sandbox\"]\n188:         O3[\"No internet / air-gapped\"] --> R3[\"Dry-run simulation mode\"]\n189:     end\n190: \n191:     R1 --> OUT[\"Same pedagogical<br/>experience regardless<br/>of execution target\"]\n192:     R2 --> OUT\n193:     R3 --> OUT\n194: \n195:     style OPTIONS fill:#fff3bf,stroke:#fab005\n196:     style OUT fill:#51cf66,stroke:#2f9e44,color:#fff\n197: ```\n198: \n199: > **How to read:** Three execution paths based on what the student has available. All three converge on the same pedagogical experience - the teaching layer is consistent regardless of where the infrastructure actually runs.\n200: \n201: ---\n202: \n203: ## Why This Matters for AWS re/Start\n204: \n205: AWS re/Start curriculum includes:\n206: \n207: 1. **Cloud Foundations** - EC2, S3, VPC basics\n208: 2. **Cloud Architecture** - Multi-tier designs\n209: 3. **DevOps Essentials** - CI/CD, IaC\n210: \n211: Currently, re/Start uses:\n212: - AWS Console (clicking) - no IaC skills\n213: - Labs with pre-built templates - no understanding of *why*\n214: - Limited Terraform exposure - not integrated with pedagogy\n215: \n216: **.forge could provide:**\n217: - Integrated IaC learning with curriculum alignment\n218: - Pedagogical annotations explaining each resource\n219: - Safe sandbox execution with FinOps budget controls\n220: - Evidence capture for portfolio/assessment\n221: \n222: ---\n223: \n224: ## Implementation Phases\n225: \n226: ### Phase 1: Terraform Viewer (Read-Only)\n227: - Parse and display .tf files in PDE\n228: - Add pedagogical annotations\n229: - No execution (just visualization)\n230: \n231: ### Phase 2: Dry-Run Mode\n232: - `terraform plan` simulation\n233: - Show what *would* be created\n234: - Cost estimation annotations\n235: \n236: ### Phase 3: Sandbox Execution\n237: - SDTP-managed AWS sandbox accounts\n238: - Real resources, isolated from production\n239: - Automatic cleanup after session\n240: \n241: ### Phase 4: Full Integration\n242: - Student can write Terraform in PDE\n243: - Commentor assists in real-time\n244: - Evidence panel captures for portfolio\n245: \n246: ---\n247: \n248: ## IP Considerations\n249: \n250: This integration does NOT create any IP issues:\n251: \n252: | Concern | Status |\n253: |---------|--------|\n254: | Terraform is open source (MPL 2.0) | We're not modifying Terraform, just orchestrating it |\n255: | HCL is a language, not copyrightable | We're not copying HCL, just parsing it |\n256: | We're adding pedagogical value | Original contribution on top of existing tools |\n257: | No vendor lock-in | Support multiple IaC providers |\n258: \n259: Same legal position as .forge features - we're building an original pedagogical layer, not copying anyone's implementation.\n260: \n261: ---\n262: \n263: ## References\n264: \n265: - Video source: \"Top Cloud Engineer Skills 2026\" (536 job descriptions analyzed)\n266: - Terraform documentation: https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform\n267: - AWS re/Start curriculum: https://aws.amazon.com/training/restart/\n268: - \"I Do, You Do, We Do\" pedagogy: Gradual Release of Responsibility model (Pearson & Gallagher, 1983)\n\n(End of file - total 268 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
