      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\internal\\\\docs-private\\\\sovereign_pde_architecture.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\internal\\docs-private\\sovereign_pde_architecture.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # The Sovereign PDE: Hyperscalability, Portability, Mesh, and Multiplayer\n2: \n3: **Classification:** Internal R&D\n4: **Author:** LAMPForge Architecture\n5: **Status:** Living Document\n6: \n7: ---\n8: \n9: ## What This Document Is\n10: \n11: This document explains the full architectural vision behind LAMPForge as a\n12: **Sovereign PDE** (Personal Development Environment). It assumes no prior\n13: knowledge. It starts from first principles, provides historical context for\n14: every concept, and explains how the pieces we have already built connect to a\n15: much larger possibility space: hyperscalability, portability, mesh networking,\n16: and multiplayer collaboration.\n17: \n18: If you are reading this and thinking \"this sounds like a browser\" -- you are\n19: correct. We are building a browser-within-a-browser that acts as a complete\n20: development environment. The key insight is that the browser is already the\n21: most deployed, most sandboxed, most portable runtime in history. We are\n22: exploiting that rather than fighting it.\n23: \n24: ---\n25: \n26: ## Table of Contents\n27: \n28: 1. [Historical Context: How We Got Here](#1-historical-context-how-we-got-here)\n29: 2. [What Is a PDE?](#2-what-is-a-pde)\n30: 3. [What \"Sovereign\" Means](#3-what-sovereign-means)\n31: 4. [The Portable Edge Browser: Our Kasm](#4-the-portable-edge-browser-our-kasm)\n32: 5. [What We Have Built So Far](#5-what-we-have-built-so-far)\n33: 6. [Hyperscalability: Why This Scales to Millions](#6-hyperscalability-why-this-scales-to-millions)\n34: 7. [Portability: USB Sticks to Cloud](#7-portability-usb-sticks-to-cloud)\n35: 8. [Mesh: Peer-to-Peer Without Servers](#8-mesh-peer-to-peer-without-servers)\n36: 9. [Multiplayer: Real-Time Collaboration](#9-multiplayer-real-time-collaboration)\n37: 10. [CPU Inference: AI Without a GPU](#10-cpu-inference-ai-without-a-gpu)\n38: 11. [The Full Stack Diagram](#11-the-full-stack-diagram)\n39: 12. [Competitive Landscape](#12-competitive-landscape)\n40: 13. [What Comes Next](#13-what-comes-next)\n41: \n42: ---\n43: \n44: ## 1. Historical Context: How We Got Here\n45: \n46: ### The Problem with Development Environments\n47: \n48: In the beginning, developers installed everything directly on their machines.\n49: You needed admin rights. You needed the right OS. You needed compatible\n50: library versions. This was called \"works on my machine\" syndrome, and it\n51: plagued the industry for decades.\n52: \n53: **2001 - VMware Workstation** gave us virtualisation: run a whole operating\n54: system inside your operating system. Schools could snapshot a VM and hand it\n55: to students. But VMs were multi-gigabyte, slow to boot, and required\n56: substantial hardware.\n57: \n58: **2013 - Docker** gave us containers: lightweight, isolated environments that\n59: share the host kernel. Containers are megabytes, not gigabytes. They boot in\n60: seconds. But they still require Docker to be installed, and Docker requires\n61: admin rights on most school networks.\n62: \n63: **2016 - Cloud9 / AWS Cloud9** put the IDE in the browser. No local installs.\n64: But it required an AWS account, internet access, and cost money per hour.\n65: \n66: **2018 - VS Code Remote** let you connect a local editor to a remote\n67: container. Same internet dependency problem.\n68: \n69: **2019 - GitHub Codespaces** combined VS Code + containers + cloud. Excellent\n70: developer experience. But it costs $0.18/hour for a 2-core machine. For a\n71: class of 30 students coding 3 hours per week for 36 weeks, that is $583.20\n72: per year -- per class. Most schools cannot justify this.\n73: \n74: **2020 - StackBlitz WebContainers** ran Node.js in the browser via\n75: WebAssembly. No server needed. But it only supports Node.js, not PHP or\n76: MySQL.\n77: \n78: **2021 - WordPress Playground** proved you could run PHP and SQLite entirely\n79: in WebAssembly in the browser. No server at all.\n80: \n81: **2022 - Kasm Workspaces** containerised entire desktop environments and\n82: streamed them to the browser. Schools loved it. But it requires a server with\n83: substantial resources (4GB RAM per user), a Linux host, and Docker. It is\n84: essentially a VDI (Virtual Desktop Infrastructure) product.\n85: \n86: **Where LAMPForge sits:** We take the \"browser is the computer\" insight from\n87: StackBlitz and WordPress Playground, combine it with the \"pre-configured\n88: environment\" insight from Kasm, and add the \"no admin rights, no cloud, no\n89: cost\" constraint from real schools. The result is a sovereign PDE that runs\n90: entirely in user-space.\n91: \n92: ### Why Schools Are Different\n93: \n94: Schools are not startups. They have:\n95: \n96: - **Locked-down machines** where students cannot install software\n97: - **Filtered networks** that block SSH, WebSocket, and sometimes HTTPS\n98: - **No budget** for cloud compute\n99: - **IT departments** that update software once per year, if that\n100: - **Exam boards** that mandate specific technologies (WJEC mandates PHP+MySQL)\n101: - **Air-gapped classrooms** where internet access is deliberately removed\n102: \n103: Every cloud-based solution fails at least one of these constraints. LAMPForge\n104: is designed to fail none of them.\n105: \n106: ---\n107: \n108: ## 2. What Is a PDE?\n109: \n110: A **PDE (Personal Development Environment)** is a self-contained workspace\n111: that gives a developer (or student) everything they need to write, run, test,\n112: and debug code. Think of it as a portable office that travels with you.\n113: \n114: Traditionally, a PDE means:\n115: - A **code editor** (VS Code, Vim, etc.)\n116: - A **runtime** (Node.js, PHP, Python, etc.)\n117: - A **database** (MySQL, PostgreSQL, SQLite, etc.)\n118: - A **web server** (Apache, Nginx, Caddy, etc.)\n119: - A **terminal** (Bash, PowerShell, etc.)\n120: \n121: LAMPForge adds:\n122: - An **AI assistant** (local inference, no cloud required)\n123: - A **curriculum engine** (lessons, evidence capture, rubrics)\n124: - A **FinOps governor** (cost limits that cannot be overridden)\n125: - A **protocol** (.forge files that declaratively describe all of the above)\n126: \n127: The key difference between a PDE and an IDE is that a PDE includes the\n128: runtime. VS Code is an IDE. VS Code + Docker + MySQL + PHP is a PDE.\n129: LAMPForge bundles all of this into a single portable unit.\n130: \n131: ---\n132: \n133: ## 3. What \"Sovereign\" Means\n134: \n135: In cloud computing, **sovereignty** means you control where your data lives\n136: and what software runs. It is the opposite of vendor lock-in.\n137: \n138: For LAMPForge, sovereign means:\n139: \n140: 1. **No cloud dependency.** The PDE works with zero internet access.\n141: 2. **No admin rights.** Everything runs in the user's own directory.\n142: 3. **No telemetry.** We disable all browser tracking and phoning home.\n143: 4. **No vendor lock-in.** The .forge protocol is an open specification.\n144: 5. **No cost.** Local inference, local compute, local storage.\n145: 6. **No Group Policy control.** We extract Edge to user-space where school\n146:    IT policies cannot reach it. The system-installed browser is the LAST\n147:    resort, not the first.\n148: 7. **You control the browser.** We extract Edge to user-space and pre-\n149:    configure every flag. We maintain our own \"supply chain\" of browser\n150:    configuration.\n151: \n152: This is analogous to how a government might demand \"sovereign cloud\" -- their\n153: data never leaves their jurisdiction. For a school, sovereign means: student\n154: data never leaves the school network, AND school IT cannot prevent the student\n155: from using the tools they need.\n156: \n157: ### Why User-Space, Not System-Level\n158: \n159: On every managed Windows machine in every school, the IT department deploys\n160: **Group Policy Objects (GPOs)**. GPOs control the system-installed browser:\n161: \n162: ```\n163: What IT can do to system-installed Edge:\n164: ├── Disable chrome://flags entries (WebGPU, WebNN, WASM)\n165: ├── Force-install monitoring extensions\n166: ├── Strip unrecognised command-line switches\n167: ├── Override homepage and new tab page\n168: ├── Block URLs via content filtering\n169: ├── Disable developer tools\n170: ├── Force sync to a managed account\n171: ├── Disable WebAssembly entirely\n172: ```\n173: \n174: GPOs target browser binaries at **system paths**:\n175: - `C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Microsoft\\Edge\\` -- GP-controlled\n176: - `C:\\Program Files\\Google\\Chrome\\` -- GP-controlled\n177: \n178: GPOs do NOT target user-space paths:\n179: - `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\LAMPForge\\edge-portable\\` -- sovereign\n180: - `D:\\USB\\LAMPForge\\edge-portable\\` -- sovereign\n181: \n182: The portable Edge binary is the **same executable**. But because it lives\n183: outside the system-registered path, Group Policy cannot find it. The binary\n184: does not check \"am I the system Edge?\" -- it runs with whatever flags the\n185: launcher provides.\n186: \n187: This is why `bootstrap.ps1` extracts Edge to user-space rather than using\n188: the system-installed copy. The system copy is the LAST RESORT -- used only\n189: when no portable or user-space binary exists, with the understanding that\n190: GP may interfere with flags.\n191: \n192: ### The Sovereign Browser Supply Chain\n193: \n194: We maintain a parallel supply chain for Microsoft Edge:\n195: \n196: ```\n197: Microsoft ships Edge Enterprise MSI\n198:         |\n199:         v\n200: bootstrap.ps1 extracts it to user-space (no admin)\n201:         |\n202:         v\n203: edge-preferences.json injects our flags (WebGPU, WebNN, WASM, etc.)\n204:         |\n205:         v\n206: Repackage-PDE.ps1 creates a distributable ZIP\n207:         |\n208:         v\n209: Teacher puts ZIP on USB stick or network share\n210:         |\n211:         v\n212: Student clicks Launch-LAMPForge.cmd -> full PDE with AI, no install\n213:         |\n214:         v\n215: Group Policy cannot touch it. Sovereign.\n216: ```\n217: \n218: This is NOT a fork of Edge. We use the exact same binary. We just control\n219: where it lives and how it is configured. Think of it as a \"golden image\"\n220: of browser settings, deployed outside the reach of institutional IT policy.\n221: \n222: ### Browser Detection Priority\n223: \n224: The launcher (`Launch-LAMPForge.cmd`) detects browsers in sovereign-first\n225: order:\n226: \n227: ```\n228: Priority 1: Portable Edge (extracted by bootstrap.ps1)\n229:             --> Fully sovereign. GP cannot touch it.\n230: \n231: Priority 2: User-space per-user installs (%LOCALAPPDATA%)\n232:             --> Mostly sovereign. Most GP targets system paths only.\n233: \n234: Priority 3: System-installed browsers (LAST RESORT)\n235:             --> GP-controlled. Flags may be overridden. Use only if\n236:                 nothing else is available.\n237: ```\n238: \n239: ---\n240: \n241: ## 4. The Portable Edge Browser: Our Kasm\n242: \n243: ### What Kasm Does\n244: \n245: Kasm Workspaces (https://kasmweb.com) is a container streaming platform. It\n246: runs a full Linux desktop inside a Docker container and streams the pixels to\n247: your browser via VNC/WebRTC. Schools love it because:\n248: \n249: - Students get a consistent environment\n250: - Nothing is installed on the local machine\n251: - The admin controls exactly what software is available\n252: - Sessions are isolated and disposable\n253: \n254: But Kasm requires:\n255: - A Linux server with Docker\n256: - 4GB RAM per concurrent user\n257: - A fast network connection\n258: - Someone to maintain the server\n259: \n260: ### What We Do Instead\n261: \n262: We achieve the same \"out of the box, pre-configured\" experience but:\n263: \n264: - **No server.** The browser IS the server.\n265: - **No streaming.** The code runs locally in WebAssembly.\n266: - **No per-user RAM cost.** Each student uses their own machine's resources.\n267: - **No network required.** Works offline after first launch.\n268: \n269: Our portable Edge with pre-injected flags IS our Kasm image. The flags we\n270: enable:\n271: \n272: | Flag | Purpose |\n273: |------|---------|\n274: | `--enable-unsafe-webgpu` | GPU-accelerated rendering for the editor |\n275: | `--enable-features=WebMachineLearningNeuralNetwork` | WebNN for local AI inference |\n276: | `--enable-features=WebAssemblyBaseline,WebAssemblyTiering` | Fast WASM for PHP-WASM and ONNX |\n277: | `--enable-features=SharedArrayBuffer` | Multi-threaded WASM workloads |\n278: | `--enable-features=IsolatedWebApps` | Future IWA distribution |\n279: | `--disable-background-networking` | Sovereignty: no phone-home |\n280: | `--app=http://localhost:5173` | Launches directly into the PDE, no browser chrome |\n281: \n282: When the student launches `launch-pde.cmd`, they do not see a browser. They\n283: see the LAMPForge PDE. Full screen. No URL bar. No tabs. No bookmarks. Just\n284: the editor, the terminal, the database workbench, and the AI assistant. It\n285: looks and feels like a native application.\n286: \n287: ---\n288: \n289: ## 5. What We Have Built So Far\n290: \n291: ### The Protocol (.forge)\n292: \n293: A declarative YAML format that describes an entire development environment:\n294: \n295: ```yaml\n296: protocol: forge/1.0\n297: intent: \"A school library management system\"\n298: runtime:\n299:   target: local\n300:   stack: lamp\n301:   components:\n302:     database: { engine: mysql, version: \"8.0\" }\n303:     scripting: { language: php, version: \"8.3\" }\n304: finops:\n305:   budget: { max_monthly_cloud: 0.00 }\n306:   inference: { prefer: local, allowed_providers: [onnx-webnn, foundry-local] }\n307: ```\n308: \n309: This single file drives everything: what software to install, what AI models\n310: to use, what budget limits to enforce, how to capture evidence for exam\n311: boards.\n312: \n313: ### The SDK (sdk/)\n314: \n315: TypeScript libraries that parse, validate, and generate from .forge files:\n316: \n317: - **forge-protocol.ts** - Zod schemas for the full .forge format\n318: - **forge-ai.ts** - Multi-stage AI inference cascade (ONNX -> Foundry Local\n319:   -> Groq -> Cerebras)\n320: - **forge-codegen.ts** - Code generation from blueprints\n321: - **forge-evidence.ts** - Evidence capture for exam boards\n322: - **forge-finops.ts** - FinOps ledger and budget enforcement\n323: \n324: ### The PDE (src/)\n325: \n326: A React application that provides:\n327: \n328: - **PDEPage** - The main development environment with panels for code,\n329:   terminal, database, AI chat\n330: - **CodeOSSFrame** - 3-tier IDE detection (OpenVSCode -> Code-OSS -> WebContainers)\n331: - **WorkbenchPage** - Standalone SQL workbench\n332: - **CanvasPage** - Visual node-based pipeline editor\n333: - **WizardPage** - Guided .forge file creation\n334: - **BroadcastChannel** - Panel undocking to separate windows\n335: \n336: ### The Runtime (runtime/)\n337: \n338: - **Supervisor API** - REST API specification for the native runtime\n339:   (MySQL, PHP, Caddy as user-space processes)\n340: - **Manifest schema** - Version compatibility and health checks\n341: - **Registry** - Component version catalogue\n342: - **Launchers** - Windows (bootstrap.ps1, launch-pde.cmd) and Linux\n343:   (launch-pde.sh) scripts\n344: \n345: ### The Curriculum (curriculum/)\n346: \n347: 44 lesson files across 6 modules covering terminal foundations, Bash, PowerShell,\n348: real-world automation, SDTP internals, and frontend styling. Each lesson is a\n349: .forge file with steps, evidence rubrics, and FinOps budgets.\n350: \n351: ### The AI Pipeline\n352: \n353: - **Olive config** - INT4 quantised ONNX model for route classification\n354: - **4-provider cascade** - ONNX (browser) -> Foundry Local -> Groq -> Cerebras\n355: - **Constitutional FinOps** - Budget enforcement wrapping every inference call\n356: \n357: ---\n358: \n359: ## 6. Hyperscalability: Why This Scales to Millions\n360: \n361: ### The Core Insight\n362: \n363: Traditional cloud-based dev environments have a **linear cost curve**: more\n364: students = more servers = more money. 1,000 students on Codespaces at\n365: $0.18/hour for 3 hours/week costs $540/week. 100,000 students costs\n366: $54,000/week.\n367: \n368: LAMPForge has a **zero marginal cost curve**: more students = zero additional\n369: infrastructure. The compute happens on the student's own machine. The AI\n370: inference happens in their browser. The storage is on their local filesystem.\n371: \n372: ```\n373: Traditional Cloud PDE:           LAMPForge Sovereign PDE:\n374: \n375: Cost                             Cost\n376:   |     /                          |  _______________\n377:   |    /                           | |\n378:   |   /                            | |\n379:   |  /                             | |\n380:   | /                              | |\n381:   |/                               |/\n382:   +---------> Users                +---------> Users\n383: \n384:   Linear scaling                   Flat cost (your CDN bill for the PWA)\n385: ```\n386: \n387: ### Why This Is Genuinely Hyperscalable\n388: \n389: 1. **The PWA is a static asset.** Once the student's browser has cached\n390:    the service worker and application shell, it never contacts your server\n391:    again. You could serve 10 million students from a single Cloudflare\n392:    Pages deployment (free tier).\n393: \n394: 2. **The AI model is shipped with the app.** The INT4 ONNX model for route\n395:    classification is ~50MB. It downloads once and caches via the service\n396:    worker. Every subsequent inference call is local. Zero server cost.\n397: \n398: 3. **The runtime is the student's machine.** MySQL, PHP, and Caddy run as\n399:    user-space processes on Windows. On browser-native mode, PHP-WASM and\n400:    wa-sqlite run in WebAssembly. Either way, no server is needed.\n401: \n402: 4. **The curriculum is static YAML.** Lesson files are `.forge` YAML served\n403:    as static assets. They can be CDN-cached indefinitely.\n404: \n405: 5. **Evidence is stored locally.** Student work, screenshots, and assessment\n406:    data live on their machine or in the browser's OPFS (Origin Private File\n407:    System). Export is explicit, not continuous.\n408: \n409: ### What \"Hyperscale\" Actually Means Here\n410: \n411: - **1 student** = USB stick, launch-pde.cmd, everything local\n412: - **30 students** = Teacher shares ZIP on school network\n413: - **1,000 students** = School intranet serves the PWA + runtime bundles\n414: - **100,000 students** = CDN serves the PWA, schools cache locally\n415: - **1 million students** = Same CDN, same static files, zero scaling concern\n416: \n417: The bottleneck shifts from \"how many servers do we need\" to \"how do we\n418: distribute the initial download.\" USB sticks, network shares, and CDNs all\n419: solve this trivially.\n420: \n421: ---\n422: \n423: ## 7. Portability: USB Sticks to Cloud\n424: \n425: ### The 4-Tier Deployment Hierarchy\n426: \n427: LAMPForge is designed to work across four deployment contexts, from most\n428: capable to most constrained:\n429: \n430: ```\n431: Tier 1: GitHub Codespaces / Cloud\n432: ├── Full Linux container\n433: ├── OpenVSCode Server\n434: ├── Real MySQL, PHP, Apache/Caddy\n435: ├── Cloud AI inference\n436: └── Internet required\n437: \n438: Tier 2: Docker / devcontainer\n439: ├── Local container\n440: ├── OpenVSCode Server\n441: ├── Real MySQL, PHP, Caddy\n442: ├── Foundry Local AI\n443: └── Docker required, no internet after pull\n444: \n445: Tier 3: Native runtime (USB / network share)\n446: ├── Portable Edge browser (user-space)\n447: ├── MySQL, PHP, Caddy as user-space processes\n448: ├── Foundry Local or ONNX browser inference\n449: ├── No admin rights, no Docker, no internet\n450: └── Windows-only (for now)\n451: \n452: Tier 4: Browser-Native (zero install)\n453: ├── Portable Edge or any Chromium browser\n454: ├── PHP-WASM + wa-sqlite (WebAssembly)\n455: ├── ONNX Runtime Web (browser AI)\n456: ├── Service Worker (offline)\n457: └── Works on any device with a modern browser\n458: ```\n459: \n460: ### What Makes It Portable\n461: \n462: The same `.forge` file works across all four tiers. The PDE reads the file,\n463: detects what tier it is running in, and adapts:\n464: \n465: ```\n466: .forge file says: runtime.stack: lamp\n467:                  runtime.components.database.engine: mysql\n468: \n469: Tier 1/2: Start real MySQL container\n470: Tier 3:   Start MySQL.exe from bundles/\n471: Tier 4:   Start wa-sqlite in WebAssembly\n472: ```\n473: \n474: The student does not know or care which tier they are on. They write PHP, they\n475: query a database, they see results. The `.forge` protocol abstracts the\n476: deployment entirely.\n477: \n478: ### The Portable Edge Package\n479: \n480: For Tier 3 and 4, the distribution looks like this:\n481: \n482: ```\n483: LAMPForge-PDE-Portable/\n484: ├── edge-portable/               # Extracted Edge (no admin needed)\n485: │   └── Microsoft/Edge/Application/msedge.exe\n486: ├── user-data/                   # Browser profile (pre-configured)\n487: │   └── Default/Preferences      # WebGPU/WebNN/WASM flags baked in\n488: ├── bundles/                     # Runtime components (Tier 3 only)\n489: │   ├── mysql-8.0-win-x64/\n490: │   ├── php-8.3-win-x64/\n491: │   └── caddy-2.9-win-x64/\n492: ├── dist/                        # Built PWA (the actual application)\n493: ├── models/                      # ONNX models for local AI\n494: ├── curriculum/                  # .forge lesson files\n495: ├── state/                       # Mutable state (DB data, logs, ledger)\n496: ├── launch-pde.cmd               # Single-click launcher\n497: ├── Launch-PDE.ps1               # PowerShell launcher (advanced)\n498: ├── Repackage-PDE.ps1            # Create distribution ZIPs\n499: └── manifest.json                # Distribution metadata\n500: ```\n501: \n502: This entire folder can be:\n503: - Copied to a USB stick and handed to students\n504: - Put on a network share and accessed via UNC path\n505: - Zipped and distributed via email/LMS\n506: - Deployed by SCCM/Intune to managed devices (still no admin at launch)\n507: \n508: ---\n509: \n510: ## 8. Mesh: Peer-to-Peer Without Servers\n511: \n512: ### What a Mesh Is\n513: \n514: A **mesh network** is a network where every node connects to every other node\n515: directly, with no central server. The internet itself started as a mesh (ARPANET,\n516: 1969). Modern examples include BitTorrent, Bitcoin, and WebRTC video calls.\n517: \n518: In the browser, **WebRTC** (Web Real-Time Communication, standardised 2017)\n519: enables peer-to-peer connections between browsers. Two browsers can exchange\n520: data directly without any server relay, after an initial \"signalling\" step\n521: where they exchange connection details.\n522: \n523: ### What We Already Have: BroadcastChannel\n524: \n525: LAMPForge already uses the **BroadcastChannel API** for communication between\n526: browser windows. When a student undocks a panel (e.g., the SQL Workbench)\n527: into a separate window, BroadcastChannel synchronises state between the main\n528: PDE window and the undocked panel.\n529: \n530: ```javascript\n531: // From the current codebase:\n532: const channel = new BroadcastChannel('lampforge-pde');\n533: channel.postMessage({ type: 'panel:undock', panel: 'sql-workbench', state: {...} });\n534: ```\n535: \n536: BroadcastChannel works between tabs/windows of the **same origin** on the\n537: **same machine**. It is the same-machine mesh.\n538: \n539: ### Extending to Cross-Machine Mesh via WebRTC\n540: \n541: The same pattern extends to cross-machine communication:\n542: \n543: ```\n544: Same machine (current):\n545:   Tab A  <-- BroadcastChannel -->  Tab B\n546: \n547: Same classroom (future - WebRTC):\n548:   Student A's PDE  <-- WebRTC DataChannel -->  Student B's PDE\n549: \n550: Same school (future - WebRTC + relay):\n551:   Classroom A  <-- WebRTC with TURN relay -->  Classroom B\n552: ```\n553: \n554: ### How WebRTC Mesh Would Work for LAMPForge\n555: \n556: **Step 1: Signalling** (the only part needing a server)\n557: \n558: Two browsers cannot find each other without help. They need to exchange\n559: \"Session Description Protocol\" (SDP) offers. This requires a signalling\n560: server. Options:\n561: \n562: - **Minimal:** A simple WebSocket service on the school intranet\n563: - **Zero-server:** Copy-paste SDP strings (ugly but works air-gapped)\n564: - **Classroom router:** The teacher's PDE acts as a signalling hub\n565: - **Future:** The LAMPForge supervisor (already at localhost:9000) could\n566:   expose a signalling endpoint on the local network\n567: \n568: **Step 2: Direct Connection**\n569: \n570: Once signalled, browsers connect directly via WebRTC DataChannel.\n571: Messages are encrypted (DTLS) and traverse NATs using ICE/STUN.\n572: \n573: **Step 3: State Synchronisation**\n574: \n575: With a DataChannel established, we can synchronise:\n576: \n577: - **File system operations** - CRDTs (Conflict-free Replicated Data Types)\n578:   for collaborative editing\n579: - **Database state** - SQL operation log replication\n580: - **Cursor positions** - For multiplayer editing\n581: - **AI inference results** - Share model outputs without re-running\n582: - **Evidence collection** - Teacher observes student progress in real-time\n583: \n584: ### The Mesh Topology\n585: \n586: In a classroom of 30 students, a full mesh (every student connected to every\n587: other) requires 435 connections (n*(n-1)/2). This is too many. Instead, we use\n588: a **star-mesh hybrid**:\n589: \n590: ```\n591:                     Teacher PDE\n592:                    /    |    \\\n593:                   /     |     \\\n594:           Student A  Student B  Student C\n595:               |         |         |\n596:          Student D  Student E  Student F\n597: \n598: - Teacher connects to all students (star)\n599: - Students connect to their pair/group (partial mesh)\n600: - Total connections: 30 (teacher) + ~15 (pairs) = 45\n601: ```\n602: \n603: This is the same topology that Kasm uses for classroom management, but\n604: without any server infrastructure. The teacher's browser IS the server.\n605: \n606: ---\n607: \n608: ## 9. Multiplayer: Real-Time Collaboration\n609: \n610: ### What \"Multiplayer\" Means for a PDE\n611: \n612: Gaming taught us that \"multiplayer\" means shared state and real-time\n613: interaction. Applied to a PDE:\n614: \n615: | Gaming Concept | PDE Equivalent |\n616: |----------------|----------------|\n617: | Shared world | Shared codebase / database |\n618: | Player position | Cursor position |\n619: | Player actions | Code edits, terminal commands |\n620: | Game state | Application state, database rows |\n621: | Spectator mode | Teacher observing student work |\n622: | Replay | Evidence capture / session recording |\n623: \n624: ### Collaboration Patterns\n625: \n626: **Pattern 1: Pair Programming (2 students, 1 codebase)**\n627: \n628: Both students see the same code. Both can edit. Cursors are colour-coded.\n629: This is what VS Code Live Share does, but ours works offline via WebRTC.\n630: \n631: Implementation: OT (Operational Transform) or CRDT for text, applied over\n632: WebRTC DataChannel.\n633: \n634: **Pattern 2: Teacher Observation (1 teacher, 30 students)**\n635: \n636: Teacher sees a dashboard of all 30 students' screens. Can drill into any\n637: student to see their code, their terminal output, their SQL queries, and\n638: their AI interactions. No screen-sharing software needed. The PDE sends\n639: structured data (not pixels) over WebRTC.\n640: \n641: This is strictly better than Kasm's approach (streaming pixels) because:\n642: - It uses ~1% of the bandwidth (sending JSON, not video frames)\n643: - The teacher can filter by \"show me all students who have syntax errors\"\n644: - Evidence capture is automatic and structured, not just screenshots\n645: \n646: **Pattern 3: Code Review (async, no real-time)**\n647: \n648: Student submits their .forge project. Teacher reviews it later. Evidence is\n649: exported as a structured PDF with curriculum references, code snapshots, and\n650: AI interaction logs.\n651: \n652: This pattern requires no mesh or real-time infrastructure at all. It is\n653: already partially built (forge-evidence.ts).\n654: \n655: **Pattern 4: Shared Database (group project)**\n656: \n657: Multiple students connect to the same MySQL instance. Each sees the same\n658: tables. SQL operations are applied in order. This is just normal database\n659: access over the local network -- no special infrastructure.\n660: \n661: For browser-native mode (Tier 4), this requires CRDT-based SQLite replication.\n662: Projects like cr-sqlite (https://vlcn.io) make this possible: SQLite with\n663: CRDT extensions that merge concurrent edits without conflicts.\n664: \n665: ### The Multiplayer Stack\n666: \n667: ```\n668: Layer 4: Application\n669: ├── Collaborative editor (CRDT-based text)\n670: ├── Shared terminal (operation log)\n671: ├── Shared database (CRDT-SQLite or networked MySQL)\n672: └── Teacher dashboard (observation + evidence)\n673: \n674: Layer 3: Synchronisation\n675: ├── CRDT engine (Yjs or Automerge)\n676: ├── Operation log (ordered events)\n677: └── Snapshot + delta sync\n678: \n679: Layer 2: Transport\n680: ├── WebRTC DataChannel (peer-to-peer)\n681: ├── BroadcastChannel (same-machine fallback)\n682: └── WebSocket (server-assisted fallback)\n683: \n684: Layer 1: Signalling\n685: ├── Teacher PDE as signalling hub\n686: ├── School intranet WebSocket\n687: └── Manual SDP exchange (air-gapped)\n688: ```\n689: \n690: ---\n691: \n692: ## 10. CPU Inference: AI Without a GPU\n693: \n694: ### Why CPU Matters\n695: \n696: Most school computers do not have discrete GPUs. They have Intel integrated\n697: graphics or, at best, an AMD APU. Cloud inference costs money. Therefore,\n698: LAMPForge must run AI on the CPU.\n699: \n700: ### What We Have: The Olive Pipeline\n701: \n702: Microsoft Olive is a model optimisation framework. We have an Olive\n703: configuration (`.olive-cache/default_workflow/olive_config.json`) that:\n704: \n705: 1. Takes a HuggingFace model (`arch-router-raw-local`)\n706: 2. Converts it to ONNX format (Open Neural Network Exchange)\n707: 3. Applies peephole optimisation (removes redundant operations)\n708: 4. Applies transformer optimisation\n709: 5. Quantises to INT4 (reduces model size by 4x, speeds up CPU inference)\n710: 6. Outputs a model that runs on `CPUExecutionProvider` only\n711: \n712: The result is a ~50MB model that can classify user intent in <1 second on a\n713: typical school laptop CPU.\n714: \n715: ### The Inference Cascade\n716: \n717: Our AI pipeline (`sdk/forge-ai.ts`) implements a 4-stage fallback:\n718: \n719: ```\n720: Stage 1: ONNX Runtime Web (browser)\n721: ├── Runs in the browser via WebAssembly\n722: ├── Uses the INT4 quantised model from Olive\n723: ├── Zero network, zero cost, zero latency (beyond compute)\n724: ├── WebNN backend if available (uses DirectML on Windows)\n725: ├── WASM backend as fallback (pure CPU)\n726: └── 8-second timeout, then fall through\n727: \n728: Stage 2: Foundry Local (localhost)\n729: ├── Microsoft's local inference runtime\n730: ├── Runs as a system service or user-space process\n731: ├── Much faster than browser WASM\n732: ├── Uses CPU, NPU, or GPU depending on hardware\n733: └── Requires Foundry to be installed\n734: \n735: Stage 3: Groq Cloud (remote)\n736: ├── Groq's ultra-fast inference API\n737: ├── Requires internet and API key\n738: ├── Subject to FinOps budget limits\n739: └── Used only when local options fail\n740: \n741: Stage 4: Cerebras Cloud (remote)\n742: ├── Cerebras' inference API\n743: ├── Same constraints as Groq\n744: └── Final fallback\n745: ```\n746: \n747: Each stage is wrapped by the FinOps Guard, which checks the session budget\n748: before allowing any inference call. If the budget is $0.00 (as in the\n749: air-gapped example), Stages 3 and 4 are never reached.\n750: \n751: ### WebNN: The CPU/NPU/GPU Abstraction\n752: \n753: **WebNN** (Web Neural Network API) is a W3C specification (Candidate\n754: Recommendation as of 2024) that provides a hardware abstraction layer for\n755: neural network inference in the browser:\n756: \n757: ```\n758: Your AI model (ONNX)\n759:        |\n760:        v\n761:   WebNN API (browser)\n762:        |\n763:        +--> DirectML (Windows) --> GPU or NPU or CPU\n764:        |\n765:        +--> CoreML (macOS) --> Apple Neural Engine or GPU or CPU\n766:        |\n767:        +--> XNNPACK (Linux) --> CPU\n768:        |\n769:        +--> WASM (fallback) --> CPU via WebAssembly\n770: ```\n771: \n772: When we enable `--enable-features=WebMachineLearningNeuralNetwork` in our\n773: portable Edge, we unlock WebNN. The ONNX Runtime Web library automatically\n774: selects the best backend:\n775: \n776: 1. If the machine has a discrete GPU -> DirectML uses the GPU\n777: 2. If the machine has an NPU (Intel Meteor Lake, Qualcomm Snapdragon) -> DirectML uses the NPU\n778: 3. If neither -> WASM backend runs on the CPU\n779: \n780: This is why the portable Edge flags matter. Without them, WebNN is not\n781: available, and inference falls back to the slower WASM-only path.\n782: \n783: ### CPU Performance: Is It Good Enough?\n784: \n785: For our use case, yes:\n786: \n787: - **Route classification** (Stage 1): The Olive-optimised INT4 model\n788:   classifies intent in 200-800ms on a typical i5 laptop CPU. This is fast\n789:   enough for a submit button workflow (not real-time streaming).\n790: \n791: - **Blueprint generation** (Stage 2): For a 500-token response from Foundry\n792:   Local using a 7B parameter model (e.g., Phi-3-mini), expect 2-5 seconds\n793:   on a modern CPU. Again, acceptable for a non-interactive generation step.\n794: \n795: - **In-browser ONNX**: The WASM execution provider processes ~50-200 tokens\n796:   per second on a modern CPU for small models (<1B params). The WebNN\n797:   provider on the same hardware can be 2-5x faster because it uses optimised\n798:   CPU instructions (AVX512, AVX-VNNI) directly.\n799: \n800: For comparison, Kasm streams video at 30fps, which requires far more CPU than\n801: our structured data approach.\n802: \n803: ---\n804: \n805: ## 11. The Full Stack Diagram\n806: \n807: ```\n808: ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n809: │                        Student's Machine                             │\n810: │                                                                      │\n811: │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │\n812: │  │              Portable Edge (User-Space, No Admin)              │  │\n813: │  │  Flags: WebGPU | WebNN | WASM | SharedArrayBuffer | IWA       │  │\n814: │  │                                                                │  │\n815: │  │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │  │\n816: │  │  │                   LAMPForge PWA                         │    │  │\n817: │  │  │                                                        │    │  │\n818: │  │  │  ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ │    │  │\n819: │  │  │  │  Code    │ │ Terminal │ │   SQL    │ │   AI    │  │    │  │\n820: │  │  │  │  Editor  │ │          │ │Workbench │ │  Chat   │  │    │  │\n821: │  │  │  └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ └────┬─────┘ │    │  │\n822: │  │  │       │            │            │            │        │    │  │\n823: │  │  │  ┌────▼────────────▼────────────▼────────────▼────┐   │    │  │\n824: │  │  │  │              .forge Protocol Engine             │   │    │  │\n825: │  │  │  │  (parse, validate, compile, govern)             │   │    │  │\n826: │  │  │  └────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┘   │    │  │\n827: │  │  │                       │                                │    │  │\n828: │  │  │  ┌────────────────────▼────────────────────────────┐   │    │  │\n829: │  │  │  │              AI Inference Cascade                │   │    │  │\n830: │  │  │  │  ONNX(browser) -> Foundry -> Groq -> Cerebras   │   │    │  │\n831: │  │  │  │                  [FinOps Guard]                  │   │    │  │\n832: │  │  │  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │    │  │\n833: │  │  │                                                        │    │  │\n834: │  │  │  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │    │  │\n835: │  │  │  │              Service Worker (Offline)            │   │    │  │\n836: │  │  │  │  Cache: App Shell | Models | Curriculum | Fonts │   │    │  │\n837: │  │  │  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │    │  │\n838: │  │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │  │\n839: │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │\n840: │                                                                      │\n841: │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │\n842: │  │              Native Runtime (Tier 3, Optional)                 │  │\n843: │  │                                                                │  │\n844: │  │  Supervisor (localhost:9000)                                   │  │\n845: │  │  ├── MySQL 8.0 (user-space, 127.0.0.1:3306)                  │  │\n846: │  │  ├── PHP 8.3 CGI (user-space)                                 │  │\n847: │  │  ├── Caddy 2.9 (user-space, 127.0.0.1:8080)                  │  │\n848: │  │  └── phpMyAdmin 5.2                                           │  │\n849: │  │                                                                │  │\n850: │  │  OR (Tier 4, Browser-Native):                                 │  │\n851: │  │  ├── PHP-WASM (WebAssembly)                                   │  │\n852: │  │  ├── wa-sqlite (WebAssembly + OPFS)                           │  │\n853: │  │  └── Service Worker (request routing)                         │  │\n854: │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │\n855: │                                                                      │\n856: │  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │\n857: │  │              Future: Mesh Layer                                │  │\n858: │  │                                                                │  │\n859: │  │  ├── BroadcastChannel (same machine - CURRENT)                │  │\n860: │  │  ├── WebRTC DataChannel (classroom peers - FUTURE)            │  │\n861: │  │  ├── CRDT Sync Engine (Yjs/Automerge - FUTURE)                │  │\n862: │  │  └── Teacher Dashboard (observation - FUTURE)                 │  │\n863: │  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘  │\n864: └──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n865: ```\n866: \n867: ---\n868: \n869: ## 12. Competitive Landscape\n870: \n871: | Product | Requires Server | Requires Internet | Requires Admin | Requires Budget | Local AI | Mesh/Multiplayer |\n872: |---------|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|\n873: | **GitHub Codespaces** | Yes (cloud) | Yes | No | Yes ($0.18/hr) | No | No |\n874: | **Replit** | Yes (cloud) | Yes | No | Yes (freemium) | No | Yes (collab) |\n875: | **Kasm Workspaces** | Yes (Linux) | Partial | Yes (Docker) | Yes (server) | No | No |\n876: | **StackBlitz** | No | Partial | No | Free | No | No |\n877: | **WordPress Playground** | No | No | No | Free | No | No |\n878: | **LAMPForge PDE** | No | No | No | Free | Yes | Future |\n879: \n880: LAMPForge is the only option that simultaneously satisfies:\n881: - No server, no internet, no admin, no cost\n882: - Full LAMP stack (PHP + MySQL, not just Node.js)\n883: - Local AI inference\n884: - Exam board curriculum integration\n885: - FinOps governance\n886: \n887: ---\n888: \n889: ## 13. What Comes Next\n890: \n891: ### Near-Term (Current Work)\n892: \n893: - Completing the portable Edge bootstrapper for Tier 3 deployment\n894: - Olive pipeline refinements for smaller/faster models\n895: - WebNN backend testing across Intel/AMD/Qualcomm CPUs\n896: \n897: ### Medium-Term\n898: \n899: - WebRTC mesh signalling via the supervisor (localhost:9000)\n900: - Teacher dashboard with student observation\n901: - CRDT-based collaborative editing\n902: - Evidence streaming to teacher PDE\n903: \n904: ### Long-Term\n905: \n906: - IWA (Isolated Web App) distribution: The PDE distributed as a signed\n907:   web bundle, installed like a native app, with its own origin\n908: - NPU-accelerated inference on Intel Meteor Lake and Qualcomm Snapdragon X\n909:   laptops (these are increasingly common in school refreshes)\n910: - Cross-school mesh: schools federating their PDEs for inter-school\n911:   collaboration, with each school maintaining sovereignty\n912: \n913: ### The End State\n914: \n915: A student clicks a single file. A complete development environment appears.\n916: It has an editor, a terminal, a database, an AI assistant, and a curriculum\n917: engine. It works offline. It works on locked-down school machines. It costs\n918: nothing. The teacher can observe and assess from their own PDE. Students can\n919: collaborate without any cloud infrastructure.\n920: \n921: This is the Kasm experience without the server. The Codespaces experience\n922: without the cloud. The VS Code experience without the installation.\n923: \n924: A truly sovereign, hyperscalable, portable, meshable, multiplayer PDE.\n\n(End of file - total 924 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
