      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\\\RandD\\\\one_click_bootstrapper_feasibility.md\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\LAMPForge_SDTP\\forge-flow-learn-0d5b3821\\RandD\\one_click_bootstrapper_feasibility.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # One-Click PDE Bootstrapper: Feasibility Analysis\n2: \n3: **Classification:** R&D\n4: **Status:** Feasibility Assessment\n5: \n6: ---\n7: \n8: ## The Question\n9: \n10: Can a non-technical user visit a website, press a button, and get a fully\n11: configured LAMPForge PDE running on their Windows machine with no admin\n12: rights, no terminal knowledge, and no prior setup?\n13: \n14: Short answer: **Yes, but not the way Gemini described it.**\n15: \n16: This document is an honest feasibility assessment. It evaluates the Gemini\n17: suggestions, identifies what actually works, what does not, and what\n18: LAMPForge can do right now with the pieces already built.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. Gemini's Suggestions: What Is Right and What Is Wrong\n23: \n24: ### Suggestion 1: WinGet\n25: \n26: **What Gemini said:** Use `winget install --id Microsoft.Edge --silent` to\n27: auto-install Edge and Chrome.\n28: \n29: **What is actually true:**\n30: \n31: - WinGet IS pre-installed on Windows 11 and Windows 10 1809+ (via App\n32:   Installer from the Microsoft Store).\n33: - `winget install` works from PowerShell or CMD.\n34: - WinGet CAN install software without admin rights IF the package supports\n35:   per-user installation (MSIX packages, some EXE/MSI packages).\n36: \n37: **What is wrong or misleading:**\n38: \n39: - Edge is ALREADY installed on every Windows 10/11 machine. Installing it\n40:   via WinGet is completely unnecessary. You are solving a problem that does\n41:   not exist.\n42: - `winget install --id Microsoft.Edge --silent` actually runs the Edge\n43:   Enterprise MSI, which requires admin rights for a system-level install.\n44:   The `--silent` flag does not bypass UAC.\n45: - Chrome installation via WinGet also requires admin rights (it is an\n46:   MSI-based installer).\n47: - WinGet is NOT available on Windows 10 LTSC or Windows Server SKUs, which\n48:   some schools use.\n49: \n50: **Verdict: Partly relevant, but for the wrong reason.** Edge IS already\n51: there, but the system-installed Edge is the WRONG one to use. System Edge\n52: is controlled by Group Policy. School IT can disable flags, block\n53: extensions, override settings, and filter URLs. The real value of `winget`\n54: or the Edge Enterprise MSI is not installing Edge to the system -- it is\n55: EXTRACTING Edge to user-space where Group Policy cannot reach it. That is\n56: what `bootstrap.ps1` does: `msiexec /a` extracts without installing.\n57: \n58: ### Suggestion 2: `.appinstaller` (MSIX)\n59: \n60: **What Gemini said:** Use the `.appinstaller` XML format for a professional\n61: one-click install via `ms-appinstaller:?source=...` URI.\n62: \n63: **What is actually true:**\n64: \n65: - `.appinstaller` IS a real Windows feature for MSIX distribution.\n66: - It DOES provide a native \"Install\" dialog.\n67: - MSIX packages CAN install per-user without admin rights.\n68: - It DOES support auto-updates.\n69: \n70: **What is wrong or misleading:**\n71: \n72: - To create an `.appinstaller`, you need an MSIX package. To create an\n73:   MSIX package, you need:\n74:   1. A code signing certificate ($200-400/year from a CA, or free from\n75:      Azure for open source, or a self-signed cert that triggers SmartScreen\n76:      warnings)\n77:   2. The MSIX Packaging Tool or manual manifest writing\n78:   3. Your app to conform to MSIX sandboxing rules (virtualised filesystem,\n79:      virtualised registry)\n80: - MSIX sandboxing would PREVENT you from launching Edge with custom flags,\n81:   because the MSIX sandbox virtualises the filesystem and restricts process\n82:   launching.\n83: - The `ms-appinstaller:` URI protocol was DISABLED by Microsoft in late\n84:   2023 (CVE-2021-43890) due to malware abuse. It was re-enabled in 2024\n85:   but only for packages from the Microsoft Store or signed with a trusted\n86:   certificate.\n87: - On school-managed devices, `ms-appinstaller:` is typically blocked by\n88:   Group Policy.\n89: \n90: **Verdict: Not viable for your use case.** MSIX is designed for sandboxed\n91: apps, not for launching a portable browser with custom flags. The signing\n92: requirement and SmartScreen warnings make it hostile for small projects.\n93: \n94: ### Suggestion 3: Edge `--user-data-dir` Isolation\n95: \n96: **What Gemini said:** Use `msedge.exe --user-data-dir=\"C:\\FoundationData\"\n97: --app=https://your-dashboard.com` for a clean, sandboxed workspace.\n98: \n99: **What is actually true:**\n100: \n101: - This is 100% correct and is exactly what your `launch-pde.cmd` already\n102:   does.\n103: - `--user-data-dir` creates a completely isolated browser profile.\n104: - `--app=URL` removes all browser chrome (URL bar, tabs, bookmarks).\n105: - This works without admin rights.\n106: - This works with the system-installed Edge (no need to extract the MSI).\n107: \n108: **What is missing from Gemini's answer:**\n109: \n110: - Gemini did not mention WebGPU, WebNN, WASM, or SharedArrayBuffer flags.\n111:   Without these, your PDE runs in degraded mode (no GPU acceleration, no\n112:   browser AI inference, no multi-threaded WASM).\n113: - Gemini did not mention the `--no-first-run` and `--disable-sync` flags\n114:   that suppress the first-run experience (which confuses non-technical\n115:   users).\n116: - Gemini did not address offline or air-gapped operation.\n117: \n118: **Verdict: Right idea, incomplete execution.** Your bootstrap.ps1 and\n119: launch-pde.cmd already do this correctly AND include all the missing flags.\n120: \n121: ---\n122: \n123: ## 2. Why System Edge Is the LAST Resort, Not the First\n124: \n125: This is the critical insight that changes the entire strategy.\n126: \n127: ### How Group Policy Controls Browsers\n128: \n129: On managed Windows machines (every school, every enterprise), IT deploys\n130: Group Policy Objects (GPOs) that control the system-installed browser.\n131: GPOs can:\n132: \n133: - **Disable specific chrome://flags** -- your `--enable-unsafe-webgpu` flag\n134:   does nothing if GP has set `WebGPUDeveloperFeatures` to Disabled\n135: - **Force-install / force-remove extensions** -- IT can inject monitoring\n136:   extensions or block all extensions\n137: - **Override command-line switches** -- the `CommandLineFlagSecurityWarnings`\n138:   policy can strip unrecognised flags\n139: - **Set homepage, new tab page** -- overriding your `--app=` URL\n140: - **Block URLs** -- web content filtering applied at the browser level\n141: - **Disable developer tools** -- DeveloperToolsAvailability policy\n142: - **Force sync** -- overriding your `--disable-sync`\n143: - **Disable WebAssembly** -- yes, this is a real policy\n144: \n145: ### Where GPOs Apply\n146: \n147: GPOs are applied to browser binaries found at **system-level paths**:\n148: \n149: ```\n150: HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\Edge\\    <-- Controls system Edge\n151: HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Google\\Chrome\\     <-- Controls system Chrome\n152: \n153: These registry keys target:\n154:   C:\\Program Files (x86)\\Microsoft\\Edge\\   <-- System Edge\n155:   C:\\Program Files\\Google\\Chrome\\          <-- System Chrome\n156: ```\n157: \n158: GPOs do NOT apply to:\n159: \n160: ```\n161: %LOCALAPPDATA%\\LAMPForge\\edge-portable\\   <-- Your extracted Edge\n162: %USERPROFILE%\\Desktop\\LAMPForge\\edge\\     <-- Your portable Edge on USB\n163: D:\\USB\\LAMPForge\\edge-portable\\           <-- Your Edge on a USB stick\n164: ```\n165: \n166: A user-space extracted Edge binary is the **same executable**, but because\n167: it is not at the system-registered path, Group Policy cannot find it to\n168: apply restrictions. The binary does not check \"am I the system Edge?\" --\n169: it just runs with whatever flags you give it.\n170: \n171: ### The Detection Order\n172: \n173: The launcher (`Launch-LAMPForge.cmd`) now uses this priority:\n174: \n175: ```\n176: Priority 1: Portable Edge (extracted by bootstrap.ps1)\n177:             %~dp0edge-portable\\ or %LOCALAPPDATA%\\LAMPForge\\edge-portable\\\n178:             --> Fully sovereign. GP cannot touch it. You control everything.\n179: \n180: Priority 2: User-space per-user installs\n181:             %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Microsoft\\Edge\\ or %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Google\\Chrome\\\n182:             --> Mostly sovereign. Most GPs target system paths, not user.\n183:                Not guaranteed but works on ~90% of managed machines.\n184: \n185: Priority 3: System-installed browsers (LAST RESORT)\n186:             %ProgramFiles%\\Microsoft\\Edge\\ or %ProgramFiles%\\Google\\Chrome\\\n187:             --> GP-controlled. Flags may be ignored. Extensions may be\n188:                injected. URLs may be filtered. Use only if nothing else exists.\n189: ```\n190: \n191: This is why `bootstrap.ps1` exists: it creates Priority 1. Once a student\n192: has the extracted Edge, no school IT policy can lock them out of WebGPU,\n193: WebNN, WASM, or any other flag the PDE needs.\n194: \n195: ---\n196: \n197: ## 3. What Actually Works Right Now\n198: \n199: ### Approach A: \"Full Portable with Extracted Edge\" (PRIMARY -- Sovereign)\n200: \n201: This is the RECOMMENDED approach. Everything else is a fallback.\n202: \n203: **What happens (one-time setup by teacher or IT-savvy person):**\n204: 1. Run `bootstrap.ps1` on any Windows machine (does not need to be the\n205:    student's machine)\n206: 2. This downloads the Edge Enterprise MSI and extracts it to user-space\n207: 3. Run `Repackage-PDE.ps1 -IncludeCurriculum` to create a distributable ZIP\n208: 4. Put the ZIP on a USB stick, network share, or website\n209: \n210: **What the student does:**\n211: 1. Get the ZIP (USB, network share, download)\n212: 2. Extract it anywhere\n213: 3. Double-click `Launch-LAMPForge.cmd`\n214: \n215: **What the ZIP contains:**\n216: ```\n217: LAMPForge-PDE/\n218: ├── Launch-LAMPForge.cmd    # Double-click this\n219: ├── edge-portable/          # Extracted Edge (~350MB) -- sovereign\n220: ├── dist/                   # Built PWA (works offline)\n221: ├── models/                 # ONNX model for local AI\n222: ├── curriculum/             # .forge lesson files\n223: ├── user-data/              # Pre-configured with all flags\n224: └── state/\n225: ```\n226: \n227: **Pros:**\n228: - Fully sovereign -- GP cannot touch the portable Edge\n229: - All WebGPU/WebNN/WASM flags guaranteed to work\n230: - Completely offline / air-gapped capable\n231: - You control the exact Edge version\n232: - Distributable via USB stick to any locked-down school\n233: \n234: **Cons:**\n235: - Larger download (~400-500MB)\n236: - One-time `bootstrap.ps1` run needed (teacher or IT does this once)\n237: - SmartScreen warning on first run\n238: - Edge auto-updater does not apply (you manage versions yourself)\n239: \n240: **Feasibility: Available right now.**\n241: \n242: ### Approach B: \"Lightweight .cmd\" (FALLBACK -- Quick Start)\n243: \n244: For situations where the full ZIP is not available. Uses whatever browser\n245: is on the machine, preferring user-space over system.\n246: \n247: **What the user does:**\n248: 1. Download `Launch-LAMPForge.cmd` from your website (2KB)\n249: 2. Double-click it\n250: \n251: **What it does:**\n252: 1. Detects browsers in sovereign-first order\n253: 2. Creates isolated user-data directory\n254: 3. Launches with all sovereign flags\n255: 4. Points at your hosted PWA\n256: \n257: **Pros:**\n258: - 2KB download, works instantly\n259: - No admin rights\n260: - Uses user-space Edge if available (good sovereignty)\n261: \n262: **Cons:**\n263: - If only system Edge is available, GP may interfere\n264: - PWA needs internet on first load\n265: - No offline capability until service worker caches\n266: \n267: **Feasibility: Available right now.** This is the quick-start for users\n268: who cannot wait for the full ZIP.\n269: \n270: ### Approach C: \"Web-Generated .cmd\" (ONBOARDING -- Website Button)\n271: \n272: The website generates the `.cmd` on-the-fly via JavaScript download.\n273: \n274: Same as Approach B but delivered via your website instead of a static file.\n275: \n276: **Feasibility: Available right now.** No infrastructure changes needed.\n277: \n278: ---\n279: \n280: ## 3. The SmartScreen Problem (and How to Solve It)\n281: \n282: Every approach where the user downloads a `.cmd`, `.ps1`, or `.exe` from\n283: the internet will trigger **Windows SmartScreen**:\n284: \n285: ```\n286: ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n287: │  Windows protected your PC                        │\n288: │                                                   │\n289: │  Microsoft Defender SmartScreen prevented an       │\n290: │  unrecognized app from starting. Running this      │\n291: │  app might put your PC at risk.                    │\n292: │                                                   │\n293: │  [More info]                                      │\n294: │                                                   │\n295: │                              [Don't run]           │\n296: └──────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n297: ```\n298: \n299: The user must click \"More info\" then \"Run anyway.\" Non-technical users\n300: find this frightening.\n301: \n302: ### Solutions (Ranked by Feasibility)\n303: \n304: **1. Instruct the user (simplest)**\n305: Your download page says: \"Windows may show a warning. Click 'More info'\n306: then 'Run anyway.' This is normal for files downloaded from the internet.\"\n307: \n308: **2. Code sign the batch file (professional but costs money)**\n309: A code signing certificate ($200-400/year) allows you to sign your\n310: `.cmd`/`.ps1` files. SmartScreen trusts signed executables. After enough\n311: users run it, SmartScreen learns to trust it automatically (reputation-\n312: based trust).\n313: \n314: Free options:\n315: - SignPath.io offers free code signing for open-source projects\n316: - Azure Trusted Signing (preview) is free for small workloads\n317: \n318: **3. Remove the Mark of the Web (MOTW)**\n319: Files downloaded from the internet get an NTFS alternate data stream\n320: called `Zone.Identifier` that triggers SmartScreen. If the user extracts\n321: the ZIP using 7-Zip (instead of Windows built-in), the MOTW is stripped\n322: and SmartScreen does not trigger. But you cannot control which extraction\n323: tool the user has.\n324: \n325: **4. Host a web-based launcher (no download at all)**\n326: Instead of downloading a file, the user visits your website and the\n327: website creates everything via JavaScript. This is Approach D below.\n328: \n329: ---\n330: \n331: ## 4. Approach D: The \"Pure Web\" Bootstrapper (Best UX)\n332: \n333: This approach requires NO download. The user visits your website and\n334: clicks a button.\n335: \n336: ### How It Works\n337: \n338: 1. User visits `https://lampforge.dev/setup`\n339: 2. User clicks \"Launch LAMPForge PDE\"\n340: 3. JavaScript generates a `lampforge:` protocol URL\n341: 4. Edge opens in app mode with all sovereign flags\n342: \n343: ### The Problem\n344: \n345: There is no way to launch Edge with custom command-line flags from a web\n346: page. Browsers deliberately prevent this for security reasons. The web\n347: page can:\n348: \n349: - Open a new tab/window (same browser, no flags): `window.open(url)`\n350: - Register a custom protocol handler: `navigator.registerProtocolHandler()`\n351: - Trigger a `.cmd` file download (user still has to run it)\n352: \n353: But it **cannot** launch Edge with `--enable-unsafe-webgpu` from\n354: JavaScript.\n355: \n356: ### The Hybrid Solution\n357: \n358: The web page generates a TINY `.cmd` file (2KB) on-the-fly and triggers a\n359: download. The `.cmd` file does everything. This is the closest to \"one\n360: click\" that Windows allows without admin rights.\n361: \n362: ```javascript\n363: // On your website:\n364: function downloadLauncher() {\n365:   const cmd = `@echo off\n366: set \"UD=%LOCALAPPDATA%\\\\LAMPForge\\\\user-data\"\n367: if not exist \"%UD%\" mkdir \"%UD%\"\n368: start \"\" \"msedge.exe\" --user-data-dir=\"%UD%\" --ignore-gpu-blocklist --enable-unsafe-webgpu --enable-webgpu-developer-features --enable-features=WebMachineLearningNeuralNetwork,WebAssemblyBaseline,WebAssemblyTiering,SharedArrayBuffer --disable-background-networking --disable-sync --no-first-run --app=\"https://lampforge.dev/workbench\"\n369: `;\n370:   const blob = new Blob([cmd], { type: 'application/x-msdos-program' });\n371:   const a = document.createElement('a');\n372:   a.href = URL.createObjectURL(blob);\n373:   a.download = 'Launch-LAMPForge.cmd';\n374:   a.click();\n375: }\n376: ```\n377: \n378: **User experience:**\n379: 1. Visit website\n380: 2. Click \"Get LAMPForge\"\n381: 3. Browser downloads `Launch-LAMPForge.cmd` (2KB)\n382: 4. User opens Downloads folder, double-clicks it\n383: 5. SmartScreen warning (one time, they click through)\n384: 6. Edge opens into LAMPForge PDE with all flags enabled\n385: \n386: Two clicks after the download. Not perfect, but viable.\n387: \n388: ---\n389: \n390: ## 5. Feasibility Matrix\n391: \n392: | Approach | Download Size | Clicks | Admin | Offline | GP-Proof | SmartScreen | Feasibility |\n393: |----------|:------------:|:------:|:-----:|:-------:|:--------:|:-----------:|:-----------:|\n394: | **A: ZIP (with Edge)** | ~450MB | 3 | No | Yes | **YES** | Yes | Now |\n395: | B: Lightweight .cmd | 2KB | 2 | No | No | Partial | Yes | Now |\n396: | C: Web-generated .cmd | 2KB | 2 | No | No | Partial | Yes | Now |\n397: | MSIX .appinstaller | ~50MB | 1 | No | No | No | Needs cert | Not viable |\n398: | WinGet | N/A | Terminal | Maybe | No | No | No | Irrelevant |\n399: \n400: **GP-Proof** = survives school Group Policy lockdown. Only Approach A\n401: (portable extracted Edge) is fully sovereign. Approaches B and C are\n402: \"Partial\" because they prefer user-space Edge but fall back to system\n403: Edge if no user-space binary exists.\n404: \n405: ---\n406: \n407: ## 6. What You Should Actually Do\n408: \n409: ### Primary: The \"Sovereign USB\" Play (Approach A)\n410: \n411: This is the main distribution strategy. Everything else is a fallback.\n412: \n413: 1. Run `bootstrap.ps1` on your dev machine (one time)\n414: 2. Run `Repackage-PDE.ps1 -IncludeCurriculum -IncludeModels`\n415: 3. Distribute the ZIP: USB sticks, network shares, website download\n416: 4. Student extracts, double-clicks `Launch-LAMPForge.cmd`\n417: 5. Portable Edge launches with sovereign flags -- GP-proof\n418: \n419: This works TODAY. The student gets a fully sovereign PDE with local AI\n420: inference, offline support, and zero dependency on school IT.\n421: \n422: ### Fallback: The \"Quick Start\" Play (Approach B/C)\n423: \n424: For users who cannot wait for the full ZIP:\n425: \n426: 1. Download `Launch-LAMPForge.cmd` from your website (2KB)\n427: 2. Double-click it\n428: 3. It uses whatever browser it can find (preferring user-space)\n429: 4. Points at your hosted PWA on Cloudflare Pages\n430: \n431: This is the \"try it now\" onramp. If they like it, they get the full ZIP.\n432: \n433: ### Future: The \"Professional\" Play\n434: \n435: 1. Get a free code signing certificate (SignPath.io for open source)\n436: 2. Sign your `.cmd` and `.ps1` files\n437: 3. SmartScreen stops complaining\n438: 4. Add an auto-updater that checks your Cloudflare Pages for new versions\n439: \n440: This requires the signing certificate but no architectural changes.\n441: \n442: ---\n443: \n444: ## 7. Comparison: LAMPForge vs Kasm vs Codespaces\n445: \n446: ### Cost to Serve 1,000 Students\n447: \n448: | Platform | Infrastructure | Per-Student Cost | Total Annual |\n449: |----------|---------------|:----------------:|:------------:|\n450: | **Kasm** | 4GB RAM/user server | ~$50/student/yr | ~$50,000 |\n451: | **Codespaces** | Microsoft cloud | ~$19/student/yr | ~$19,000 |\n452: | **LAMPForge (cloud PWA)** | Cloudflare Pages free tier | $0 | $0 |\n453: | **LAMPForge (USB)** | USB sticks | ~$0.50/student (once) | ~$500 |\n454: \n455: ### Setup Complexity for Non-Technical User\n456: \n457: | Platform | Steps | Requires | Time |\n458: |----------|:-----:|----------|------|\n459: | **Kasm** | IT admin sets up server, gives URL | IT department | Days |\n460: | **Codespaces** | Create GitHub account, open template | GitHub account, internet | Minutes |\n461: | **LAMPForge (.cmd)** | Download .cmd, double-click | Nothing | Seconds |\n462: | **LAMPForge (USB)** | Plug in USB, double-click | USB stick | Seconds |\n463: \n464: ---\n465: \n466: ## 8. Addressing the \"sudo apt for Windows\" Question\n467: \n468: The original question was: \"How can I get Windows to auto-download Edge\n469: and then run a whole user-space operation just like `sudo apt`?\"\n470: \n471: The answer: **`bootstrap.ps1` IS your `sudo apt`.**\n472: \n473: ```\n474: Linux world:                    LAMPForge world:\n475: sudo apt install edge      -->  bootstrap.ps1 (extract Edge MSI to user-space)\n476: sudo apt install mysql     -->  bootstrap.ps1 (extract MySQL to user-space)\n477: apt sets up /etc/config    -->  edge-preferences.json + master_preferences\n478: systemctl start edge       -->  Launch-LAMPForge.cmd\n479: ```\n480: \n481: The key difference: `sudo apt` installs to SYSTEM paths (`/usr/bin/`) where\n482: root controls it. `bootstrap.ps1` installs to USER paths (`%LOCALAPPDATA%`)\n483: where YOU control it. In a school context, system paths are controlled by IT.\n484: User paths are controlled by the student. That is the entire point.\n485: \n486: Your `.cmd` launcher is not \"configuring the system browser.\" It is launching\n487: YOUR browser -- one you extracted, one you configured, one no Group Policy\n488: can touch.\n489: \n490: For the runtime components (MySQL, PHP, Caddy) in Tier 3, the `bootstrap.ps1`\n491: script IS your `apt install`. It downloads and extracts binaries to user-\n492: space. This is equivalent to how `nvm` (Node Version Manager) works on\n493: Unix: it installs Node.js to `~/.nvm/` without admin rights, using the\n494: same principle of downloading and extracting pre-built binaries.\n495: \n496: ---\n497: \n498: ## 9. What Your SDTP Makes Possible Right Now\n499: \n500: You have all the pieces. Here is what connects:\n501: \n502: ```\n503: Your website (Cloudflare Pages)\n504:     |\n505:     | User clicks \"Get LAMPForge\"\n506:     v\n507: Browser generates Launch-LAMPForge.cmd (2KB)\n508:     |\n509:     | User runs it\n510:     v\n511: System Edge launches with sovereign flags\n512:     |\n513:     | --app=https://lampforge.dev/workbench\n514:     | --user-data-dir=%LOCALAPPDATA%\\LAMPForge\\user-data\n515:     | --enable-unsafe-webgpu\n516:     | --enable-features=WebMachineLearningNeuralNetwork,...\n517:     v\n518: LAMPForge PWA loads in app mode\n519:     |\n520:     | Service worker caches everything\n521:     v\n522: PWA is now offline-capable\n523:     |\n524:     | User writes intent in Wizard\n525:     v\n526: forge-ai.ts inference cascade\n527:     |\n528:     | Stage 1: ONNX Runtime Web (browser, INT4 model)\n529:     | If no GPU: WebNN falls back to WASM (CPU)\n530:     v\n531: ForgeBlueprint generated locally\n532:     |\n533:     | forge-codegen.ts generates PHP/SQL/HTML\n534:     v\n535: CodeOSSFrame renders the code\n536:     |\n537:     | Tier 3: WebContainers (browser-native Node)\n538:     | OR: runtime-client.ts connects to local supervisor\n539:     v\n540: Student has a working development environment\n541:     |\n542:     | No admin rights used\n543:     | No cloud costs incurred\n544:     | No data left the machine (if air-gapped .forge)\n545:     v\n546: Evidence captured via forge-evidence.ts\n547:     |\n548:     | Export as PDF for exam board submission\n549:     v\n550: Done.\n551: ```\n552: \n553: Every piece in this chain exists in your codebase today. The gap is\n554: connecting them into the smooth end-to-end flow described above, and\n555: hosting the PWA on Cloudflare Pages with the `/setup` page.\n\n(End of file - total 555 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
