      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\mistral_oci.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: Mistral Evaluation Report for a Welsh OCI-Based\n4: Agentic Services Business\n5: Executive summary\n6: Marek Porycki is directionally right on the core facts , but he overstates the parts that require\n7: architectural proof. It is verified that Mistral Medium 3.5  is a 128B dense  model with a 256k  context\n8: window, released as open weights  under a Modified MIT  license; Mistral also says it can be self-hosted on \n9: as few as four GPUs , is built for long-horizon tasks  and multiple tool calls , became the new default in Le\n10: Chat , and replaced Devstral 2  in Vibe . What is not verified in Mistral’s public materials is his specific\n11: technical explanation that dense beats MoE because of “expert drift” over long tool sessions. Mistral’s public\n12: argument is product-level and operational, not a published MoE-vs-dense ablation. \n13: The licensing point is more serious than his post implies. The text published for Modified MIT  on the model\n14: repositories is not plain MIT and not Apache 2.0: it says you cannot exercise license rights  if your\n15: company or employer had global consolidated monthly revenue above $20 million in the preceding\n16: month , unless you obtain a commercial license or use Mistral’s hosted services. That means the weights are\n17: publicly downloadable, but the license is revenue-restricted , so they should be treated as open weights\n18: with a commercial condition , not as unrestricted open-source software in the usual OSI sense. \n19: For your company, the strongest near-term conclusion is commercial rather than ideological: API-first is\n20: overwhelmingly cheaper than self-hosting  for typical SME and public-sector pilot volumes. Using Mistral’s\n21: current public API prices, even fairly active monthly usage usually lands in the tens to low hundreds of\n22: dollars , whereas a 24/7 single-accelerator self-host starts around $942–$1,460/month  on public pricing\n23: examples, and a serious 123B–128B private deployment quickly moves into the high four figures to tens of\n24: thousands per month  before internal operations cost. Self-hosting becomes rational mainly for \n25: sovereignty, private networking, procurement constraints, deterministic throughput, or very high\n26: token volumes , not because it is cheaper at ordinary pilot scale. \n27: The recommended minimal viable path for a LAMPForge-style product is therefore: keep your app tier on \n28: OCI where possible, start with a model router  that sends low-risk orchestration and extraction work to \n29: Ministral 3 14B  or 8B, reserve Mistral Medium 3.5  for difficult multi-step agent runs, and only add self-\n30: hosted open weights after you have a live audit trail of workloads that actually justify it. If customers later\n31: demand private deployment, the first cost-effective self-host tier is 24B-class  models; the first serious\n32: private coding-agent tier is Devstral 2  or Medium 3.5  on 4× H100-class  infrastructure. \n33: What Mistral actually offers now\n34: Mistral’s current portfolio relevant to agentic services splits cleanly into five practical buckets. Mistral\n35: Medium 3.5  is the new flagship merged model for coding, reasoning, and instruction following; Devstral 2\n36: is the frontier open-weight code-agent model; Devstral Small 2  is the compact 24B coding/agent model but1\n37: 2\n38: 3\n39: 4\n40: 1\n41: --- PAGE 2 ---\n42: is already marked as deprecated in Mistral’s own API docs; Magistral Small  is the 24B reasoning-focused\n43: open model; and Ministral 3  is the efficient edge/on-prem family in 3B, 8B, and 14B  sizes. \n44: Current model status and positioning\n45: ModelWhat Mistral says\n46: it isContext Public API price LicensePractical commercial\n47: reading\n48: Mistral\n49: Medium\n50: 3.5Frontier\n51: multimodal model\n52: optimized for\n53: agentic and\n54: coding use cases;\n55: first flagship\n56: merged model256k$1.5/M input,\n57: $7.5/M outputModified\n58: MITBest current default for\n59: premium agent\n60: workflows; self-host\n61: possible, but license\n62: needs review for larger\n63: enterprises. \n64: Devstral 2Frontier code-\n65: agents model for\n66: software\n67: engineering256k$0.4/M input,\n68: $2/M outputModified\n69: MITBest open-weight\n70: coding-agent candidate\n71: for serious private\n72: deployment. \n73: Devstral\n74: Small 2Compact open-\n75: source coding/\n76: agent model256kIntro pricing\n77: announced at\n78: $0.1/M input,\n79: $0.3/M outputApache\n80: 2.0Excellent budget/self-\n81: host option, but not a\n82: safe anchor for new\n83: hosted products\n84: because the Mistral API\n85: card marks it\n86: deprecated and\n87: replaced by Devstral 2. \n88: Magistral\n89: SmallSmall, efficient\n90: reasoning model128kNot publicly\n91: emphasized in\n92: the current\n93: materials\n94: gathered hereApache\n95: 2.0Useful when you want a\n96: compact reasoning\n97: specialist, but Mistral\n98: Medium 3.5 has now\n99: displaced the Magistral\n100: family in Le Chat. \n101: Ministral\n102: 3 14BEfficient open\n103: model for edge or\n104: on-prem with full\n105: platform feature\n106: support256k$0.2/M input,\n107: $0.2/M outputApache\n108: 2.0Strong low-cost\n109: orchestrator , extractor ,\n110: and RAG-worker model.\n111: Ministral\n112: 3 8BSmaller edge/on-\n113: prem option with\n114: full platform\n115: feature support256k$0.15/M input,\n116: $0.15/M outputApache\n117: 2.0Cheap helper/triage/\n118: router model. 5\n119: 6\n120: 7\n121: 8\n122: 9\n123: 10\n124: 11\n125: 2\n126: --- PAGE 3 ---\n127: The most important portfolio change is that Mistral Medium 3.5 is not merely another large model ;\n128: Mistral explicitly positions it as the model that made long-running cloud agents practical in Vibe and as the\n129: new default for complex work in Le Chat. That confirms the commercial direction Marek pointed to, even if\n130: his dense-vs-MoE rationale is still his own interpretation. \n131: Licensing and compliance implications\n132: The Modified MIT  terms now used for Mistral Medium 3.5  and Devstral 2  are straightforward in text and\n133: material in effect. The license grants broad rights to use, modify, distribute, sublicense, and sell copies of\n134: the model, but then removes those rights  for companies or employers whose global consolidated\n135: monthly revenue exceeded $20 million  in the prior month. Mistral’s help center says these models\n136: otherwise carry the “same permissions as Apache 2.0,” with that revenue-based exception. \n137: That matters for three reasons. First, the revenue test is tied to the company or employer , not just the\n138: specific product team, so an SME reseller working independently may be fine while a reseller embedded in\n139: a larger integrator may not be. Second, the restriction expressly extends to derivatives, modifications,\n140: and combined works , so wrapping the weights in your own service layer does not remove the issue. Third,\n141: because the license is conditioned on who you are and on a commercial threshold, it is very unlikely to fit\n142: normal OSI open-source  criteria, which prohibit discrimination against persons, groups, or fields of\n143: endeavor . \n144: There is also a more subtle legal difference from Apache 2.0. The Apache 2.0 text includes an express\n145: patent license  from contributors; the published Modified MIT texts for Medium 3.5 and Devstral 2 do not\n146: contain an equivalent patent clause in the license file itself. Mistral’s help article says the modified license\n147: offers the same permissions as Apache 2.0 except for the revenue threshold, but that statement is\n148: explanatory support material, not the operative patent language in the repository license text. For risk-\n149: averse enterprise and public-sector procurement, that is a review point for counsel rather than something\n150: to gloss over . \n151: For Welsh public-sector selling, the compliance picture is nuanced. The EU AI Act  is not automatically the\n152: domestic rulebook for the public sector in the United Kingdom , but it still matters commercially if you\n153: serve EU institutions, build EU-facing systems, or bid into procurements that contractually require AI Act\n154: alignment. The European Commission states that the obligations for providers of general-purpose AI\n155: models entered into application on August 2, 2025 , and Article 53 / Annex XII require technical and\n156: transparency information for downstream integrators. In parallel, the ICO says a DPIA  should be carried\n157: out before using an AI tool, ideally at procurement stage , when personal data is involved. In practice, a\n158: Welsh vendor should prepare AI Act-style downstream documentation even for UK deals, because it\n159: shortens due diligence and makes public-sector assurance easier . \n160: Mistral has at least started to build the paperwork chain that public buyers will ask for . Its legal center\n161: positions itself as an AI governance hub for AI Act resources, and its DPA points customers to a trust center\n162: for technical and organizational measures. That helps, but it does not remove the need for your own\n163: service-level documentation on logging, approval flows, data retention, human oversight, and incident\n164: handling. 12\n165: 13\n166: 14\n167: 15\n168: 16\n169: 17\n170: 18\n171: 3\n172: --- PAGE 4 ---\n173: Legal and compliance risk register\n174: Risk Why it matters Recommended response\n175: Revenue-restricted\n176: open weightsIf your company, parent, or employer is\n177: above the threshold, self-host rights are\n178: not available under the posted license. Record legal entity structure now;\n179: treat this as a procurement gate\n180: before any private deployment\n181: offer .\n182: OSI-open-source\n183: mismatch“Open source” language in sales can\n184: become misleading if the license is not\n185: OSI-compliant. Say open weights  for Modified MIT\n186: models, not unrestricted open\n187: source.\n188: Patent-language\n189: ambiguityApache 2.0 has an explicit patent grant;\n190: the published Modified MIT text does\n191: not. Flag for legal review in any\n192: enterprise or public-sector contract\n193: pack.\n194: Downstream AI\n195: Act / procurement\n196: assurancePublic buyers will ask what model is\n197: used, how it is controlled, and what\n198: documentation exists. Ship a technical dossier with model\n199: card, DPA summary, data-flow map,\n200: approval policy, and DPIA template.\n201: Data-protection\n202: exposure in agentsAgentic systems tend to aggregate\n203: documents, inboxes, issue trackers, and\n204: code, often with personal data. Put retrieval, tool permissioning,\n205: and export controls behind explicit\n206: policy gates.\n207: Deployment options and recommended architectures\n208: Managed deployment options are broader than just Mistral’s hosted API. Mistral’s docs say its commercial/\n209: optimized models are available through cloud integrations on Oracle  Cloud Infrastructure , Amazon\n210: Web Services , Microsoft  Azure, Google  Cloud, Snowflake  Cortex, IBM  watsonx, and \n211: Outscale . For open-weight self-deployment, Mistral’s own deployment docs point to local/self-host\n212: paths that range from single-GPU setups to clusters with 4+ H100s  for larger models. \n213: On self-host routes, the practical split is as follows. vLLM  is the strongest mainstream serving option if you\n214: want a production server with an OpenAI-compatible endpoint  and Mistral-specific tool-call parsing. \n215: SGLang  is a serious production serving framework with OpenAI-compatible APIs , tool parsing, structured\n216: outputs, and quantization support; however , its docs describe GGUF  support as future work rather than the\n217: primary route today. Ollama  is the simplest packaging path for local tests and internal demos, and it\n218: already exposes Devstral Small 2 , Magistral , and Mistral Medium 3.5  in its library. Unsloth/GGUF  is the\n219: practical path for quantized experiments and cost-constrained local runs, with explicit current guidance for\n220: Devstral 2 and Small 2; but for Medium 3.5, Unsloth warns that long-context GGUF support is still WIP . 13\n221: 19\n222: 20\n223: 21\n224: 22\n225: 23\n226: 24 25 26 27 28\n227: 29\n228: 30\n229: 31\n230: 4\n231: --- PAGE 5 ---\n232: Tooling fit by route\n233: Route Best use Strengths Current caution\n234: vLLMProduction API\n235: server for open\n236: weightsOpenAI-compatible server; can\n237: use Transformers backend and\n238: Mistral tool parser . You still need to validate\n239: exact tokenizer/chat-\n240: template behavior model by\n241: model.\n242: SGLangHigh-throughput\n243: agent servingOpenAI-compatible APIs, tool\n244: parser , structured outputs,\n245: production focus. GGUF is not the main route\n246: yet; docs frame it as\n247: upcoming. \n248: OllamaLocal packaging,\n249: demos, small-team\n250: internal useVery fast setup, easy model\n251: pulls for Devstral Small 2,\n252: Magistral, Medium 3.5. Great for evaluation; less\n253: ideal as your final enterprise\n254: serving layer for complex\n255: multi-tenant workloads.\n256: Unsloth /\n257: GGUFQuantized\n258: experiments, cost-\n259: constrained self-\n260: hostingDevstral Small 2 guide says 24B\n261: fits in ~25GB RAM/VRAM;\n262: Devstral 2 guide says 123B fits\n263: in ~128GB. Medium 3.5 GGUF long-\n264: context behavior is currently\n265: flagged as WIP. \n266: For networking and buyer assurance, the hyperscalers all give you a private story. OCI supports VCNs ,\n267: private subnets, and private load balancers; AWS uses VPC and PrivateLink ; Azure uses VNet  and Private\n268: Link ; Google Cloud uses VPC and Private Service Connect . For public-sector work, those primitives matter\n269: more than marginal GPU economics because they are what let you answer questions about isolation,\n270: auditability, and non-public traffic paths. \n271: API-first architecture on OCI\n272: This is the recommended starting point for your business: keep the web/API tier , queue, storage, audit\n273: logging, and tenancy controls on OCI, but consume Mistral models via API until you have measured,\n274: repeated evidence that private hosting is commercially justified. OCI’s Free Tier includes Always Free AMD/\n275: Arm compute and storage allowances, which makes it a good place to park the app tier even when the\n276: model tier stays hosted. \n277: flowchart LR\n278:     U[Client / Buyer] --> W[Web App on OCI]\n279:     W --> O[Orchestrator / Policy Engine]\n280:     O --> R[Model Router]\n281:     R --> M1[Mistral API - Ministral 14B or 8B]\n282:     R --> M2[Mistral API - Medium 3.5]\n283:     R --> M3[Mistral API - Devstral 2]\n284:     O --> V[Vector Store / Search]\n285:     O --> Q[Job Queue]32\n286: 33 34\n287: 35\n288: 3637\n289: 38\n290: 39\n291: 5\n292: --- PAGE 6 ---\n293:     O --> A[Audit Log / Approval Store]\n294:     O --> T[Tool Connectors]\n295: Private self-host architecture on OCI\n296: If a customer later requires private deployment, run the model servers in private subnets behind a private\n297: load balancer , and expose only an application-tier gateway or bastion path. That aligns well with OCI’s VCN/\n298: private-load-balancer model. For 24B-class models, a single A10/L4-class setup can be enough; for Devstral\n299: 2 or Medium 3.5, plan around 4× H100-class infrastructure as the minimum serious serving tier . \n300: flowchart TB\n301:     C[Customer Network / VPN] --> G[Private API Gateway]\n302:     G --> LB[Private Load Balancer]\n303:     LB --> S1[Model Server Node 1]\n304:     LB --> S2[Model Server Node 2]\n305:     LB --> S3[Model Server Node 3]\n306:     LB --> S4[Model Server Node 4]\n307:     S1 --> DB[Vector DB / Metadata DB]\n308:     S2 --> OBJ[Object Storage]\n309:     S3 --> OBS[Telemetry / Metrics]\n310:     S4 --> Q2[Queue / Worker Bus]\n311: OpenAI-compatible serving patterns\n312: A vLLM-style serving layer is the shortest path if you want an internal API that looks like the OpenAI\n313: ecosystem from the app’s point of view. vLLM explicitly documents an OpenAI-compatible server path and a\n314: Mistral tool parser . \n315: # Example: vLLM OpenAI-compatible server\n316: vllmservemistralai/Devstral-2-123B-Instruct-2512 \\\n317: --trust-remote-code \\\n318: --tensor-parallel-size 4\\\n319: --host0.0.0.0\\\n320: --port8000\n321: SGLang offers the same compatibility pattern and is particularly attractive if you care about structured\n322: output and lower-level serving controls. Its docs explicitly position it as an OpenAI-compatible API layer . \n323: # Example: SGLang OpenAI-compatible server\n324: python3 -msglang.launch_server \\\n325: --model-path mistralai/Devstral-2-123B-Instruct-2512 \\\n326: --host0.0.0.0\\40\n327: 32\n328: 41\n329: 6\n330: --- PAGE 7 ---\n331: --port30000\\\n332: --tp4\n333: A simple application-side proxy pattern is then enough:\n334: fromopenaiimportOpenAI\n335: client=OpenAI(\n336: base_url =\"https://your-internal-llm-endpoint/v1\" ,\n337: api_key=\"internal-token\"\n338: )\n339: resp=client.chat.completions .create(\n340: model=\"devstral-2\" ,\n341: messages =[\n342: {\"role\":\"system\" ,\"content\" :\"You are a controlled coding agent.\" },\n343: {\"role\":\"user\",\"content\" :\"Analyze this repo and propose a safe patch \n344: plan.\"}\n345: ],\n346: tools=[{\n347: \"type\":\"function\" ,\n348: \"function\" :{\n349: \"name\":\"open_file\" ,\n350: \"description\" :\"Read one file from the sandbox\" ,\n351: \"parameters\" :{\n352: \"type\":\"object\" ,\n353: \"properties\" :{\"path\":{\"type\":\"string\" }},\n354: \"required\" :[\"path\"]\n355: }\n356: }\n357: }]\n358: )\n359: print(resp.choices[0].message)\n360: Cost models and TCO scenarios\n361: The figures below use a simple planning assumption of £1 = $1.25  or $1 = £0.80  for budgeting, 730 hours/\n362: month , and published public list prices where they are available. These are planning models , not invoices.\n363: Storage, egress, logging, and engineering labor are not fully loaded into the infrastructure rows unless\n364: noted, which means the true all-in TCO of self-hosting will usually be higher than the raw compute line. The\n365: reason to show them this way is to isolate the economic question the clearest way possible: how much are\n366: you actually buying with self-hosting that the API is not already giving you?\n367: 7\n368: --- PAGE 8 ---\n369: Hosted API cost scenarios\n370: Scenario AssumptionDevstral\n371: Small 2Devstral 2Mistral\n372: Medium 3.5Ministral 3\n373: 14B\n374: Prototype10M input / 2M\n375: output$1.60 /\n376: £1.28$8.00 /\n377: £6.40$30.00 /\n378: £24.00$2.40 /\n379: £1.92\n380: Intermittent dev50M input /\n381: 10M output$8.00 /\n382: £6.40$40.00 /\n383: £32.00$150.00 /\n384: £120.00$12.00 /\n385: £9.60\n386: Always-on\n387: production200M input /\n388: 50M output$35.00 /\n389: £28.00$180.00 /\n390: £144.00$675.00 /\n391: £540.00$50.00 /\n392: £40.00\n393: Enterprise private\n394: alternative\n395: benchmark500M input /\n396: 125M output$87.50 /\n397: £70.00$450.00 /\n398: £360.00$1,687.50 /\n399: £1,350.00$125.00 /\n400: £100.00\n401: Basis:  current public Mistral prices for Medium 3.5 and Devstral 2 from model cards/blogs, and current\n402: public Ministral 3 prices from model cards. Devstral Small 2 pricing comes from the Devstral 2 launch\n403: announcement; its API card is now deprecated. \n404: Those numbers are why an API-first approach is the rational default. Even at the “always-on production”\n405: benchmark, the hosted bill for strong models remains dramatically below the cost of keeping GPU servers\n406: warm 24/7. For most SMEs, self-host should be triggered by privacy, procurement, or latency\n407: determinism , not by a belief that it will obviously reduce cost. \n408: Representative self-host infrastructure costs\n409: Provider /\n410: instanceRepresentative\n411: GPU tierPublic price\n412: exampleMonthly\n413: at 730hBuyer/operations note\n414: OCI\n415: VM.GPU.A10.11× A10 $2.00/h$1,460 /\n416: £1,168Good first self-host tier for 8B–\n417: 24B-class models. \n418: OCI\n419: BM.GPU.A10.44× A10 $8.00/h$5,840 /\n420: £4,672More headroom, but still usually\n421: unnecessary in phase one. \n422: OCI\n423: BM.GPU.L40S.44× L40S $14.00/h$10,220 /\n424: £8,176Useful inference/perf middle tier\n425: when available. \n426: OCI\n427: BM.GPU.H100.88× H100 $80.00/h$58,400 /\n428: £46,720Serious private deployment;\n429: usually needs enterprise\n430: justification. \n431: OCI\n432: BM.GPU.H200.88× H200 $80.00/h$58,400 /\n433: £46,720Same published GPU-hour as\n434: H100 in Oracle’s material, but\n435: accessed via AI infrastructure /\n436: sales-led routes. 42\n437: 43\n438: 44\n439: 44\n440: 45\n441: 46\n442: 47\n443: 8\n444: --- PAGE 9 ---\n445: Provider /\n446: instanceRepresentative\n447: GPU tierPublic price\n448: exampleMonthly\n449: at 730hBuyer/operations note\n450: GCP g2-\n451: standard-484× L4 $4.0017/h$2,921 /\n452: £2,337Strong public benchmark for\n453: low-cost L4-class inference. \n454: GCP a3-\n455: highgpu-8g8× H100 $101.0074/h$73,735 /\n456: £58,988On-demand hyperscale-grade\n457: H100 example. \n458: GCP a3-\n459: ultragpu-8g8× H200 $99.7739/h$72,835 /\n460: £58,268H200 example with very strong\n461: networking. \n462: Lambda 1× A10 1× A10 $1.29/h$942 /\n463: £754Attractive for lab work and\n464: quantized 24B-class testing. \n465: Lambda 1× H100\n466: PCIe1× H100 $3.29/h$2,402 /\n467: £1,922Good single-card benchmark;\n468: not enough for official full-size\n469: 123B/128B recommendations. \n470: Hyperstack 1×\n471: H100 SXM1× H100 SXM $2.40/h$1,752 /\n472: £1,402Often cheaper than hyperscalers\n473: on raw GPU-hour . \n474: Hyperstack 1×\n475: H200 SXM1× H200 SXM $3.50/h$2,555 /\n476: £2,044Strong raw economics if\n477: procurement permits use of a\n478: specialist provider . \n479: The table above is not a claim that every provider has the same enterprise posture. It is a raw-price\n480: comparison where public prices exist. Specialized GPU clouds often win on bare GPU-hour price, but they\n481: may lose on procurement frameworks, region choice, private-linking maturity, or public-sector comfort.\n482: Conversely, Azure looks competitive operationally for many buyers, but anonymous public web pricing for\n483: the target GPU SKUs is not readily extractable in the same way; in practice, much Azure planning still runs\n484: through the calculator or quote process. \n485: Procurement-oriented provider comparison\n486: Provider L4 A10 H100 H200Private\n487: network\n488: optionsProcurement\n489: reading\n490: OCIEdge /\n491: CC@C-\n492: oriented in\n493: Oracle’s\n494: public\n495: material, not\n496: the standard\n497: public-region\n498: GPU routeYes, public\n499: pricing at\n500: $2/GPU-hYes,\n501: public\n502: pricing\n503: at $10/\n504: GPU-hYes,\n505: public\n506: pricing\n507: at $10/\n508: GPU-hVCN, private\n509: subnets,\n510: private LBsStrong if the\n511: customer values\n512: Oracle footprint,\n513: private\n514: networking, and\n515: a simple route\n516: from your\n517: existing OCI\n518: tenancy. 48\n519: 49\n520: 50\n521: 51\n522: 51\n523: 52\n524: 52\n525: 53\n526: 54\n527: 9\n528: --- PAGE 10 ---\n529: Provider L4 A10 H100 H200Private\n530: network\n531: optionsProcurement\n532: reading\n533: AWS G6 family G5 familyP5\n534: familyP5e/\n535: P5en\n536: familyVPC,\n537: PrivateLinkStrong public-\n538: sector familiarity;\n539: public\n540: anonymous\n541: prices are easier\n542: to find for\n543: capacity blocks\n544: than for everyday\n545: on-demand list\n546: prices. \n547: AzurePublic web\n548: material\n549: focused\n550: more on SKU\n551: availability\n552: than\n553: anonymous\n554: list price\n555: visibilityNVads A10\n556: v5NCads\n557: H100\n558: v5ND\n559: H200\n560: v5VNet,\n561: Private LinkOften\n562: procurement-\n563: friendly for\n564: enterprise/public\n565: sector , but expect\n566: quote/calculator\n567: work. \n568: GCP G2 familyNo\n569: comparable\n570: public A10\n571: family in the\n572: gathered\n573: materialA3\n574: familyA3\n575: Ultra\n576: familyVPC, Private\n577: Service\n578: ConnectExcellent\n579: transparent\n580: public pricing and\n581: strong large-scale\n582: network story. \n583: Specialized\n584: GPU\n585: cloudsVaries Varies Yes YesUsually\n586: private\n587: networking\n588: exists but\n589: maturity\n590: varies by\n591: vendorBest unit\n592: economics;\n593: procurement win\n594: depends on\n595: buyer comfort\n596: with\n597: subcontractors,\n598: sovereignty, and\n599: assurance\n600: evidence. \n601: Sensitivity analysis\n602: The hidden cost driver in agentic systems is not just token price; it is token multiplication  from retries,\n603: long transcripts, tool-call traces, and context replay. If your nominal monthly workload is 200M input / 50M\n604: output , then the bill changes as follows:55\n605: 56\n606: 57\n607: 58\n608: 10\n609: --- PAGE 11 ---\n610: Workload\n611: multiplierAll Devstral\n612: 2All Medium\n613: 3.5All Ministral 3\n614: 14B80% Ministral 14B + 20%\n615: Medium 3.5\n616: 1× nominal $180 / £144 $675 / £540 $50 / £40 $175 / £140\n617: 3× effective\n618: tokens$540 / £432$2,025 /\n619: £1,620$150 / £120 $525 / £420\n620: 5× effective\n621: tokens$900 / £720$3,375 /\n622: £2,700$250 / £200 $875 / £700\n623: The implication is simple. A smart router plus strict prompt hygiene has more financial value than chasing a\n624: “cheaper” self-host story too early. If you can keep most workflow steps on small models and escalate only\n625: the hard branches, your gross margin improves immediately. The minute you let every job default to the\n626: biggest model with long conversational state, your economics degrade quickly. The underlying token rates\n627: are the public ones above; the multiplier is a planning assumption for agent loops. \n628: Model comparison and recommendations\n629: Which models are actually suitable for stable agentic workloads\n630: ModelPractical self-\n631: host floorQuantization\n632: feasibilityAgent\n633: suitabilityLatency /\n634: reliability\n635: expectationLicense\n636: constraintRecommended\n637: use\n638: Devstral\n639: Small 2Single GPU,\n640: consumer\n641: hardware,\n642: and even\n643: CPU-only for\n644: some usesStrong: Unsloth\n645: says ~25GB\n646: RAM/VRAM;\n647: Ollama route\n648: existsGood for\n649: coding\n650: agents and\n651: low-cost\n652: private pilotsFastest\n653: practical\n654: self-host\n655: option in\n656: the Mistral\n657: coding\n658: familyApache\n659: 2.0Best first\n660: private pilot\n661: for SMEs;\n662: avoid building\n663: new API\n664: products\n665: around it\n666: because the\n667: API card is\n668: deprecated. \n669: Devstral\n670: 2Mistral\n671: recommends\n672: minimum 4\n673: H100-class\n674: GPUs for\n675: deploymentStrong for\n676: quantized\n677: experimentation;\n678: Unsloth says\n679: 123B fits in\n680: 128GBExcellent for\n681: software-\n682: engineering\n683: agentsGood fit for\n684: serious\n685: codebase\n686: exploration\n687: and multi-\n688: file editsModified\n689: MITBest open-\n690: weight coding\n691: model if a\n692: customer\n693: really needs\n694: private\n695: deployment. 43\n696: 59\n697: 60\n698: 11\n699: --- PAGE 12 ---\n700: ModelPractical self-\n701: host floorQuantization\n702: feasibilityAgent\n703: suitabilityLatency /\n704: reliability\n705: expectationLicense\n706: constraintRecommended\n707: use\n708: Mistral\n709: Medium\n710: 3.5Mistral says\n711: self-host on\n712: as few as 4\n713: GPUsMixed: Ollama\n714: exists, but\n715: Unsloth says\n716: GGUF long-\n717: context is still\n718: WIPHighest\n719: current\n720: Mistral fit for\n721: premium\n722: long-running\n723: agentsMistral\n724: positions it\n725: as the\n726: model that\n727: made Vibe\n728: remote\n729: agents\n730: practicalModified\n731: MITBest premium\n732: default for\n733: research,\n734: analysis, and\n735: cross-tool\n736: agent\n737: workflows. \n738: Magistral\n739: Small24B-class\n740: local\n741: deploymentPractical via\n742: OllamaGood for\n743: explicit\n744: reasoning\n745: tasksViable, but\n746: not\n747: Mistral’s\n748: current\n749: flagship\n750: directionApache\n751: 2.0Use when you\n752: specifically\n753: want a\n754: compact\n755: reasoning\n756: specialist;\n757: otherwise\n758: prefer Medium\n759: 3.5 or Ministral\n760: 14B. \n761: Ministral\n762: 3 14B14B-class\n763: local/edge\n764: deploymentFeasible on\n765: modest\n766: hardware;\n767: intended for on-\n768: prem/edgeVery good for\n769: orchestration,\n770: extraction,\n771: and RAG-\n772: worker rolesLower cost\n773: and lower\n774: latency\n775: than the\n776: flagship\n777: tierApache\n778: 2.0Best default\n779: “worker”\n780: model in a\n781: router\n782: architecture. \n783: Ministral\n784: 3 8B8B-class\n785: local/edge\n786: deploymentHighly feasibleGood for\n787: routing,\n788: triage, helper\n789: toolsLowest cost\n790: among\n791: worthwhile\n792: Mistral API\n793: options\n794: hereApache\n795: 2.0Best cheap\n796: helper/router\n797: model. \n798: The practical recommendation is to think in roles , not in one-model absolutism. Use Ministral 14B or 8B  for\n799: cheap steps, extraction, routing, and bounded tool tasks. Use Medium 3.5  as the premium planner/\n800: executor for multi-step runs and the offer you show to demanding customers. Use Devstral 2  specifically\n801: where the differentiator is codebase work, pull-request generation, and engineering productivity. Use self-\n802: hosted Devstral Small 2  only as a privacy-friendly pilot or low-cost private proof-of-concept, not as the\n803: backbone of a long-lived hosted SKU unless you control the full risk of its deprecation in the managed API\n804: channel. 61\n805: 62\n806: 10\n807: 11\n808: 63\n809: 12\n810: --- PAGE 13 ---\n811: Roadmap, minimal viable stack, and commercial packaging\n812: A realistic implementation roadmap is four stages. The first is control and paperwork : define data classes,\n813: prompt redaction, approval rules, logging, output retention, and a DPIA template. The second is API-first\n814: buildout  on your existing OCI footprint. The third is a measured routing stage , where you capture real\n815: token, latency, and approval metrics to see which requests actually need premium models. The fourth is \n816: private deployment only for demanded cases , not as a default religion. This roadmap follows directly\n817: from the cost and licensing evidence above. \n818: Suggested implementation roadmap\n819: Stage Duration Core output Decision gate\n820: Governance and\n821: architecture1–2 weeksData map, approval policy, DPIA\n822: template, supplier pack, model-\n823: routing designDo you have a contract-safe\n824: story for public-sector\n825: buyers?\n826: API-first\n827: prototype2–4 weeksOCI-hosted app tier , audit log,\n828: model router , first agent\n829: workflowsAre users getting value before\n830: private hosting is even\n831: discussed?\n832: Pilot and\n833: hardening4–8 weeksUsage telemetry, prompt\n834: libraries, role-based approvals,\n835: failure taxonomyWhich workloads truly need\n836: the premium model or private\n837: deployment?\n838: Private\n839: deployment\n840: option4–10 weeks\n841: after pilotvLLM/SGLang serving, VCN-\n842: private deployment, sandboxed\n843: tools, enterprise dossierIs there a signed buyer\n844: requirement for private\n845: hosting or sovereignty?\n846: Recommended minimal viable stack for a LAMPForge-style product\n847: The minimal viable stack I would recommend is:\n848: OCI app tier  on existing Free Tier/PAYG resources for the portal, admin UI, queue workers, storage,\n849: and logs. OCI’s free tier supports Always Free AMD/Arm compute and storage allowances, which is\n850: ideal for keeping the product shell cheap. \n851: Model router  with three lanes:\n852: cheap lane: Ministral 3 8B / 14B,\n853: premium lane: Mistral Medium 3.5,\n854: coding lane: Devstral 2 only when the task is genuinely software-engineering heavy. \n855: Human-in-the-loop approvals  for external writes, message sends, ticket creation, or document\n856: modification. \n857: Audit and export pack  with model ID, prompt class, tools used, approvals, retrieved documents,\n858: and final artifacts. 64\n859: 1. \n860: 39\n861: 2. \n862: 3. \n863: 4. \n864: 5. 65\n865: 6. \n866: 7. \n867: 13\n868: --- PAGE 14 ---\n869: Optional self-host dev box  only for evaluation: one A10-class node for testing small open-weight\n870: models, not for day-one production. \n871: Costed MVP recommendation\n872: Under a conservative MVP assumption, keep the application shell near-free or low-cost on OCI and spend\n873: your budget where it moves the needle: the model layer . A sensible base commercial mix is 80% Ministral\n874: 14B / 20% Medium 3.5 . At a monthly benchmark of 200M input / 50M output , that mix costs about $175 /\n875: £140  in LLM charges. If your non-LLM shell remains mostly inside OCI Always Free or light PAYG usage, the\n876: real MVP can stay in the low hundreds per month , not the thousands. By contrast, forcing a 24/7 self-\n877: hosted A10 node immediately pushes you toward $942–$1,460/month  before people cost, and a serious 4×\n878: H100-class private tier pushes much higher . \n879: Migration path from API-first to self-host\n880: The clean migration path is:\n881: Phase one:  Hosted API only, but with a router and internal abstraction layer from day one. \n882: Phase two:  Drop in a self-hosted 8B–24B lane for sensitive but bounded workloads. \n883: Phase three:  Introduce private Devstral 2 or Medium 3.5 only  when a contract requires private\n884: networking, air-gapped-ish behavior , or strong buyer control over logs and data transit. \n885: Phase four:  Offer customer-VPC or customer-tenancy deployment as a premium SKU. \n886: That sequence minimizes sunk cost and lets the customer pay for privacy only when privacy actually\n887: changes the buying decision. It also avoids building yourself into a corner around Devstral Small 2’s\n888: managed-API deprecation. \n889: Sales and packaging suggestions for Welsh customers\n890: For Welsh buyers, especially the public sector , sell assurance packages , not just model performance. The\n891: offer should be framed as:\n892: Discovery and DPIA package : workshop, data-flow design, model register , security and approval\n893: rules. \n894: Hosted secure pilot : API-first, human-approved actions, full audit logs, no customer-side GPU\n895: commitment. \n896: Private deployment add-on : customer VPC / OCI tenancy / approved network path, with vLLM or\n897: SGLang, only for workloads that justify it. \n898: Engineering agent package : Devstral 2 or Medium 3.5 for code workflows, sandboxed tool\n899: execution, branch/PR generation, and approval gates. \n900: The message that will resonate is not “we self-host because open source,” but “we can start cheaply and\n901: safely, then move private when your governance, data class, or procurement model requires it.” That is a\n902: much stronger sales story because it aligns with how public-sector organizations actually buy risk down. 8. \n903: 66\n904: 67\n905: • \n906: • \n907: • \n908: • \n909: 68\n910: • \n911: • \n912: • \n913: • \n914: 69\n915: 14\n916: --- PAGE 15 ---\n917: Open questions and limitations\n918: A few items remain incomplete in the public materials I reviewed. Azure’s public web pages clearly confirm\n919: the relevant A10, H100, and H200 VM families, but they do not expose clean anonymous list pricing in the\n920: same way as OCI, GCP, or some specialist GPU clouds, so Azure should be treated as calculator/quote\n921: required  for final financial comparison. Mistral Compute private-cluster pricing is also not publicly detailed\n922: in the sources gathered here. And for Mistral Medium 3.5 , the GGUF long-context path remains a live\n923: moving target , so it should not yet be the basis of a production commitment. \n924: The highest-confidence recommendation, therefore, is: build API-first, route aggressively, self-host only\n925: where governance or customer procurement truly requires it, and describe Modified MIT models as\n926: open weights subject to a revenue-based commercial condition.\n927: https://mistral.ai/news/vibe-remote-agents-mistral-medium-3-5\n928: https://mistral.ai/news/vibe-remote-agents-mistral-medium-3-5\n929: https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mistral-Medium-3.5-128B/blob/main/LICENSE\n930: https://huggingface.co/mistralai/Mistral-Medium-3.5-128B/blob/main/LICENSE\n931: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/mistral-medium-3-5-26-04\n932: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/mistral-medium-3-5-26-04\n933: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/ministral-3-14b-25-12\n934: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/ministral-3-14b-25-12\n935: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/devstral-2-25-12\n936: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/devstral-2-25-12\n937: https://mistral.ai/news/devstral-2-vibe-cli\n938: https://mistral.ai/news/devstral-2-vibe-cli\n939: https://mistral.ai/news/magistral\n940: https://mistral.ai/news/magistral\n941: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/ministral-3-8b-25-12\n942: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/ministral-3-8b-25-12\n943: https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n944: https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n945: https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/guidelines-gpai-providers\n946: https://digital-strategy.ec.europa.eu/en/policies/guidelines-gpai-providers\n947: https://legal.mistral.ai/\n948: https://legal.mistral.ai/\n949: https://opensource.org/osd\n950: https://opensource.org/osd\n951: https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/artificial-intelligence/guidance-on-\n952: ai-and-data-protection/\n953: https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/uk-gdpr-guidance-and-resources/artificial-intelligence/guidance-on-ai-and-data-protection/70\n954: 71\n955: 112 61 63\n956: 213 14 23 24\n957: 3 5 616 29 42 43\n958: 410 65 67\n959: 7\n960: 859 60\n961: 962\n962: 11\n963: 15 20 28\n964: 17 21\n965: 18\n966: 19\n967: 22\n968: 15\n969: --- PAGE 16 ---\n970: https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/tutorials/devstral-2\n971: https://unsloth.ai/docs/models/tutorials/devstral-2\n972: https://cloud.google.com/products/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/pricing\n973: https://cloud.google.com/products/gemini-enterprise-agent-platform/pricing\n974: https://cloud.google.com/products/compute/pricing/accelerator-optimized\n975: https://cloud.google.com/products/compute/pricing/accelerator-optimized\n976: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/deployment/cloud-deployments\n977: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/deployment/cloud-deployments\n978: https://docs.vllm.ai/en/latest/models/supported_models.html\n979: https://docs.vllm.ai/en/latest/models/supported_models.html\n980: https://docs.sglang.ai/basic_usage/openai_api_completions.html\n981: https://docs.sglang.ai/basic_usage/openai_api_completions.html\n982: https://docs.sglang.ai/advanced_features/quantization.html\n983: https://docs.sglang.ai/advanced_features/quantization.html\n984: https://ollama.com/library/devstral-small-2\n985: https://ollama.com/library/devstral-small-2\n986: https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Mistral-Medium-3.5-128B-GGUF\n987: https://huggingface.co/unsloth/Mistral-Medium-3.5-128B-GGUF\n988: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Balance/Concepts/load_balancer_types.htm\n989: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Balance/Concepts/load_balancer_types.htm\n990: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/\n991: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/\n992: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/graphics-rendering-nvidia-a10-gpu-oci\n993: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/graphics-rendering-nvidia-a10-gpu-oci\n994: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/ga-compute-nvidia-l40s-gpu-ai-omniverse\n995: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/ga-compute-nvidia-l40s-gpu-ai-omniverse\n996: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/now-ga-largest-ai-supercomputer-oci-nvidia-h200\n997: https://blogs.oracle.com/cloud-infrastructure/now-ga-largest-ai-supercomputer-oci-nvidia-h200\n998: https://lambda.ai/pricing\n999: https://lambda.ai/pricing\n1000: https://www.hyperstack.cloud/gpu-pricing\n1001: https://www.hyperstack.cloud/gpu-pricing\n1002: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/sizes/gpu-accelerated/nc-family\n1003: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/virtual-machines/sizes/gpu-accelerated/nc-family\n1004: https://www.oracle.com/apac/a/ocom/docs/cloud/accelerate-ai-with-oci-supercluster-apac.pdf\n1005: https://www.oracle.com/apac/a/ocom/docs/cloud/accelerate-ai-with-oci-supercluster-apac.pdf\n1006: https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/g6/\n1007: https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/instance-types/g6/25 36\n1008: 26 49 50\n1009: 27 48 57\n1010: 30\n1011: 31 32\n1012: 33 41\n1013: 34\n1014: 35\n1015: 37\n1016: 38 40\n1017: 39\n1018: 44 66\n1019: 45\n1020: 46 47\n1021: 51 58\n1022: 52\n1023: 53\n1024: 54\n1025: 55\n1026: 16\n1027: --- PAGE 17 ---\n1028: https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/blog/choose-the-right-size-for-your-workload-with-nvads-a10-v5-\n1029: virtual-machines-now-generally-available/\n1030: https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/blog/choose-the-right-size-for-your-workload-with-nvads-a10-v5-virtual-machines-now-\n1031: generally-available/\n1032: https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/media-centre/news-and-blogs/2024/11/thinking-of-using-ai-to-\n1033: assist-recruitment-our-key-data-protection-considerations/\n1034: https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/media-centre/news-and-blogs/2024/11/thinking-of-using-ai-to-assist-recruitment-our-key-data-\n1035: protection-considerations/\n1036: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/devstral-small-2-25-12\n1037: https://docs.mistral.ai/models/model-cards/devstral-small-2-25-12\n1038: https://help.mistral.ai/en/articles/347393-under-which-license-are-mistral-s-open-models-available\n1039: https://help.mistral.ai/en/articles/347393-under-which-license-are-mistral-s-open-models-available56 70\n1040: 64 69\n1041: 68\n1042: 71\n1043: 17\n\n(End of file - total 1043 lines)\n</content>",
