    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\oracle_linux_lxd.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\oracle_linux_lxd.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: The Solopreneur's Kernel: What Oracle Linux, LXD, and the LXD\n4: Web UI Actually Unlock\n5: An Architecture Decision Record for One-Person Infrastructure\n6: Preamble: The Problem With Being Alone\n7: There is a speciﬁc kind of cognitive trap that catches every solopreneur who tries to build serious\n8: infrastructure. You understand the goal clearly. You understand the components individually.\n9: But at the moment when you need to reason about the whole thing — the way one part fails and\n10: cascades into another, the way a Tuesday morning software update on one container can corrupt\n11: the runtime of a container two layers away, the way your Always Free budget is consumed not by\n12: one big thing but by ten small ineﬃciencies compounding — you ﬁnd that there is nobody to\n13: call.\n14: In a team, this is the Systems Architect's job. The Systems Architect sits between the code and\n15: the hardware, between the developer's optimism and the production environment's\n16: indiﬀerence. The Systems Architect maintains the mental model of the whole.\n17: As a solopreneur, you are the Systems Architect. And the question is whether your infrastructure\n18: supports that role or ﬁghts it.\n19: Oracle Linux with LXD, combined with the LXD Web UI and the Oracle Autonomous Database\n20: stack already documented in ADR-001 through ADR-009, is the answer to that question. It is not\n21: merely a collection of tools. It is the architecture of a one-person operations team.\n22: This document makes that case using the same ADR reasoning discipline applied to the previous\n23: technical decisions — because the discipline is as important as the content. When you are alone\n24: and something breaks at 2:00 AM, the ADR is the artefact that tells you why you made the\n25: choices you made, and therefore which choices you are allowed to change and which ones you\n26: must not.\n27: The Argument in One Paragraph\n28: Oracle Linux on OCI Always Free is not just an operating system. It is the host kernel for a\n29: virtualisation layer (LXD) that gives a single person the same operational capabilities as a\n30: Platform Engineering team: container isolation, VM-level security boundaries, live snapshotting,\n31: network bridging, storage pools, resource capping, and a graphical management UI that turns a\n32: terminal-only discipline into a visual, auditable, zero-installation management surface. When\n33: these capabilities are combined with an Oracle Autonomous Database that manages its own\n34: patching, its own backups, and its own job orchestration, the result is an infrastructure that a\n35: solopreneur can run without a DevOps team, without a DBA, without a Platform Engineer, and\n36: without burning their Always Free compute budget on management overhead. What they have\n37: --- PAGE 2 ---\n38: left — the full allocation of 4 OCPUs and 24GB RAM — is available exclusively for the value-\n39: generating workloads: Gemma 4 inference, Open WebUI, the Python middleware, and the ORDS\n40: API layer.\n41: ADR-010: Oracle Linux 8/9 as the Sovereign Host Operating System\n42: Date: 2026-05-18\n43: Status: Accepted\n44: Decision Level: Infrastructure Foundation — Aﬀects All Components\n45: Context\n46: The host operating system is the substrate on which everything else runs. On OCI Always Free\n47: ARM Ampere A1 instances, Oracle provides several OS images at no cost: Oracle Linux 8, Oracle\n48: Linux 9, Ubuntu 22.04, Ubuntu 24.04, and CentOS Stream 9. The choice determines: (a) the\n49: kernel features available to LXD; (b) the package ecosystem available for software installation;\n50: (c) the long-term support timeline; (d) the alignment with Oracle Autonomous Database's own\n51: Linux kernel, which matters for ONNX model loading paths, OML4Py connectivity, and network\n52: driver compatibility.\n53: The practical matter for a solopreneur is not which OS is theoretically superior. The practical\n54: matter is: which OS creates the least friction when something goes wrong? Friction, at 2:00 AM\n55: when a container has lost its network bridge and the Ollama endpoint is unreachable, is\n56: measured in minutes of searching documentation, following conﬂicting Stack Overﬂow answers,\n57: and trying patches that work on Ubuntu but silently fail on ARM.\n58: Oracle Linux 9 is built on Red Hat Enterprise Linux 9 sources. It ships with the UEK\n59: (Unbreakable Enterprise Kernel) — a Linux kernel maintained by Oracle with speciﬁc\n60: optimisations for OCI hardware, including the Ampere A1's ARM Neoverse N1 cores. The UEK\n61: ships with io_uring support enabled by default, which beneﬁts Ollama's asynchronous I/O\n62: patterns; with cgroup v2 fully implemented, which LXD requires for resource capping; and\n63: with virtiofs and 9p ﬁlesystem drivers that LXD uses for container-to-host storage sharing.\n64: Beyond the kernel, the alignment argument is compelling: Oracle Linux is the OS on which\n65: Oracle Database 23ai was tested and certiﬁed. When the ONNX model loading pathway, the\n66: Oracle Instant Client driver, and the OML4Py Python runtime all need to talk to each other, every\n67: one of those communication paths was tested by Oracle's own engineers on Oracle Linux. That is\n68: not nothing, when you are a solopreneur and the alternative is discovering at 11:00 PM that an\n69: Ubuntu glibc version mismatch has broken the OML4Py embedding function.\n70: Decision\n71: We will run Oracle Linux 9 with the Unbreakable Enterprise Kernel (UEK) on all OCI Always\n72: Free ARM instances. No third-party OS will be used on the compute layer.\n73: Key conﬁgurations at the OS level:\n74: --- PAGE 3 ---\n75: cgroup v2 enabled (default in UEK r7+, required for LXD resource capping)\n76: HugePages conﬁgured at 2MB granularity for the Gemma 4 inference container's memory\n77: space, reducing TLB misses during weight matrix access\n78: vm.swappiness = 10 — the kernel will defer swap use as long as physically possible,\n79: keeping model weights in RAM\n80: firewalld disabled, replaced by OCI VCN Security Lists and a host-level nftables\n81: ruleset managed by LXD's own network bridge rules\n82: Oracle Instant Client 23ai installed at the OS level, available to all LXD containers via a\n83: shared bind mount, eliminating duplicate installation\n84: dnf-automatic security-only updates enabled and scheduled outside peak inference\n85: hours\n86: Alternatives Considered\n87: Ubuntu 24.04: The most popular Linux distribution for cloud deployments. Rejected because:\n88: (a) glibc version diﬀerences occasionally cause friction with Oracle Instant Client and OML4Py;\n89: (b) Ubuntu's kernel does not include Oracle's UEK optimisations for OCI hardware; (c) Ubuntu's\n90: systemd-resolved DNS management conﬂicts with LXD's internal DNS bridge on some OCI\n91: network conﬁgurations.\n92: CentOS Stream 9: Rolling release model means the base OS is always in a state of transition.\n93: Unacceptable for a solopreneur infrastructure where the operator cannot aﬀord the cognitive\n94: overhead of tracking upstream RHEL changes.\n95: Oracle Linux 9 (chosen): Chosen for hardware alignment, Oracle software certiﬁcation, UEK\n96: kernel features, and long-term support timeline (until 2032).\n97: Consequences\n98: Positive: Every Oracle-published deployment guide, troubleshooting document, and known-\n99: issue article is written for Oracle Linux. When LXD's network bridge exhibits an unexpected\n100: behaviour, the OCI documentation and the Oracle Support knowledge base are the most relevant\n101: resources. The alignment eliminates an entire category of \"works on Ubuntu but not here\"\n102: debugging sessions.\n103: Negative: Oracle Linux has a smaller community footprint than Ubuntu for general-purpose\n104: Linux problems. Non-Oracle software (Terraform, Ansible, Node.js tools) has excellent Oracle\n105: Linux 9 / RHEL 9 support, but the community size diﬀerence is noticeable when searching for\n106: edge-case solutions. The mitigation is that the UEK is well-documented, and the core workloads\n107: (LXD, Ollama, Python) all have RHEL 9 packages.\n108: ADR-011: LXD as the Container and VM Orchestration Layer\n109: Date: 2026-05-18\n110: Status: Accepted\n111: --- PAGE 4 ---\n112: Decision Level: Infrastructure — Aﬀects All Workloads\n113: Context\n114: Here is the solopreneur's dilemma in infrastructure, stated plainly.\n115: Docker containers are simple to start and simple to reason about for individual services. But\n116: Docker does not give you full OS-level isolation; it shares the host kernel. If a container process\n117: triggers a kernel bug, it can aﬀect every other container. Docker Compose gives you multi-\n118: container orchestration, but its networking model is limited: every container is in the same\n119: network namespace unless you conﬁgure explicit overrides, which means a compromised\n120: container can reach every other container's internal ports. Docker has no native VM support, no\n121: live migration, no snapshot-and-restore, and no graphical management UI that a solopreneur can\n122: use to see the whole system in one view.\n123: Kubernetes gives you everything Docker lacks plus horizontal scaling, self-healing pod\n124: management, and a rich ecosystem. But Kubernetes requires a minimum of three nodes for a\n125: production-grade cluster and a dedicated operations person to manage it. A solopreneur running\n126: Kubernetes on OCI Always Free is spending more compute on the cluster control plane than on\n127: the actual workloads.\n128: LXD is the correct abstraction for a solopreneur running a production AI stack on OCI Always\n129: Free. It is not Docker and it is not Kubernetes. It occupies a diﬀerent position in the taxonomy: a\n130: system container and VM manager that provides:\n131: System containers (OS-level isolation): Each LXD container runs its own init system (systemd),\n132: its own process namespace, its own network interface, its own ﬁlesystem, and its own user\n133: namespace. A process inside the Gemma 4 container cannot see — let alone aﬀect — a process\n134: inside the Open WebUI container. This is kernel-enforced isolation, not Docker's process-level\n135: isolation.\n136: Virtual machines: LXD can run full VMs (using KVM/QEMU under the hood) on the same host\n137: as system containers. For workloads that require a diﬀerent kernel version or Windows\n138: compatibility, LXD VMs are available without changing the management model.\n139: Proﬁles: LXD proﬁles are reusable conﬁguration templates. A gpu-ready proﬁle, a memory-\n140: limited proﬁle, a shared-db-client proﬁle — these are deﬁned once and applied to any\n141: container. When you provision a new client environment, you apply the pre-tested proﬁle rather\n142: than typing raw conﬁguration commands.\n143: Storage pools: LXD manages storage at the pool level. The default pool on an OCI boot volume\n144: can be ZFS or btrfs (both supported on Oracle Linux 9 with UEK). ZFS copy-on-write semantics\n145: mean that snapshotting a container before a software update takes milliseconds and consumes\n146: no additional disk space until the snapshot diverges from the live state. For a solopreneur, this\n147: means: snapshot before every potentially breaking operation, and rollback in seconds if the\n148: operation breaks something.\n149: Network bridges: LXD creates a lxdbr0 bridge by default, with its own DHCP server and DNS\n150: resolver. Every container gets a stable hostname (e.g., gemma.lxd, openwebui.lxd,\n151: --- PAGE 5 ---\n152: middleware.lxd) resolvable from the host and from other containers. No manual IP\n153: conﬁguration is required. No /etc/hosts editing. The network topology is deﬁned declaratively\n154: in LXD proﬁles.\n155: For the Sovereign AI Stack, the container topology is:\n156: Container Name Purpose Memory\n157: CapCPU\n158: CapNetwork\n159: gemma4 Ollama inference server\n160: (Gemma 4 GGUF)16GB 3 OCPUlxdbr0, internal only\n161: openwebui Open WebUI interface +\n162: Python middleware4GB 0.5\n163: OCPUlxdbr0 + host port\n164: 3000\n165: oracle-clientORDS calls, OML4Py scripts,\n166: Ansible targets2GB 0.25\n167: OCPUlxdbr0, outbound to\n168: OCI DB endpoint\n169: cloudflare-\n170: tunnelCloudﬂared daemon,\n171: exposes ORDS/WebUI512MB0.1\n172: OCPUlxdbr0 + external\n173: This topology means the public internet never reaches gemma4 directly. Requests arrive at\n174: Cloudﬂare's edge, pass through the Cloudﬂare Tunnel daemon in the cloudflare-tunnel\n175: container, hit the openwebui container's Python middleware, which assembles the prompt, calls\n176: gemma4 over the internal lxdbr0 bridge, and returns the result back through the same path.\n177: The Gemma 4 model server is, at the network level, invisible to the outside world.\n178: Decision\n179: We will use LXD 5.x (LTS channel) on Oracle Linux 9 as the sole container and VM\n180: orchestration layer. Docker will not be installed on the host system. All workloads will run as\n181: LXD system containers or LXD VMs.\n182: The LXD storage pool will use ZFS on the OCI boot volume block device, providing copy-on-\n183: write snapshots for pre-update protection. ZFS's ARC (Adaptive Replacement Cache) will be\n184: capped at 2GB to prevent it from competing with the Gemma 4 inference memory allocation.\n185: Three proﬁles will be deﬁned at setup:\n186: base: Oracle Linux 9 base image, Oracle Instant Client bind mount, nftables rules, NTP\n187: sync\n188: inference: extends base, adds limits.memory = 16GB, limits.cpu = 3, ONNX\n189: runtime libs\n190: service: extends base, adds limits.memory = 4GB, limits.cpu = 0.5, port proxy\n191: rules\n192: Alternatives Considered\n193: --- PAGE 6 ---\n194: Docker + Docker Compose: Rejected for the isolation, snapshotting, and networking reasons\n195: described in the Context. Docker's process-level isolation is insuﬃcient for a multi-tenant SaaS\n196: model where client data must be cryptographically separated at the OS level.\n197: Podman + systemd containers: A strong alternative to Docker on RHEL-based systems.\n198: Rejected because LXD's system container model provides stronger isolation guarantees than\n199: Podman rootless containers for the multi-tenant case, and LXD's proﬁle system and Web UI\n200: (ADR-012) are signiﬁcantly more suited to solopreneur management.\n201: Kata Containers: VM-in-container model providing strong isolation. Rejected because the\n202: performance overhead on the Ampere A1 is incompatible with the inference latency\n203: requirements, and the tooling complexity is inappropriate for a solopreneur.\n204: LXD (chosen): The only option that combines OS-level isolation, VM support, ZFS snapshots,\n205: proﬁle-based multi-tenancy, and a graphical management UI in a single zero-additional-cost\n206: package on OCI Always Free.\n207: Consequences\n208: Positive: The solopreneur gains a capability that is otherwise only available on dedicated bare-\n209: metal infrastructure: the ability to snapshot the entire system state before a risky operation, roll\n210: back to that snapshot in under ten seconds if the operation fails, and do so without any data loss\n211: or service disruption. This single capability eliminates the largest class of \"I've broken it and I\n212: can't get back\" incidents that make solopreneur infrastructure so stressful.\n213: Negative: LXD has a steeper initial learning curve than Docker. The lxc command-line\n214: interface is powerful but unfamiliar to developers who have spent years with docker. The\n215: mitigation is the LXD Web UI (ADR-012), which makes the most common operations visual, and\n216: the investment in learning LXD's model is repaid many times over in operational resilience.\n217: On the multi-tenancy business model: When a new client is onboarded, a new LXD container is\n218: provisioned using the base proﬁle, connected to a dedicated LXD network bridge (isolated from\n219: other clients' bridges), and given its own Oracle Autonomous Database schema. The\n220: provisioning takes under ﬁve minutes using the Ansible playbook. Each client's data is isolated at\n221: the OS kernel level — they cannot reach each other's containers even if both are running on the\n222: same OCI instance. This is the technical foundation of the \"Never-Learned-From\" guarantee.\n223: ADR-012: The LXD Web UI as the Solopreneur's Operations Centre\n224: Date: 2026-05-18\n225: Status: Accepted\n226: Decision Level: Operations — Aﬀects Operator Experience\n227: Context\n228: There is an assumption baked into most infrastructure documentation that the person reading it\n229: is a specialist. The assumption is that you know what lxc launch ubuntu:22.04 mycontainer\n230: --- PAGE 7 ---\n231: does, that you can read a cgroups v2 hierarchy without squinting, that you understand why\n232: lxdbr0 has its own DHCP scope and what happens if you accidentally delete it.\n233: A solopreneur with a primary product to build and clients to serve cannot be a full-time LXD\n234: specialist. The cognitive overhead of a purely terminal-based infrastructure management\n235: discipline — remembering command syntax, mentally tracking which containers are running,\n236: manually correlating CPU usage with inference latency — is overhead stolen from the work that\n237: generates revenue.\n238: The LXD Web UI is LXD's oﬃcial browser-based management interface, introduced with LXD\n239: 5.x and accessible at https://your-oci-instance-ip:8443 after a single lxc config set\n240: core.https_address ... command. It does not require a separate installation, a separate\n241: service, or a separate compute allocation. It is built into the LXD daemon.\n242: What it provides that a terminal cannot:\n243: Visual Container Topology: A single screen showing all running containers, their status, their\n244: CPU utilisation, their memory consumption, and their network addresses. The mental model of\n245: \"what is running and what state is it in\" becomes a ﬁve-second visual scan rather than a\n246: sequence of lxc list, lxc info, and lxc monitor commands.\n247: Snapshot Management: The LXD Web UI shows all snapshots for a container, their creation\n248: times, their sizes, and provides one-click restore. For a solopreneur preparing to apply a\n249: potentially breaking update to the gemma4 container, the workﬂow is: open the Web UI, click\n250: \"Create Snapshot,\" give it a name (before-gemma-4.1-update), apply the update, test it, and if it\n251: fails, click \"Restore\" from the snapshot list. Total time for the snapshot/restore cycle:\n252: approximately ﬁfteen seconds.\n253: Resource Cap Visualisation: The Web UI shows each container's memory limit and CPU limit as\n254: conﬁgured in its proﬁle, alongside its current consumption. This is the visual equivalent of\n255: asking \"is my Always Free budget being used eﬃciently?\" without running lxc info on each\n256: container and doing the arithmetic manually.\n257: Network Bridge Management: The Web UI shows all LXD network bridges, their DHCP ranges,\n258: their DNS conﬁgurations, and which containers are attached to which bridge. For the multi-\n259: tenant client isolation model, this is the visual audit tool that conﬁrms no two clients' containers\n260: are on the same bridge.\n261: Storage Pool and Volume Management: ZFS storage pools, individual container disk\n262: allocations, and snapshot space consumption are all visible in the Web UI. For a solopreneur\n263: managing a growing knowledge base, watching the PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE volume grow\n264: over time is an early warning system for approaching the 20GB Always Free storage ceiling.\n265: Terminal Access: The Web UI provides a browser-based terminal into any running container.\n266: For a solopreneur working from a mobile device, a tablet, or a customer's machine, the ability to\n267: open a browser, navigate to the LXD Web UI, and get a terminal into the gemma4 container\n268: without installing an SSH client is not a convenience — it is a genuine operational capability that\n269: a terminal-only discipline cannot match.\n270: --- PAGE 8 ---\n271: Decision\n272: We will enable and expose the LXD Web UI on a non-default port, secured with a client\n273: certiﬁcate generated at setup and stored in the operator's password manager. The Web UI will\n274: not be publicly accessible; it will be reachable only via the Cloudﬂare Tunnel's split tunneling\n275: conﬁguration or via SSH port forwarding.\n276: The LXD Web UI will be the primary operational interface for:\n277: Monitoring container health and resource consumption\n278: Creating and restoring snapshots before any update operation\n279: Auditing client isolation (network bridge assignments)\n280: Storage pool monitoring\n281: Emergency container terminal access from any device\n282: The lxc CLI will remain available for scripted operations (Ansible playbooks,\n283: DBMS_SCHEDULER shell script steps) but will not be the primary human interface.\n284: Alternatives Considered\n285: Portainer: Docker-focused management UI. Does not support LXD. Irrelevant to this\n286: architecture.\n287: Cockpit with cockpit-machines: A capable RHEL system management UI with VM\n288: management via libvirt. Does not have native LXD support. Requires a separate installation and\n289: compute overhead.\n290: Terminal only: The discipline of a senior infrastructure engineer. Not the discipline of a\n291: solopreneur building a product and serving clients simultaneously. The cognitive overhead is an\n292: unacceptable tax.\n293: LXD Web UI (chosen): Built into the LXD daemon, zero additional compute cost, full container\n294: and VM management capability, browser-based terminal access, and snapshot management. For\n295: a solopreneur, the question is not \"is this the most powerful tool?\" but \"does this give me the\n296: operational visibility I need with the least possible cognitive overhead?\" The LXD Web UI\n297: answers yes on both counts.\n298: Consequences\n299: Positive: The solopreneur can perform a complete health check of the entire infrastructure — all\n300: containers, their resource usage, their network assignments, their snapshot state — in under two\n301: minutes, from any device with a browser. This makes the diﬀerence between an infrastructure\n302: that is understood and an infrastructure that is feared.\n303: Negative: The LXD Web UI is a relatively new interface (LXD 5.x, 2023 onwards). Some advanced\n304: LXD operations (complex proﬁle inheritance, cluster node management) are not yet available in\n305: the Web UI and require the CLI. For this stack's use case — single-node, multi-container — the\n306: Web UI covers 95% of the operations the solopreneur will need.\n307: --- PAGE 9 ---\n308: ADR-013: LXD Proﬁles as Terraform for the Solopreneur\n309: Date: 2026-05-18\n310: Status: Accepted\n311: Decision Level: Infrastructure Automation — Aﬀects Onboarding Speed\n312: Context\n313: The multi-tenant business model described in the main ADR suite requires that a new client\n314: environment be provisioned in minutes, not days. The provision of a new client environment\n315: means: a new LXD container, a new LXD network bridge, a new Oracle Autonomous Database\n316: schema, a new ORDS endpoint preﬁx, a new Open WebUI workspace, and a new Cloudﬂare\n317: Tunnel subdomain.\n318: Terraform and Ansible are the standard tools for this. They are the right tools for the job. But\n319: their learning curve and their operational overhead — maintaining Terraform state ﬁles,\n320: managing Ansible inventory, debugging idempotency issues — are non-trivial for a solopreneur\n321: in the ﬁrst months of building the business.\n322: LXD proﬁles ﬁll the gap between \"clicking through a UI every time\" and \"maintaining a full\n323: Terraform codebase.\" A proﬁle is a named, reusable conﬁguration object stored in the LXD\n324: database. It speciﬁes a container's memory limits, CPU limits, storage root size, network\n325: attachments, and bind mounts. Launching a new client container is:\n326: That command creates a new container with exactly the conﬁguration deﬁned in the base and\n327: service proﬁles — the right Oracle Instant Client bind mount, the right memory cap, the right\n328: network bridge assignment, the right DNS suﬃx. It is not \"Infrastructure as Code\" in the\n329: Terraform sense; it is \"Infrastructure as Conﬁguration\" in the LXD sense. And for a solopreneur\n330: at launch stage, Conﬁguration beats Code on the operational complexity curve.\n331: The evolution path is explicit: once the client base grows beyond ten, the Ansible playbook\n332: (which wraps lxc launch with the correct proﬁle arguments) becomes the primary\n333: provisioning tool, and Terraform codiﬁes the OCI resource layer. The LXD proﬁle discipline\n334: makes this transition smooth: the proﬁles become the Ansible role speciﬁcations, and the\n335: Ansible inventory becomes the source of truth for client environments.\n336: Decision\n337: We will deﬁne ﬁve LXD proﬁles at the Oracle Linux host level, stored in the LXD database and\n338: visible in the LXD Web UI:\n339: base: Shared conﬁguration applied to every container. Contains:bash\n340: lxc launch ubuntu-minimal:24.04 client-acme --profile base --profile service\n341: --- PAGE 10 ---\n342: Oracle Linux 9 minimal image\n343: Oracle Instant Client 23ai bind mount from host /opt/oracle/instantclient\n344: NTP sync conﬁguration\n345: nftables default deny inbound ruleset\n346: DNS search domain .lxd\n347: inference: The Gemma 4 inference proﬁle. Extends base:\n348: limits.memory = 16GB\n349: limits.cpu = 3\n350: ONNX runtime library bind mount\n351: Ollama data directory at /var/lib/ollama (mapped to ZFS dataset)\n352: No external port proxy (inference is internal only)\n353: service: The Open WebUI / middleware proﬁle. Extends base:\n354: limits.memory = 4GB\n355: limits.cpu = 0.5\n356: Port proxy: host port 3000 → container port 3000 (Open WebUI)\n357: Port proxy: host port 8080 → container port 8080 (middleware API)\n358: oracle-client: The DB connectivity proﬁle. Extends base:\n359: limits.memory = 2GB\n360: limits.cpu = 0.25\n361: Oracle tnsnames.ora and wallet bind mounts for mTLS to Autonomous Database\n362: tunnel: The Cloudﬂare Tunnel proﬁle. Extends base:\n363: limits.memory = 512MB\n364: limits.cpu = 0.1\n365: External network interface (host bridged, not lxdbr0)\n366: Cloudﬂared conﬁg bind mount\n367: Consequences\n368: Positive: A new client environment is a three-command operation: create the client network\n369: bridge, launch the container with the appropriate proﬁles, create the Oracle DB schema. The LXD\n370: Web UI shows the result immediately. No Terraform state management required at this stage.\n371: Negative: Proﬁles do not manage Oracle-side provisioning (schema creation, ORDS endpoint\n372: registration, wallet generation). These steps require either manual SQL execution or an Ansible\n373: playbook task. At the ﬁve-client scale, manual is acceptable. At the twenty-client scale, the\n374: Ansible playbook becomes non-optional.\n375: --- PAGE 11 ---\n376: ADR-014: ZFS Snapshots as the Solopreneur's Insurance Policy\n377: Date: 2026-05-18\n378: Status: Accepted\n379: Decision Level: Risk Management — Aﬀects All Components\n380: Context\n381: The single most stressful moment in solopreneur infrastructure management is the moment\n382: immediately after a change that has broken something you don't immediately understand. The\n383: Gemma 4 container is no longer responding. The Open WebUI interface is returning 502s. The\n384: Oracle ORDS endpoint is timing out. And you do not know whether the cause is the update you\n385: applied ﬁve minutes ago, the conﬁguration change you made this morning, or something that\n386: was silently wrong for three days and only became visible now.\n387: In a team environment, this is the post-incident review. In a solopreneur environment, this is\n388: Tuesday.\n389: ZFS snapshots, enabled by LXD's ZFS storage pool backend, are the technical solution to this\n390: problem. A ZFS snapshot is an instantaneous, copy-on-write record of a container's complete\n391: ﬁlesystem state at a point in time. It consumes no additional disk space at the moment of creation\n392: — only the blocks that subsequently change are written to disk. Restoring from a snapshot\n393: returns the container to its exact state at the snapshot moment in under ten seconds, regardless\n394: of how much has changed since.\n395: The operational protocol is simple:\n396: 1. Before any potentially breaking change (model update, conﬁguration change, dependency\n397: upgrade, database schema migration), create a named LXD snapshot: lxc snapshot\n398: gemma4 before-ollama-update.\n399: 2. Apply the change.\n400: 3. Test the change.\n401: 4. If the test passes, delete the snapshot (free the disk space): lxc delete gemma4/before-\n402: ollama-update.\n403: 5. If the test fails, restore the snapshot: lxc restore gemma4 before-ollama-update.\n404: This is the solopreneur's equivalent of a staging environment. You do not need a separate\n405: \"staging\" OCI instance consuming Always Free budget. You snapshot, change, verify, and either\n406: commit or rollback. The LXD Web UI makes steps 1 and 5 a single mouse click.\n407: The business-critical implication: a client's AI environment can be snapshotted before a\n408: knowledge graph refresh (ADR-004's Librarian and Judge steps). If the refresh introduces an\n409: error — a malformed pipe-delimited index, a broken ORDS endpoint, a projection weight\n410: corruption — the entire client environment can be restored to pre-refresh state in seconds, with\n411: no client-visible downtime and no data loss.\n412: --- PAGE 12 ---\n413: Decision\n414: We will implement automated pre-operation snapshots via a DBMS_SCHEDULER shell script\n415: step that runs before every SOVEREIGN_PIPELINE chain execution. The snapshot will be\n416: named with the timestamp and the chain step name: lxc snapshot gemma4 pre-\n417: pipeline-$(date +%Y%m%d%H%M).\n418: Snapshot retention policy:\n419: Pre-pipeline snapshots: retained for 48 hours, then automatically deleted\n420: Manual snapshots (before software updates): retained until manually deleted\n421: Weekly baseline snapshots: retained for 30 days\n422: All snapshots are visible in the LXD Web UI.\n423: Consequences\n424: Positive: The operational risk of any change is bounded. \"I can always roll back\" is not a hope; it is\n425: a technical guarantee, enforced by the ZFS copy-on-write ﬁlesystem and the LXD snapshot API.\n426: The solopreneur can move faster and with less anxiety because the safety net is always in place.\n427: Negative: Snapshot retention consumes disk space on the OCI Always Free 20GB boot volume\n428: allocation. The 48-hour auto-deletion policy for pre-pipeline snapshots and the 30-day limit for\n429: weekly baselines are designed to keep the snapshot footprint below 5GB on a typical knowledge\n430: graph workload. If the knowledge base grows rapidly and the container's ZFS dataset diverges\n431: signiﬁcantly from the snapshot baseline, snapshot storage can exceed this estimate.\n432: ADR-015: The Cloudﬂare Free Tier as the Solopreneur's Edge Network\n433: Date: 2026-05-18\n434: Status: Accepted\n435: Decision Level: Network Security — Aﬀects External Access\n436: Context\n437: The OCI Always Free ARM instance has a public IP address. That public IP, if exposed directly, is\n438: visible to the entire internet and is subject to port scans, brute-force SSH attempts, and DDoS\n439: traﬃc from the moment it is provisioned. A solopreneur cannot monitor this traﬃc continuously.\n440: The OCI VCN Security Lists provide basic ﬁrewall functionality, but they are stateless (they do\n441: not track connections) and they do not provide the DDoS mitigation, global TLS termination, or\n442: response caching that a production AI service requires.\n443: Cloudﬂare's free tier solves all three problems at zero cost via two mechanisms:\n444: Cloudﬂare Tunnel: A daemon (cloudflared) running inside a dedicated LXD container\n445: (tunnel) that establishes an outbound-only encrypted tunnel to Cloudﬂare's edge. The OCI\n446: instance's public IP is never exposed. Port 443 is not open on the OCI instance's VCN Security\n447: --- PAGE 13 ---\n448: List. All traﬃc arrives through the Cloudﬂare Tunnel, which the cloudflared daemon routes to\n449: the appropriate internal container (openwebui.lxd:3000 for the UI, oracle-client.lxd:8080\n450: for the ORDS API). The gemma4.lxd container receives no direct external traﬃc.\n451: Cloudﬂare WAF + DDoS (free tier): Traﬃc arriving at ai.yourdomain.com passes through\n452: Cloudﬂare's global anycast network before reaching the Tunnel. Common attack patterns (SQL\n453: injection in URL parameters, large-payload POST ﬂoods, bot scraping) are blocked at\n454: Cloudﬂare's edge, before they consume OCI compute. For a solopreneur with a single Always\n455: Free instance, this is meaningful: a DDoS attack that would saturate the 4GB network bandwidth\n456: ceiling of the instance is absorbed by Cloudﬂare's global infrastructure.\n457: Response Caching: Static ORDS responses — the 8KB Working Memory Map endpoint, the\n458: Golden Set evaluation trigger, the Coherence Index dashboard data — can be cached at\n459: Cloudﬂare's edge with appropriate cache headers. A client in Tokyo requesting the Working\n460: Memory Map does not incur a round-trip to Manchester or wherever the OCI instance is located;\n461: they receive the cached response from the nearest Cloudﬂare PoP in under 5ms.\n462: The cloudflare-tunnel LXD container is the only container with an external network\n463: interface. All other containers are on the internal lxdbr0 bridge. The network topology is\n464: strictly layered: internet → Cloudﬂare edge → Tunnel → lxdbr0 bridge → destination container.\n465: There is no path from the internet to gemma4.lxd that does not traverse all four layers.\n466: Decision\n467: We will use Cloudﬂare Tunnel (free tier) for all external access to the Sovereign AI Stack. No\n468: service on the OCI instance will have a direct public IP port open except SSH (restricted to the\n469: operator's IP range via VCN Security List).\n470: The DNS for ai.yourdomain.com and api.yourdomain.com will be managed via Cloudﬂare\n471: DNS. The cloudflared daemon will run inside the tunnel LXD container, limited to 512MB\n472: RAM and 0.1 OCPU (see ADR-013's tunnel proﬁle).\n473: Consequences\n474: Positive: The attack surface of the OCI instance is reduced to the SSH port. All application traﬃc\n475: is mediated by Cloudﬂare's edge, providing DDoS protection, WAF ﬁltering, TLS termination,\n476: and response caching at zero cost. The Gemma 4 model server is completely invisible to the\n477: internet.\n478: Negative: Cloudﬂare Tunnel introduces a dependency on Cloudﬂare's availability. If Cloudﬂare\n479: experiences an outage, the application is unreachable from the public internet. The mitigation is\n480: that the application remains fully functional for internal use (the operator can reach all\n481: containers via the lxdbr0 bridge directly, and Gemma 4 inference continues uninterrupted).\n482: The Oracle Autonomous Database is unaﬀected by Cloudﬂare availability.\n483: --- PAGE 14 ---\n484: The Whole Picture: What a Solopreneur Actually Has\n485: Let us step back from the individual ADRs and look at what the complete Oracle Linux + LXD +\n486: LXD Web UI stack actually gives a single person.\n487: It gives them, in operational terms, something that has no name in the standard cloud\n488: infrastructure taxonomy. It is not a Developer Environment. It is not a Production Cluster. It is\n489: not a Staging Platform. It is a Sovereign Compute Mainframe — a single-node infrastructure\n490: that provides enterprise-grade operational capabilities (isolation, snapshotting, resource\n491: capping, visual management, edge security) at zero cost, managed by one person via a browser-\n492: based UI.\n493: The Kahneman framing is useful here. Infrastructure management, when done badly, is pure\n494: System 2 work: constant eﬀortful deliberation about what is running, what state it is in, whether\n495: the change you just made broke something, whether the client data is correctly isolated. Every\n496: lxc list you run instead of looking at a dashboard is a System 2 tax. Every manual rollback\n497: you attempt by re-typing conﬁguration commands instead of clicking \"Restore Snapshot\" is a\n498: System 2 tax.\n499: The LXD Web UI, the ZFS snapshot discipline, the proﬁle-based multi-tenancy, and the\n500: Cloudﬂare Tunnel collectively convert infrastructure management from primarily System 2\n501: work to primarily System 1 work. The status of the system is visible at a glance. The recovery\n502: from a bad change is a single click. The onboarding of a new client is a three-command sequence\n503: backed by pre-tested proﬁles. The external attack surface is invisible.\n504: What the solopreneur has left — their System 2 capacity — is available for the things that only a\n505: human can do: understanding a client's domain deeply enough to curate the right Golden Set,\n506: designing the Coherence Index thresholds that are meaningful for a speciﬁc business context,\n507: writing the AGENTS.md index precisely enough that Gemma 4 navigates the knowledge graph\n508: at 100% pass rate rather than 53%.\n509: The infrastructure does not need to be thought about. It runs. When it requires attention, the\n510: LXD Web UI tells you where to look. When it needs to be recovered, the snapshot is waiting.\n511: That is the unlocking. Not raw computational power. Not global scale. But the operational\n512: freedom to stop managing infrastructure and start building intelligence.\n513: The Business Argument: What This Unlocks That Cloud Cannot\n514: There is a ﬁnal point that the ADR framework, with its technical rigour, cannot fully capture.\n515: The combination described in these records — Oracle Linux, LXD, the LXD Web UI, the ZFS\n516: snapshot discipline, the Cloudﬂare Tunnel, and the Oracle Autonomous Database — is not\n517: merely a cost-eﬀective substitute for a cloud-managed stack. It is structurally diﬀerent in a way\n518: that creates business advantages cloud cannot replicate.\n519: --- PAGE 15 ---\n520: When you run managed Kubernetes on AWS EKS and a client asks \"Where exactly is my data?\",\n521: the honest answer is: \"In AWS, in a region you speciﬁed, managed by AWS's infrastructure team,\n522: subject to AWS's terms of service and legal hold obligations.\" That answer is not a technical\n523: failure. It is the honest description of what managed cloud provides.\n524: When you run this stack and a client asks the same question, the honest answer is: \"In your\n525: Oracle Autonomous Database schema, on your OCI tenancy, processed by Gemma 4 running\n526: inside an LXD container on your OCI compute instance, with no external API calls made during\n527: ingestion or retrieval. The network traﬃc logs, which you can audit at any time, will show no\n528: outbound connections to any non-OCI endpoint during your data's processing lifecycle.\"\n529: That is a diﬀerent kind of answer. It is an answer that closes legal, compliance, and procurement\n530: conversations that cloud-managed stacks cannot close. GDPR Article 28 (processor agreements),\n531: ISO 27001 Annex A control 8.10 (information deletion), HIPAA's minimum necessary standard —\n532: all of these are easier to satisfy when the architecture's data boundary is a single OCI VCN rather\n533: than a distributed mesh of managed cloud services.\n534: The solopreneur who has built this stack is not competing with OpenAI or Google Vertex AI.\n535: They are occupying a diﬀerent market position: the provider of veriﬁable, auditable, technically\n536: sovereign AI infrastructure for organisations that cannot or will not use shared cloud AI services.\n537: That market is growing. The healthcare sector, the legal sector, the ﬁnancial services sector,\n538: public sector bodies in jurisdictions with data residency requirements — none of these\n539: organisations are going to route their most sensitive workloads through a shared cloud API.\n540: They need someone who has built the alternative. Oracle Linux. LXD. The Autonomous\n541: Database. The 8KB Working Memory Map. The Coherence Index. The Drift Management\n542: dashboard in APEX.\n543: One person can build and operate all of it.\n544: That is what Oracle Linux and LXD unlock. Not just infrastructure. The possibility of an entirely\n545: diﬀerent kind of AI business.\n546: This document constitutes Architecture Decision Records ADR-010 through ADR-015 in the\n547: Sovereign Intelligence Architecture series. All decisions are at the Infrastructure Foundation\n548: level per the GDS ADR Framework (GOV.UK, November 2025). Review scheduled alongside the\n549: main ADR suite, quarterly or on material change to OCI Always Free terms, LXD major version, or\n550: Oracle Linux kernel release.\n\n(End of file - total 550 lines)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
