      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\sovereign_ai_stack_v1.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\sovereign_ai_stack_v1.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: now reviewing the doc in files called: ChatGPT-quality\n4: interface but owns every byte of what runs behind it.\n5: …expand_more\n6: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n7: Yes, your plan is entirely feasible, but it requires a vital shift in how you think about \n8: Jan.\n9: Jan is traditionally built as a desktop client (Electron app). However, because you are\n10: leveraging an OCI Always Free ARM instance (Ampere A1 with 4 OCPUs and 24GB\n11: RAM), you cannot simply double-click an installer. Instead, you will run Jan's\n12: underlying inference engine (Nitro) and its core services in a headless server\n13: configuration inside an LXD container on OCI.\n14: You can absolutely import your exported ChatGPT and Claude data, rehydrate them,\n15: and have them appear as active chats and projects. To do this without running into \n16: Muda (the waste of massive token overhead and quadratic memory explosions), we\n17: cannot simply dump your entire history into the model's active window. We have to\n18: build an architecture where the database acts as a persistent, externalized KV cache.\n19: Below is the continuation of your documentation, structured as a new series of distinct\n20: .md files designed to turn your intuition into an executable blueprint for your stack.\n21: ARCHITECTURE_EVOLUTION.mdS\n22: # Architecture Evolution: Headless Jan + Oracle 23ai Sovereign Stack\n23: This document outlines the system topology for running a sovereign, multi-sour\n24:                       +------------------------------------------+\n25:                       |               User Browser               |Show thinkingexpand_more\n26: Markdown downloadcontent_copy\n27: --- PAGE 2 ---\n28: DATA_REHYDRATION_PIPELINE.md                      |          (Open WebUI / Jan App)          |\n29:                       +--------------------+---------------------+\n30:                                            | HTTPS / WebSockets\n31:                                            v\n32: +------------------------------------------+----------------------------------\n33: | OCI Always Free ARM Instance (Ampere A1: 4 OCPUs, 24GB RAM)                 \n34: |                                                                             \n35: |  +----------------------------------+      +--------------------------------\n36: |  | LXD Container 1: Headless Jan    |      | LXD Container 2: Oracle 23ai Fr\n37: |  |                                  |      |                                \n38: |  |  +----------------------------+  |      |  +-----------------------------\n39: |  |  | Jan Core / Nitro Engine    |  |      |  | Native Vector DB            \n40: |  |  | (Gemma 4 2B/4B via Ollama) |  |      |  | (Stores Chat History Vectors\n41: |  |  +--------------+-------------+  |      |  +---------------+-------------\n42: |  |                 ^                |      |                  ^             \n43: |  |                 | Token/Context  |      |                  | On-Disk Vect\n44: |  |                 v                |      |                  v             \n45: |  |  +--------------+-------------+  |      |  +---------------+-------------\n46: |  |  | API Gateway / Next-Token   |  |      |  | DBMS_VECTOR ONNX Model      \n47: |  |  | Speculative Decoder        |  |      |  | (Gemma 4 Embedding Weights) \n48: |  |  +--------------+-------------+  |      |  +---------------+-------------\n49: |  +-----------------|----------------+      +------------------|-------------\n50: |                    |                                          |             \n51: |                    +------------------ ORDS / PL/SQL ---------+             \n52: |                               (Zero-Muda Vector Routing)                    \n53: +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n54: ## 1. Headless Jan Node Deployment\n55: Instead of local execution, the Jan core architecture is deployed inside a Lin\n56: ***Inference Subsystem:** Jan uses the Nitro engine to serve quantized varian\n57: ***API Compatibility:** Exposes an OpenAI-compatible endpoint natively inside\n58: ***Storage Abstraction:** The default filesystem-based chat storage (`~/jan/c\n59: ## 2. The Shared Space Principle (Anti-Muda Layer)\n60: Following the structural engineering paradigms of low-latency systems (such as\n61: ***The Problem:** Traditional RAG pipelines pipe information by translating t\n62: ***The Fix:** We export the native embedding weights of Gemma 4 into an ONNX \n63: ***The Outcome:** The database performs semantic operations using the exact m\n64: ## 3. Hardware Constraint Mitigation\n65: Because the Always Free tier provides ARM CPUs rather than dedicated high-bandMarkdown downloadcontent_copy\n66: --- PAGE 3 ---\n67: COGNITIVE_SCHEDULING.md# Unified Data Portability & Rehydration Protocol\n68: This framework defines how historical, unstructured conversation exports from \n69: ## 1. Normalization Matrix\n70: Data packages pulled via GDPR Article 20 data extraction are structurally dive\n71: | Source Platform | Native Format | Target Structural Schema | Extraction Targ\n72: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n73: | **OpenAI / ChatGPT** | `conversations.json` | `SOVEREIGN_CHAT_LINES` | Full \n74: | **Anthropic / Claude** | `conversations.json` | `SOVEREIGN_CHAT_LINES` | Seq\n75: ## 2. Database Schema Blueprint\n76: ```sql\n77: -- Core conversation tracker\n78: CREATE TABLE sovereign_projects (\n79:     project_id VARCHAR2(64) PRIMARY KEY,\n80:     project_name VARCHAR2(255),\n81:     source_platform VARCHAR2(32),\n82:     created_at TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE\n83: );\n84: -- Individual chat messages mapped to an externalized vector layer\n85: CREATE TABLE sovereign_chat_lines (\n86:     message_id VARCHAR2(64) PRIM