ale into millions of tokens\n117: ***The Linear Solution:** Future iterations will transition the core inferenc\n118: ***The Structural Advantage:** Mamba's state-space formulation scales **linea\n119: # Hackathon Evaluation Blueprint & Competitive Differentiation\n120: A tactical breakdown of the final submission strategy targeting the Gemma 4 Go\n121: ## 1. The Value Proposition Matrix\n122: | Evaluator Focus | The Common Approach (Bottom 95%) | The Sovereign Stack App\n123: | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n124: | **Impact & Vision** | \"Here is another educational chatbot run via a corpora\n125: | **Technical Moat** | Standard langchain setups connecting Python to a basic Markdown downloadcontent_copy\n126: Markdown downloadcontent_copy\n127: --- PAGE 5 ---\n128: would having supabase in the stack help here?\n129: Yes, your question is highly distinct, and it addresses\n130: the absolute core of making a private AI stack feel like a\n131: seamless transition rather than an ongoing data-…Immediate Action Plan\n132: To secure this submission before the deadline tonight, do not get bogged down trying\n133: to write a flawless, automated production system. Focus entirely on a verifiable proof\n134: of concept:\n135: 1. Spin up your Always Free Autonomous Database 23ai directly inside your OCI\n136: dashboard console (it takes under 5 minutes to deploy).\n137: 2. Run a basic Python routine inside your workspace to parse a mini-segment of\n138: your real chat data history.\n139: 3. Run a single SQL statement to verify you can execute a VECTOR distance query\n140: inside your database.\n141: 4. Record your demo video showing this execution flow.\n142: You have the architectural blueprint, the technical differentiation, and the\n143: infrastructure ready to deploy. Focus on shipping the code before the countdown\n144: ends.## 2. Core Submission Deliverables (Due Tonight)\n145: 1.**The Core Narrative:** \"Democratizing corporate AI value. Moving data out \n146: 2.**The Proof-of-Concept Video (3 Minutes):**\n147:    ***0:00 - 0:45:** The Problem (The Data Trap, Token Waste, and Muda).\n148:    ***0:45 - 2:00:** The Infrastructure (Showing Jan headless running inside \n149:    ***2:00 - 3:00:** The Demo (Ingesting a real JSON historical chat sample, \n150: 3.**The 1,500 Word Technical Writeup:** Compiled from the architectural notes\n151: expand_more\n152: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem S\n153: Show thinkingexpand_more\n154: --- PAGE 6 ---\n155: In the context of the sovereign, resource-optimized AI stack we’ve sketched out,\n156: adding Supabase to the mix would introduce significant Muda (architectural\n157: redundancy and waste).\n158: While Supabase is an exceptional tool for rapid application development, integrating it\n159: into this specific setup creates severe friction against your core constraints:\n160: maximizing the OCI Always Free tier and maintaining an elegant, unified data layer.\n161: Here is the direct engineering assessment of why Supabase is redundant here,\n162: followed by the single edge-case scenario where it would make sense.\n163: Why Supabase Introduces Architectural Muda\n164: 1. The Database Duplication Problem\n165: You have already provisioned Oracle 23ai Free to act as your enterprise-grade\n166: relational and native vector engine.\n167: Supabase is fundamentally a wrapper around PostgreSQL (pgvector).\n168: If you introduce Supabase, you are now running two massive, competing\n169: relational database management systems (RDBMS) on a single machine. This\n170: creates a fragmented source of truth where you have to synchronize data\n171: between Postgres and Oracle 23ai, defeating the purpose of a consolidated\n172: intelligence engine.\n173: 2. State & Authentication Overlap\n174: One of Supabase's primary selling points is instant Auth and real-time state sync.\n175: However, Open WebUI already handles these vectors out of the box:\n176: Open WebUI possesses its own built-in authentication, multi-user role\n177: management, and session state persistence (backed by SQLite or its own\n178: isolated PostgreSQL instance).\n179: It directly manages the tree-structured conversation histories and markdown\n180: parsing. Inserting Supabase as an intermediary between Open WebUI and your\n181: database layer adds zero functional utility while inserting an extra network hop.\n182: 3. Severe RAM and OCPU Thrashing\n183: Your OCI Ampere A1 instance provides a generous but rigid 24GB of RAM and 4\n184: OCPUs. Let's look at the actual compute footprint if you add Supabase:\n185: --- PAGE 7 ---\n186: The LLM Subsystem (Ollama/Jan + Gemma 4): Consumes 8GB to 16GB RAM\n187: depending on quantization level and context length.\n188: Oracle 23ai Free: Allocates a strict System Global Area (SGA) and Program\n189: Global Area (PGA) footprint (often 2GB to 4GB minimum to maintain performant\n190: vector indexing).\n191: Open WebUI: Low overhead, but requires ~1GB for its container and local cache.\n192: The Supabase Stack: Supabase is not just Postgres. It is a collection of\n193: microservices: Kong (API Gateway), GoTrue (Auth), PostgREST (REST API),\n194: Realtime (WebSockets), Storage, and Supabase Studio. Running this entire\n195: ecosystem via Docker alongside your inference engine and Oracle 23ai will push\n196: your ARM instance to the absolute brink of memory swap death.\n197: The One Scenario Where Supabase Does Help\n198: The only reason to introduce Supabase into this architecture is if you decide to \n199: abandon Open WebUI entirely because you are building a custom, proprietary SaaS\n200: application or a highly tailored, programmatic user interface from scratch.\n201: If you are writing a custom frontend (e.g., using Next.js or a spatial-first web layout)\n202: and you need an instant backend to handle user accounts, custom webhooks, and\n203: rapid API generation, Supabase is brilliant. In that specific layout, Oracle 23ai would be\n204: relegated strictly to a deep backend analytical role, or you would drop Oracle entirely\n205: and let Supabase's pgvector act as the sole database.\n206: Given that your immediate goal is to rehydrate legacy ChatGPT/Claude data into a\n207: clean, operational workspace layout today, stick to the lean stack:\n208: This keeps your architecture unified, ensures sub-second latency on your Ampere ARM\n209: architecture, and keeps your resource consumption well below the OCI ceiling.\n210: Are you planning to use this stack strictly as a personal sovereign cockpit via Open\n211: WebUI, or is this the foundation for a custom application you intend to build out?[Open WebUI] ---> [Ollama / Nitro Engine]\n212:      |\n213:      +------------> [Oracle 23ai (Vector & Core Logs)]\n214: --- PAGE 8 ---\n215: no then i want to strip jan ui and make it work on my oci :\n216: Skip to content\n217: janhq…expand_more\n218: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n219: Stripping the GUI (src-tauri and web-app) to run a headless inference server on\n220: your OCI Ampere A1 instance is the exact right play. It completely eliminates the\n221: Node.js/Tauri graphical runtime overhead, saving you precious gigabytes of RAM for\n222: your context windows.\n223: +1\n224: You have two primary ways to achieve this sovereign, headless setup on your ARM64\n225: architecture:\n226: Option 1: The Monorepo Headless Run (Using the pasted code)\n227: If you have already cloned janhq/jan on your instance, you do not need to build or\n228: run the desktop UI.You can bypass make dev (which triggers Tauri) and target the\n229: core API server directly.\n230: +1\n231: 1. Install Bare Headless Dependencies\n232: Ensure your ARM64 instance has the runtime foundations (Node 20+ and Yarn) but skip\n233: any graphical/X11 requirements:S\n234: link\n235: link\n236: link\n237: # Install Node.js 20 & Yarn if not present\n238: curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -\n239: sudo apt-get install -y nodejs\n240: corepack enable && corepack prepare yarn@4.5.3 --activateShow thinkingexpand_more\n241: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n242: --- PAGE 9 ---\n243: 2. Install and Spin Up the Server\n244: Instead of using the standard make routines, initialize dependencies and call the\n245: server-only execution target:\n246: This boots the local orchestration server on port 1337 by default, exposing an OpenAI-\n247: compatible interface.\n248: Option 2: The Pure C++ Sovereign Route (Nitro Engine)\n249: If you want the absolute highest efficiency on an Always Free ARM instance, you\n250: should drop the Node/TypeScript monorepo altogether.\n251: Jan's underlying heavy lifter is actually Nitro—a lightweight (~3MB), native C++\n252: inference engine built on top of llama.cpp and packaged with the high-performance \n253: drogon C++ web framework. Running Nitro directly bypasses Node.js processing\n254: queues entirely.\n255: 1. Deploy the Native Engine on ARM64\n256: You can fetch and compile/install the standalone Nitro binary natively on your Linux\n257: instance:# Clone and enter repo\n258: git clone https://github.com/janhq/jan\n259: cd jan\n260: link\n261: yarn install\n262: # Run the OpenAI-compatible API server without the Tauri UI\n263: yarn dev:server\n264: link\n265: link\n266: [Your Custom UI / Open WebUI] \n267:        │ (Port 3928)\n268:        ▼\n269: [Nitro C++ Binary (llama.cpp)] ── ►  Shared Memory ── ►  ARM64 Cores\n270: linkBash downloadcontent_copy\n271: --- PAGE 10 ---\n272: 2. Spin Up the Engine\n273: Execute the binary directly, configuring thread allocation to align cleanly with your 4\n274: OCPUs:\n275: 3. Load a Model and Run Inference via cURL\n276: Nitro starts as an empty, high-performance frame.You instruct it to hot-load your\n277: GGUF models directly via an API call:\n278: Once loaded, it listens natively on port 3928 with clean OpenAI parity:curl -sfL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/janhq/nitro/main/install.sh | sudo\n279: link\n280: # Usage: ./nitro [threads] [host] [port]\n281: nitro 4 0.0.0.0 3928\n282: link\n283: # Load your model into memory\n284: curl http://localhost:3928/inferences/llamacpp/loadmodel \\\n285:   -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\\n286:   -d '{\n287:     \"llama_model_path\": \"/path/to/your/gemma-2-9b.gguf\",\n288:     \"ctx_len\": 4096,\n289:     \"cpu_threads\": 4\n290:   }'\n291: link\n292: curl http://localhost:3928/v1/chat/completions \\\n293:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n294:   -d '{\n295:     \"messages\": [Bash downloadcontent_copy\n296: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n297: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n298: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n299: --- PAGE 11 ---\n300: Making It Sovereign: Systemd Automation\n301: To ensure this server runs out of sight and automatically recovers when your OCI\n302: instance cycles, encapsulate it in a systemd service file:\n303: Paste the following system unit configuration:\n304: Enable and fire it up:\n305: This completely decouples your inference execution from any graphical desktop\n306: clutter, letting you wire it straight to a minimal client or programmatic workflow over      {\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Optimize this system loop.\"}\n307:     ]\n308:   }'\n309: sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/nitro-engine.service\n310: [Unit]\n311: Description=Nitro C++ Headless Inference Engine\n312: After=network.target\n313: [Service]\n314: Type=simple\n315: User=ubuntu\n316: WorkingDirectory=/home/ubuntu\n317: ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/nitro 40.0.0.03928\n318: Restart=always\n319: RestartSec=5\n320: [Install]\n321: WantedBy=multi-user.target\n322: sudo systemctl daemon-reload\n323: sudo systemctl enable nitro-engine\n324: sudo systemctl start nitro-engineBash downloadcontent_copy\n325: Ini, TOML downloadcontent_copy\n326: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n327: --- PAGE 12 ---\n328: no but i want janhq ui of their chat bot:your internal virtual cloud network.\n329: link\n330: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n331: Understood. You don’t want to compromise on the interface—you want Jan's signature\n332: minimalist layout, clean dark mode, and sleek sidebar workspace running directly in\n333: your browser, hosted entirely out of your OCI cloud instance.\n334: Since Jan's desktop app is a Tauri wrapper around a web application, you can isolate\n335: and run the web-app directory (visible in your repository tree) as a cloud-hosted\n336: portal.\n337: Transforming the codebase into a web service running on your Ampere instance\n338: requires a specific setup.\n339: The Two-Tier Cloud Deployment\n340: To achieve this, your OCI instance must run two separate decoupled processes\n341: simultaneously:\n342: 1. The Core Inference Server: Manages models and handles OpenAI-compatible\n343: requests on port 1337.SlinkSources\n344: Show thinkingexpand_more\n345: --- PAGE 13 ---\n346: 2. The Web UI App: Serves the interface to your browser on port 3000 (or your\n347: preferred web port).\n348: Step-by-Step Implementation\n349: Step 1: Install & Build the Monorepo\n350: Connect to your OCI ARM instance via SSH, step into your cloned directory, and ensure\n351: all workspace packages are natively compiled for your architecture:\n352: Step 2: Spin Up the Core Server\n353: The UI needs its engine. Fire up the headless API server first. It is best practice to run\n354: this in a multiplexer like tmux or screen so it stays alive after you close your SSH\n355: connection:\n356: Verify it is healthy by checking if it listens locally:curl\n357: http://localhost:1337/v1/models[Your Browser] ── (Port 3000) ── ►  [Jan Web UI]\n358:                                      │\n359:                              (Internal Loopback)\n360:                                      ▼\n361:                                 [Jan Server] ── (Port 1337) ── ►  [Gemma 4 / Nitro\n362: cd jan\n363: # Clean out any partial builds and install dependencies across all workspaces\n364: yarn clean\n365: yarn install\n366: # Trigger a build of the core dependencies\n367: yarn build\n368: # Boot the engine in headless daemon mode\n369: yarn dev:serverBash downloadcontent_copy\n370: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n371: --- PAGE 14 ---\n372: Step 3: Launch the Standalone Web UI\n373: Open a second terminal window or a separate tmux pane, navigate into the web\n374: workspace, and host it to the public interface:\n375: (Note: If the underlying framework fails to recognize the --host flag due to structural\n376: updates, execute it via the standard node flag:yarn dev -H 0.0.0.0 -p 3000).\n377: Step 4: Open Your OCI Network Gates\n378: By default, Oracle Cloud drops all incoming traffic to unapproved ports. You must\n379: explicitly allow ingress traffic for port 3000 to access the chat UI in your browser.\n380: 1. Clear the Host OS Firewall (Ubuntu/Debian default)\n381: 2. Configure the OCI VCN Ingress Rules\n382: 1. Open your Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Console.\n383: 2. Navigate to Networking > Virtual Cloud Networks > Click on your specific VCN.\n384: 3. Select your Security List (usually Default Security List for vcn-...).\n385: 4. Click Add Ingress Rules and apply these specifications:\n386: Source Type:CIDR\n387: Source CIDR:0.0.0.0/0 (or your personal home IP for locked-down\n388: privacy)\n389: IP Protocol:TCP\n390: Destination Port Range:3000cd web-app\n391: # Launch the dev environment bound to all network interfaces\n392: yarn dev --host 0.0.0.0 --port 3000\n393: sudo ufw allow 3000/tcp\n394: sudo ufw reloadBash downloadcontent_copy\n395: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n396: --- PAGE 15 ---\n397: permanetnely? and now if i want to save this version in my\n398: personal git and then start an lxd with oracle linux 9 and use\n399: it with gemma for the competition as u see in my memory.Accessing Your Sovereign Cockpit\n400: Open your browser and navigate to your OCI instance's public IP layout:\n401: You will see the native Jan Chat interface render directly in your browser window. Head\n402: into the UI settings panel, point the API base connection string to your local engine\n403: (http:/