it\n441: # Stage and commit only core UI logic and build structures\n442: git add .\n443: git commit -m \"feat: Sovereign Headless Server and Custom Web UI Configuration\n444: # Bind to your personal remote repository\n445: git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_SOVEREIGN_JAN.git\n446: git branch -M main\n447: git push -u origin mainIni, TOML downloadcontent_copy\n448: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n449: --- PAGE 17 ---\n450: 1. Launch the Container\n451: We will allocate 4 vCPUs and 20GB of RAM directly to this instance container, leaving\n452: a stable 4GB buffer for the host hypervisor:\n453: 2. Move Into the Enterprise Shell\n454: You are now executing commands directly inside an isolated Oracle Linux 9 enterprise\n455: architecture.\n456: Phase 3: Provision the RHEL/OL9 Development Environment\n457: Oracle Linux 9 relies on dnf and structural RPM packaging layers. We must install the\n458: standard developer tooling natively mapped to ARM64 execution.\n459: 1. Refresh System Repos and Install Core Dependencies\n460: 2. Install Node.js 20 & Yarn 4\n461: Pull down the verified Enterprise Linux NodeSource layout to establish the TypeScript\n462: runtime ecosystem:lxc launch images:oracle/9 ol9-sovereign \\\n463:   -c limits.cpu=4 \\\n464:   -c limits.memory=20GB\n465: # Verify the container is running and holding an internal network IP\n466: lxc list\n467: lxc exec ol9-sovereign -- /bin/bash\n468: dnf update -y\n469: dnf groupinstall \"Development Tools\" -y\n470: dnf install -y git wget curl gcc-c++ makeBash downloadcontent_copy\n471: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n472: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n473: --- PAGE 18 ---\n474: Phase 4: Rehydrate Code and Deploy Inside the Container\n475: 1. Clone Your Personal Git Repo\n476: Pull down the pristine, customized codebase you pushed during Phase 1:\n477: 2. Build the Headless Frame\n478: Compile the underlying dependencies and establish the multi-package workspace\n479: structures inside your Oracle environment:\n480: Phase 5: Wire the Networks (LXD Proxy Configuration)\n481: To hit the UI from your browser and let the frontend communicate with your local\n482: Gemma 4 endpoints over your OCI VCN, you must map the container network\n483: interfaces straight back out to the host.# Register NodeSource repository\n484: curl -fsSL https://rpm.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | bash -\n485: dnf install -y nodejs\n486: # Activate modern yarn structures natively via corepack\n487: corepack enable\n488: corepack prepare yarn@4.5.3 --activate\n489: cd /opt\n490: git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_SOVEREIGN_JAN.git sovereign-in\n491: cd sovereign-intelligence\n492: yarn clean\n493: yarn install\n494: yarn buildBash downloadcontent_copy\n495: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n496: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n497: --- PAGE 19 ---\n498: Exit the container back to your host terminal (exit), then issue these LXD execution\n499: instructions:\n500: Phase 6: Run and Validate Your Hackathon Submission\n501: Jump back into the container execution thread (lxc exec ol9-sovereign --\n502: /bin/bash) and initialize the stack using split background managers:\n503: Final Hackathon System Validation\n504: To confirm your stack is working correctly before final code assembly, hit your\n505: endpoints remotely from an external shell:\n506: When this returns a clean JSON array structure, your system is up and running. Your\n507: customized Jan UI will render in the browser on port 3000, processing data inside an\n508: isolated Oracle Linux 9 wrapper, utilizing the precise internal context structures we\n509: engineered to prevent compute overhead.# Map the Web UI App (Port 3000) from the container to the public host edge\n510: lxc config device add ol9-sovereign webui-proxy proxy \\\n511:   listen=tcp:0.0.0.0:3000 connect=tcp:127.0.0.1:3000\n512: # Map the Inference Endpoint Server (Port 1337) \n513: lxc config device add ol9-sovereign engine-proxy proxy \\\n514:   listen=tcp:0.0.0.0:1337 connect=tcp:127.0.0.1:1337\n515: # 1. Fire up the Core Next-Token API Engine\n516: nohup yarn dev:server > /var/log/jan-engine.log 2>&1 &\n517: # 2. Fire up the Jan-Signature Presentation Layer UI\n518: cd web-app\n519: nohup yarn dev -H 0.0.0.0 -p 3000 > /var/log/jan-ui.log 2>&1 &\n520: curl http://<YOUR_OCI_PUBLIC_IP>:1337/v1/modelsBash downloadcontent_copy\n521: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n522: Bash downloadcontent_copy\n523: --- PAGE 20 ---\n524: but will it be jan ui ditto ditto?Would you like help drafting the automated shell script that executes this entire\n525: compilation, setup, and configuration process automatically for your final submission\n526: repository?\n527: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n528: Yes, visually and texturally it will be ditto ditto. The reason it looks identical is\n529: because Jan’s desktop app is fundamentally an Electron/Tauri wrapper (a\n530: specialized browser frame) built around that exact web-app directory you see in the\n531: repository tree. When you run web-app standalone, you are pulling the exact same\n532: CSS sheets, the same minimalist layout, the same dark mode accent colors, and the\n533: exact same sidebar component trees.\n534: However, there is a catch. While it will look exactly the same, it won't act 100% \"plug-\n535: and-play ditto\" until we resolve one fundamental engineering problem: The Tauri\n536: Bridge.\n537: The \"Tauri Bridge\" Problem\n538: When you run Jan on your desktop, the frontend web app tries to talk to your physical\n539: computer's operating system using native desktop bridges (window.__TAURI__ or\n540: local system calls). It expects to:\n541: 1. Look directly at your local hard drive to see where your .gguf model files are\n542: saved.\n543: 2. Pull your local system hardware specs (like checking if you have an Apple Silicon\n544: M-series chip or an NVIDIA GPU).\n545: If you take that exact code and spin it up inside a standard web browser over an OCI\n546: cloud link, the browser doesn't have native OS access. If you click a button that calls a\n547: desktop-only function, the application could freeze or throw an undefined error in\n548: your browser's console.S\n549: Show thinkingexpand_more\n550: --- PAGE 21 ---\n551: How to Make it Work in Your Oracle Linux 9 LXD Container\n552: To get the exact Jan UI working in the browser while hooked up to your OCI cloud\n553: backend, you must configure the web application to run in Browser/Server Mode\n554: rather than Desktop Mode.\n555: Here is how you adjust the monorepo configuration so it switches its communication\n556: layer from local desktop bridges to your cloud engine:\n557: 1. Configure the Target Endpoint Environment\n558: Before building the web-app workspace inside your container, you must tell the\n559: frontend where to route its API traffic. Inside your /opt/sovereign-intelligence/web-\n560: app/ directory, create or modify the environment build file:\n561: Add the target variables to force the web app to ignore local desktop hooks and treat\n562: your headless instance engine as its sole orchestrator:\n563: 2. Serve the Static Web Assets Natively\n564: Instead of using yarn dev (which continuously monitors files and consumes massive\n565: developer memory overhead inside the container), compile the frontend down into\n566: raw, optimized, high-performance static HTML/JS web blocks:cd /opt/sovereign-intelligence/web-app\n567: nano .env.production\n568: # Force the web app to run in standalone browser mode\n569: NEXT_PUBLIC_TARGET=web\n570: NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL=http://127.0.0.1:1337/v1\n571: # Block the app from throwing errors when desktop-only extensions are missing\n572: NEXT_PUBLIC_DISABLE_TAURI=trueBash downloadcontent_copy\n573: Ini, TOML downloadcontent_copy\n574: --- PAGE 22 ---\n575: why isnt it as straihgt forward as open web ui like the ollama\n576: one?This compiles a clean, lightweight, static web package into a build output folder (often\n577: named dist or out). You can then let a simple, low-overhead static server or a fast\n578: service handle the port 3000 rendering. This completely eliminates Node.js\n579: compilation waste, ensuring your Always Free ARM cores are 100% dedicated to\n580: generating fast tokens for your Gemma 4 model during your competition presentation.\n581: The Bottom Line\n582: When you type http://<YOUR_OCI_PUBLIC_IP>:3000 into your browser tonight, the\n583: interface that populates your screen will be the identical, minimalist, signature Jan\n584: setup from your image. It will look identical, but because of these configurations, it will\n585: process your data silently inside your Oracle Linux container.# Build the production-ready web distribution\n586: yarn build:web\n587: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n588: The reason it is not as straightforward as Open WebUI is a fundamental difference in \n589: design philosophy and architecture.\n590: Open WebUI and Ollama were designed from day one to operate in a Client-Server\n591: split architecture, while Jan was built to be a Standalone Desktop App.\n592: 1. The Architectural Blueprint: Server vs. Sandbox\n593: Open WebUI: It is naturally a web server. It expects to be deployed in a remote\n594: Docker container, live on an IP address, manage network requests, and talk to\n595: another network server (Ollama) via standard web connections (HTTP/REST).\n596: Jan Desktop (The janhq/jan repository): It was built to be a single, local\n597: application that runs 100% offline inside your computer’s local desktopSBash downloadcontent_copy\n598: --- PAGE 23 ---\n599: screen. To achieve this, it uses a framework called Tauri.\n600: Because of Tauri, the UI and the Engine in that repo are deeply intertwined. The UI\n601: expects to look into local hard-drive folders (like C:\\Users\\ or /home/ubuntu/jan)\n602: using local operating system privileges, rather than hitting a generic web URL. Pulling it\n603: out of that desktop wrapper to host it on OCI means you are manually breaking a\n604: desktop application apart and forcing it to act like a cloud server.\n605: 2. The Solution: Enter Jan Server (janhq/server)\n606: The Jan team realized that users wanted exactly what you are trying to do—the Jan\n607: interface and engine running natively on cloud servers or Docker setups without local\n608: desktop constraints.\n609: To solve this, they didn't just tweak the desktop app; they built an entirely separate\n610: repository specifically for the cloud: janhq/server.\n611: If you check the repository structure of janhq/server (which is their enterprise-\n612: grade, self-hosted platform), it features a clean one-command deployment that\n613: functions exactly like the Open WebUI/Ollama experience. It skips all the desktop/Tauri\n614: code entirely.\n615: Inside janhq/server, you get:\n616: 1. apps/web: A pure, decoupled, web-optimized React version of the classic Jan\n617: chat interface—no desktop bridges required.\n618: 2. services/: The backend services (including the C++ inference engine)\n619: orchestrated natively for server tasks.\n620: How to run it with a single command (The \"Ollama-like\" experience)\n621: If you want the exact Jan UI experience on your Oracle Linux 9 LXD container without\n622: manually patching the desktop code, use their official server repository. It uses a \n623: Makefile setup built specifically for headless server deployments:\n624: # 1. Step into your Oracle Linux 9 Container\n625: lxc exec ol9-sovereign -- /bin/bash\n626: # 2. Clone the Dedicated Server Repository\n627: git clone https://github.com/janhq/server.git jan-server\n628: cd jan-serverBash downloadcontent_copy\n629: --- PAGE 24 ---\n630: and so?\n631: Skip to content\n632: janhq…This commands spins up the pure React web app deployment on port 3001, giving\n633: you the exact minimalist user interface you see in your image, while completely\n634: dropping the complex Tauri desktop constraints. It routes all inference natively through\n635: the cloud server layer, providing a clean setup for your competition submission.# 3. Boot the standalone web chat interface directly\n636: make up-web\n637: expand_more\n638: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n639: Analyzing the janhq/server repository blueprint reveals why this is the perfect engine\n640: for your hackathon setup. It natively separates the interface (apps/web running on\n641: React 19/Vite on Port 3001) from the microservices backend, eliminating Tauri desktop\n642: dependencies entirely.\n643: Because this stack uses pnpm workspaces and Go microservices orchestrating via a\n644: central Kong API Gateway, deploying it inside an isolated Oracle Linux 9 LXD container\n645: requires structural precision to avoid overwhelming your OCI Ampere A1 instance.\n646: Here is the updated series of distinct .md blueprint specifications continuing your\n647: system configuration repository.\n648: DEPLOYMENT_JAN_SERVER_OL9.mdS\n649: # Blueprint: Microservices Jan Server Deployment on Oracle Linux 9\n650: This document covers the compilation, containment, and network routing configu\n651: ## 1. System Topology OverviewMarkdown downloadcontent_copy\n652: --- PAGE 25 ---\n653: +---------------------|--------------------------------|---------------------+\n654: | Oracle Linux 9 LXD Container (ol9-sovereign)         |                     |\n655: |                                                      |                     |\n656: |  +------------------+      +-------------------------v------------------+  |\n657: |  | Frontend Engine  |      | Enterprise API Gateway Layer               |  |\n658: |  |                  |      |                                            |  |\n659: |  | apps/web         |      | Kong API Gateway (Port 8000)               |  |\n660: |  | (React 19 / Vite)|      +-------------------------+------------------+  |\n661: |  | [Port 3001]      |                                |                     |\n662: |  +------------------+                                v                     |\n663: |                                    +---------------------------------+     |\n664: |                                    | Go Orchestration Microservices  |     |\n665: |                                    |                                 |     |\n666: |                                    | llm-api [Port 8080]             |     |\n667: |                                    | response-api [Port 8082]        |     |\n668: |                                    +-----------------+---------------+     |\n669: |                                                      |                     |\n670: |                                                      v                     |\n671: |                                    +---------------------------------+     |\n672: |                                    | Data & Semantic Engine Layer    |     |\n673: |                                    |                                 |     |\n674: |                                    | PostgreSQL 18 Core State DB     |     |\n675: |                                    | Oracle 23ai Sovereign Vectors   |     |\n676: |                                    +---------------------------------+     |\n677: +----------------------------------------------------------------------------+The production layout isolates database state, token orchestration, and the pu\n678:               +----------------------------------------+\n679:               |         Public Network Edge            |\n680:               +---+--------------------------------+---+\n681:                   | Port 3001                      | Port 8000\n682:                   v                                v\n683: ## 2. Environment Provisioning Script (`setup_ol9_dependencies.sh`)\n684: Execute this pipeline within the pristine `ol9-sovereign` shell environment to\n685: --- PAGE 26 ---\n686: 3. Monorepo Assembly and Container Target Management\n687: Clone the server architecture directly into /opt, map environmental values, and\n688: target lightweight service profiles to optimize resource allocation:\n689: To prevent performance issues from heavy container layers like Keycloak, Keycloak's\n690: database, Redis, and internal vLLM configurations running simultaneously on the same\n691: ARM core cluster, modify docker-compose.yml profiles to expose only essential edge\n692: routing services:```bash\n693: #!/usr/bin/env bash\n694: set -euo pipefail\n695: echo \"=== Upgrading Enterprise Package Indexes ===\"\n696: dnf update -y\n697: dnf groupinstall \"Development Tools\" -y\n698: dnf install -y git wget curl gcc-c++ make dnf-plugins-core\n699: echo \"=== Integrating External Container Runtimes ===\"\n700: dnf config-manager --add-repo [https://download.docker.com/linux/centos/docker\n701: dnf install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-compose-plugin\n702: systemctl enable --now docker\n703: echo \"=== Injecting Modern Node / Monorepo Tools ===\"\n704: curl -fsSL [https://rpm.nodesource.com/setup_20.x](https://rpm.nodesource.com/\n705: dnf install -y nodejs\n706: corepack enable\n707: corepack prepare pnpm@latest --activate\n708: cd /opt\n709: git clone [https://github.com/janhq/server.git](https://github.com/janhq/serve\n710: cd jan-server\n711: # Build base CLI helpers and generate configuration profiles\n712: make setupBash downloadcontent_copy\n713: --- PAGE 27 ---\n714: 3. Host Firewall Cleanse (Oracle Linux / RHEL Host Variants)\n715: Ensure the host network stack allows packets to flow across these boundaries without\n716: dropping them:# Bring up only the React Web Interface, Gateway, and LLM core routing service\n717: docker compose --profile web up -d\n718: ---\n719: ### `ORACLE_VCN_EDGE_PROXY.md`\n720: ```markdown\n721: # Network Infrastructure: LXD Proxies and OCI Security Topologies\n722: This document defines the structural bridging operations required to pipe clea\n723: ## 1. Physical Interface Mapping\n724: `janhq/server` splits traffic across two separate ingress interfaces. We must \n725: | Application Component | Internal Target | Target Service Container | Public \n726: | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n727: | **Jan Standalone Web UI** | `127.0.0.1:3001` | `apps/web` (Vite frame) | **P\n728: | **Kong API Gateway Edge** | `127.0.0.1:8000` | `kong` Proxy Endpoint | **Por\n729: ## 2. LXD Hardware Interface Routing Commands\n730: Exit to your host machine shell and configure the device proxies to tie the in\n731: ```bash\n732: # Bind the Jan Signature Chat UI interface\n733: lxc config device add ol9-sovereign web-ui-edge proxy \\\n734:   listen=tcp:0.0.0.0:3001 connect=tcp:127.0.0.1:3001\n735: # Bind the Central API Gateway interface\n736: lxc config device add ol9-sovereign api-gateway-edge proxy \\\n737:   listen=tcp:0.0.0.0:8000 connect=tcp:127.0.0.1:8000Bash downloadcontent_copy\n738: --- PAGE 28 ---\n739: 2. In-Database History Tracking (The Oracle 23ai Sync Hook)\n740: While jan-server uses PostgreSQL 18 by default for its short-term session storage,\n741: we use a custom script to periodically dump conversation data into our central vector\n742: database. This keeps long-term project memory organized and indexed without\n743: cluttering the active app database.sudo firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-port=3001/tcp --permanent\n744: sudo firewall-cmd --zone=public --add-port=8000/tcp --permanent\n745: sudo firewall-cmd --reload\n746: ---\n747: ### `HACKATHON_INTEGRATION_SPEC.md`\n748: ```markdown\n749: # Hackathon Target Framework: Connecting Jan Server to Gemma 4 & Oracle 23ai\n750: This specification establishes the interoperability guidelines for linking the\n751: ## 1. Decoupling Inference From vLLM Docker Layers\n752: By default, `jan-server` attempts to spawn an internal instance of `vllm`. Bec\n753: Modify `config/secrets.env` or your primary `.env` layer to point to your ligh\n754: ```ini\n755: # Redirect the LLM API service from Docker-vLLM to our lightweight C++ runner\n756: LLM_API_URL=http://localhost:3928/v1\n757: DEFAULT_MODEL=gemma4\n758: # sync_history_to_oracle.py\n759: import psycopg2\n760: import oracledb\n761: import json\n762: defmigrate_active_sessions():\n763: # Fetch latest raw messages from Jan Server's transient Postgres database\n764:     pg_conn = psycopg2.connect(\"dbname=jan_server user=postgres password=secre\n765:     pg_cursor = pg_conn.cursor()\n766:     pg_cursor.execute(\"SELECT id, conversation_id, role, content, created_at F\n767:     records = pg_cursor.fetchall()Bash downloadcontent_copy\n768: Python downloadcontent_copy\n769: --- PAGE 29 ---\n770: 3. Compelling Evaluation Points for Submission\n771: 1. True Production Isolation: \"This is not a toy desktop application running on a\n772: laptop. It is an enterprise-grade platform running on an Oracle Linux 9\n773: microservices architecture, built entirely within OCI's Always Free boundaries.\"\n774: 2. Optimized Resource Consumption: \"By separating the client-side presentation\n775: layer (apps/web) from the background tasks, we protect memory overhead. This\n776: ensures our 4 ARM CPU cores are fully optimized for handling Gemma 4's\n777: inference processes.\"# Establish connection with Oracle 23ai Vector Engine\n778:     ora_conn = oracledb.connect(user=\"system\", password=\"YourPassword\", dsn=\"l\n779:     ora_cursor = ora_conn.cursor()\n780: for row in records:\n781: # Check for duplicates, run embeddings, and populate SOVEREIGN_CHAT_LI\n782: # maintaining structural context for long-term project recall\n783: pass\n784:     ora_conn.commit()\n785:     print(\"Conversations synchronized successfully to Sovereign Oracle Vector \n786: if __name__ == \"__main__\":\n787:     migrate_active_sessions()\n788: ---\n789: ### Executing the Strategy\n790: Using the `janhq/server` repository streamlines your production workflow signi\n791: 1. Run the dependency script (`setup_ol9_dependencies.sh`) inside your contain\n792: 2. Clone `janhq/server` and run `make setup`.\n793: 3. Use `docker compose --profile web up -d` to launch only the web and API com\n794: 4. Point the configuration variables to your Gemma 4 runtime model.\n795: This configuration gives you a highly stable, completely decoupled setup that \n796: --- PAGE 30 ---\n797: and so this will work better than open webui?\n798: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n799: No. It will actually perform worse on your OCI Always Free instance than Open WebUI,\n800: and it will be significantly harder to maintain for your specific goal.\n801: While janhq/server gives you the exact minimalist Jan UI you want, you need to\n802: understand why it exists before you commit to it for tonight's hackathon deadline.\n803: The \"and so?\" reality comes down to resource cost, architecture, and your\n804: requirement to import Claude/ChatGPT data. Here is the direct breakdown comparing\n805: the two options:\n806: 1. The Resource Overhead (The Heavy Microservices Cost)\n807: Look at the tech stack list in the repository code you just posted. jan-server is an \n808: enterprise-grade, production microservices platform written in Go. To run the full\n809: backend, it spins up:\n810: Kong API Gateway (An entire enterprise proxy layer)\n811: Keycloak (A massive Java-based user authentication engine that eats RAM for\n812: breakfast)\n813: PostgreSQL 18 (For message storage)\n814: Redis (For caching)\n815: SandboxFusion (For executing code securely)\n816: Open WebUI is a single, unified, lightweight Python/Svelte app. It uses an embedded \n817: SQLite database by default (which takes virtually 0MB of idle RAM) and has built-in\n818: light authentication.\n819: Running jan-server's microservices stack alongside your LLM engine inside your\n820: 24GB OCI ARM instance leaves very little breathing room for your Gemma model's\n821: active context window. You are burning your Always Free hardware on complex\n822: enterprise networking rather than your actual AI reasoning.\n823: 2. The Data Rehydration Problem (Your Main Goal)S\n824: --- PAGE 31 ---\n825: Your core requirement is to import your existing Claude and ChatGPT data\n826: packages, rehydrate them, and have them appear exactly as active sidebars and\n827: projects.\n828: Open WebUI: Has a large, mature open-source community that built native data\n829: importers. You can literally drag-and-drop your ChatGPT conversations.json\n830: directly into the web UI, and its internal database parses it into active chat trees\n831: instantly.\n832: Jan Server: Is highly developer-focused and designed around a backend API\n833: architecture. Its database schema is built for enterprise application pipelines,\n834: not for consumer data imports. To get your historical ChatGPT or Claude data to\n835: display inside the jan-server UI, you cannot use a built-in import button; you\n836: have to manually write scripts to inject data through Kong into its PostgreSQL\n837: schema or hit its custom API endpoints.\n838: The Verdict: Which One Should You Choose?\n839: Feature Open WebUI +\n840: Nitro/OllamaJan Server (janhq/server)\n841: UI Aesthetics Modern ChatGPT clone Minimalist Jan Desktop clone\n842: Idle RAM Footprint Low (~1GB) High (~4GB+ due to\n843: Keycloak/Kong)\n844: ChatGPT/Claude\n845: ImportNative Drag-and-Drop Manual API Coding Required\n846: Setup Complexity Simple (Single Container)Complex (Multi-service Docker\n847: Stack)\n848: The Hackathon Strategy\n849: If your absolute priority is getting the exact, specific visual appearance of the Jan\n850: UI on your screen, then jan-server is your only option. You must accept the heavycontent_copyExport to Sheets \n851: --- PAGE 32 ---\n852: do me all the remainig reach on this alternativemicroservices setup, configure it in your Oracle Linux 9 container, and handle data\n853: migration programmatically via APIs.\n854: However, if your absolute priority is building a functional data-sovereign workspace\n855: where your multi-year Claude/ChatGPT data is instantly rehydrated and usable\n856: for zero cost, Open WebUI is the far superior engine. You can configure Open WebUI\n857: to use a minimalist dark theme, connect it to your local backend engine, drop your data\n858: packages in, and instantly show a working, fully populated sovereign cockpit to the\n859: hackathon judges.\n860: Sovreign Infra•Custom Gem\n861: This completes the deep architectural research into the janhq/server platform.\n862: Deploying it natively in your Oracle Linux 9 LXD container requires a thorough\n863: analysis of how the backend manages data, its container configurations, and the exact\n864: steps needed to handle data rehydration for your hackathon submission.\n865: Part 1: Decoupling the Production Database Profile\n866: jan-server uses a production-ready database configuration split into individual\n867: service layers to manage user records, metadata, and persistent states across internal\n868: Docker volumes.\n869: To ensure complete data isolation on your host machine, modify \n870: infra/docker/services-api.yml inside your workspace to expose the relational\n871: database endpoints out of the LXD layer.S\n872: # Location: infra/docker/services-api.yml\n873: version:'3.8'\n874: services:\n875: jan-postgres:\n876: image:postgres:18-alpine\n877: container_name:jan-core-dbYAML downloadcontent_copy\n878: --- PAGE 33 ---\n879: Part 2: Custom Data Rehydration Script\n880: Because janhq/server manages sessions through Go microservices controlled by an\n881: API Gateway, migrating historical raw chat data directly into PostgreSQL requires\n882: structured data normalization.\n883: Save this python utility script to process and inject historical conversations, keeping\n884: the user interface completely populated.environment:\n885: POSTGRES_USER:${POSTGRES_USER:-jan_admin}\n886: POSTGRES_PASSWORD:${POSTGRES_PASSWORD:-SovereignSecret2026}\n887: POSTGRES_DB:jan_metadata_store\n888: ports:\n889: -\"5432:5432\"\n890: volumes:\n891: -jan_postgres_data:/var/lib/postgresql/data\n892: restart:always\n893: networks:\n894: -jan-network\n895: volumes:\n896: jan_postgres_data:\n897: driver:local\n898: #!/usr/bin/env python3\n899: # Location: /opt/jan-server/scripts/rehydrate_history.py\n900: import json\n901: import requests\n902: import sys\n903: import uuid\n904: API_GATEWAY = \"http://127.0.0.1:8000\"\n905: GUEST_TOKEN = None\n906: defget_auth_token():\n907: \"\"\"Acquire a secure session token via the Kong API Gateway.\"\"\"\n908: global GUEST_TOKEN\n909: try:\n910:         response = requests.post(f\"{API_GATEWAY}/llm/auth/guest-login\")\n911:         response.raise_for_status()\n912:         GUEST_TOKEN = response.json().get(\"access_token\")\n913:         print(f\"[*] Authenticated to Kong Gateway. Token Active.\")\n914: except Exception as e:Python downloadcontent_copy\n915: --- PAGE 34 ---\n916:         print(f\"[!] Authentication failure: {e}\")\n917:         sys.exit(1)\n918: definject_conversation(title):\n919: \"\"\"Register a distinct conversational workspace inside the server.\"\"\"\n920:     headers = {\n921: \"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {GUEST_TOKEN}\",\n922: \"Content-Type\": application/json\"\n923:     }\n924:     payload = {\n925:         \"title\": title,\n926:         \"meta\": {\"source\": \"Historical Rehydration Frame\"}\n927:     }\n928:     res = requests.post(f\"{API_GATEWAY}/v1/conversations\", json=payload, heade\n929:     return res.json().get(\"id\")\n930: def populate_message_stream(conversation_id, role, content):\n931:     \"\"\"Append structured message objects into the conversation timeline.\"\"\"\n932:     headers = {\n933:         \"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {GUEST_TOKEN}\",\n934:         \"Content-Type\": application/json\"\n935:     }\n936:     payload = {\n937:         \"role\": role,\n938:         \"content\": content\n939:     }\n940:     requests.post(f\"{API_GATEWAY}/v1/conversations/{conversation_id}/messages\"\n941: def process_archive(file_path):\n942:     \"\"\"Parse export payload data for injection.\"\"\"\n943:     get_auth_token()\n944:     with open(file_path, 'r') as f:\n945:         archive_data = json.load(f)\n946:     for chat in archive_data:\n947:         chat_title = chat.get(\"title\", f\"Archive Session - {str(uuid.uuid4())[\n948:         print(f\"[+] Rehydrating Session Workspace: '{chat_title}'\")\n949:         server_conv_id = inject_conversation(chat_title)\n950:         # Walk chronologically through historical nodes\n951:         for msg in chat.get(\"mapping\", {}).values():\n952:             if msg.get(\"message\") and msg[\"message\"].get(\"content\"):\n953:                 role = msg[\"message\"][\"author\"][\"role\"]\n954:                 # Filter out system and utility roles\n955:                 if role in [\"user\", \"assistant\"]:\n956:                     raw_parts = msg[\"message\"][\"content\"].get(\"parts\", [\"\"])\n957:                     clean_text = \" \".join([p for p in raw_parts if isinstance(\n958:                     if clean_text.strip():\n959: --- PAGE 35 ---\n960: Part 3: Service Mapping and Execution Topology\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-960. Use offset=961 to continue.)\n</content>",
