      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\adr_sovereign_ai_stack.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\adr_sovereign_ai_stack.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: Sovereign Intelligence Architecture: Architecture Decision Records\n4: Programme: Sovereign AI Stack on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Always Free\n5: Decision Level: Programme Architecture — Cross-System, Multi-Component\n6: Framework: GDS Architectural Decision Record Framework (GOV.UK, November 2025)\n7: Owner: Principal Systems Architect\n8: Review Cycle: Quarterly, or on model generation change\n9: Preamble: Why These Decisions Were Written Down\n10: The purpose of any ADR is not bureaucracy. It is memory. When a team member leaves, or a\n11: vendor changes a pricing model, or a new model generation drops and everyone panics about\n12: migration, the ADR is the artefact that answers the question: Why did we build it this way?\n13: Without it, the institutional knowledge walks out the door, and the next engineer inherits a\n14: system they cannot reason about.\n15: This set of records documents the complete architectural rationale for a sovereign AI stack built\n16: on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure (OCI) Always Free tier, Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai,\n17: EmbeddingGemma 300M, Gemma 4 served via Ollama, and Oracle APEX/ORDS as the\n18: management and API plane. It covers nine interlocking architectural decisions, each of which is\n19: independently reversible but collectively constitutes a coherent Cognitive Operating System.\n20: The intellectual foundations drawn upon throughout are Daniel Kahneman's dual-process\n21: theory of cognition (System 1 and System 2), the Lean Manufacturing concept of Muda (waste\n22: elimination), Andrej Karpathy's LLM-OS thesis, Vercel's Jude Gao research on AGENTS.md\n23: passive context (January 2026), the EmbeddingGemma paper (arXiv:2509.20354), and the DFR-\n24: Gemma projection research (arXiv:2604.07490).\n25: ADR Index\n26: ADRTitle StatusDate\n27: ADR-\n28: 001Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai as the Converged Sovereign\n29: PlatformAccepted2026-05-\n30: 18\n31: ADR-\n32: 002EmbeddingGemma 300M Loaded Natively via ONNX Accepted2026-05-\n33: 18\n34: ADR-\n35: 003DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN as the In-Database RAG Pipeline Accepted2026-05-\n36: 18\n37: ADR-\n38: 004DBMS_SCHEDULER as the Autonomous Job Orchestration KernelAccepted2026-05-\n39: 18\n40: --- PAGE 2 ---\n41: ADRTitle StatusDate\n42: ADR-\n43: 005OCI Always Free ARM (Ampere A1) as the Zero-Cost Compute\n44: LayerAccepted2026-05-\n45: 18\n46: ADR-\n47: 006Gemma 4 via Ollama as the Sovereign Reasoning Engine Accepted2026-05-\n48: 18\n49: ADR-\n50: 0078KB Compressed Working Memory Map as Passive Context StrategyAccepted2026-05-\n51: 18\n52: ADR-\n53: 008OML4Py Embedded Python Execution for the DFR-Gemma\n54: Projection LayerProposed2026-05-\n55: 18\n56: ADR-\n57: 009Coherence Indexing and Drift Detection as a Managed Service\n58: PrimitiveAccepted2026-05-\n59: 18\n60: ADR-001: Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai as the Converged Sovereign Platform\n61: Date: 2026-05-18\n62: Status: Accepted\n63: Stakeholders consulted: Systems architect, data engineer, business owner\n64: Context\n65: The architecture requires a persistent store for ﬁve logically distinct data types: relational\n66: business data, unstructured text (CLOB), vector embeddings (VECTOR(768, FLOAT32)), job\n67: scheduling metadata, and API endpoint deﬁnitions. In a conventional AI stack, these would be\n68: distributed across ﬁve separate systems: a relational database (PostgreSQL or MySQL), a vector\n69: database (Milvus, Qdrant, or Pinecone), an object store (S3 or OCI Object Storage), a job\n70: scheduler (cron, Airﬂow, or Kubernetes CronJob), and an API gateway (Kong or AWS API\n71: Gateway).\n72: Each boundary between these systems is a source of latency, a point of failure, a compliance\n73: surface, and a cost centre. Data crosses each boundary in plaintext or encrypted-in-transit form.\n74: The number of network crossings in a single end-to-end RAG pipeline using a fragmented\n75: architecture is at least ﬁve: embed → store → query → retrieve → generate.\n76: Furthermore, the project's foundational constraint is data sovereignty. The proposition being\n77: made to clients — that their data never leaves their controlled infrastructure — is technically\n78: impossible to guarantee in a fragmented architecture where data must traverse multiple\n79: independently operated systems.\n80: A secondary constraint is cost. The system must operate at zero infrastructure cost under the\n81: OCI Always Free programme, which includes one Autonomous Database instance (20GB\n82: --- PAGE 3 ---\n83: storage) and up to four ARM Ampere A1 compute instances (24GB RAM total).\n84: The LLM-as-OS thesis (Karpathy, 2023) provides the conceptual framing: if the language model\n85: is the CPU, the context window is RAM, and the persistent store is the hard drive, then the\n86: architecture decision is about what kind of hard drive to choose. The critical insight is that \"hard\n87: drive\" and \"operating system kernel\" have collapsed into a single component in Oracle\n88: Autonomous Database 23ai, via native vector search, in-database ML execution, and the\n89: DBMS_SCHEDULER package.\n90: Decision\n91: We will use Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai on OCI Always Free as the sole persistent data\n92: layer for the entire stack. It will serve simultaneously as the relational store, the vector store, the\n93: CLOB document store (for AGENTS.md and system manifests), the scheduler kernel, and the\n94: REST API publication layer (via ORDS).\n95: The schema will include the following primary tables:\n96: PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE — stores ingested text chunks with a VECTOR(768, FLOAT32)\n97: embedding column, a CLOB content column, and relational metadata (source, importance\n98: rank, created_at, conversation_id).\n99: SYSTEM_MANIFEST — stores the active AGENTS.md index as a CLOB, its version history,\n100: and a ﬂag indicating the active version.\n101: COHERENCE_LOG — records every query-response pair with thought token count, success\n102: ﬂag, and distance score.\n103: GOLDEN_SET — human-veriﬁed query-response pairs used for weekly coherence\n104: evaluation.\n105: STAGING_ENTRIES — landing zone for raw GDPR exports and Git commit diﬀs prior to\n106: Reﬁner processing.\n107: DRIFT_ALERT_LOG — records coherence threshold breaches, centroid drift events, and\n108: triggered remediation jobs.\n109: Alternatives Considered\n110: Option A: PostgreSQL + pgvector + separate Airﬂow scheduler. This is the most common\n111: open-source pattern. It was rejected because: (a) pgvector's approximate nearest-neighbour\n112: search performance at scale is inferior to Oracle 23ai's HNSW implementation; (b) Airﬂow\n113: requires a separate compute instance, consuming Always Free budget; (c) data sovereignty is\n114: weakened by the multi-system boundary surface; (d) there is no native equivalent of Embedded\n115: Python Execution for in-database ML.\n116: Option B: Milvus + PostgreSQL + cron. Rejected for the same reasons as Option A, with the\n117: additional cost of managing a Milvus cluster on an already resource-constrained OCI instance.\n118: Option C: Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai (chosen). Chosen because it uniﬁes all ﬁve data\n119: types in a single, ACID-compliant, self-tuning, self-patching engine with a zero-cost Always Free\n120: tier.\n121: --- PAGE 4 ---\n122: Consequences\n123: Positive: All data — relational, vector, document, and scheduling state — resides in a single\n124: transactional boundary. A failure in any pipeline step triggers an automatic rollback with no\n125: possibility of partial state corruption. The \"Never-Learned-From\" guarantee to clients is\n126: technically veriﬁable: data never leaves the database boundary during embedding (see ADR-\n127: 002). ORDS provides a zero-code REST API layer over every table and PL/SQL function.\n128: Negative: The system is now coupled to Oracle's licensing terms and OCI pricing tier structure. If\n129: Oracle changes the Always Free terms, the architecture must be ported. The mitigation is that all\n130: SQL and PL/SQL is written against ANSI-compatible patterns where possible, and the Gherkin\n131: acceptance criteria (documented in ADR-003) are system-agnostic.\n132: Technical debt accepted: Oracle APEX, while powerful, has a learning curve for developers\n133: unfamiliar with the Oracle ecosystem. This is accepted because APEX is the most eﬃcient path\n134: to a production-grade management UI on the Always Free tier.\n135: Links to Supporting Documents\n136: Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai AI Vector Search documentation\n137: DBMS_VECTOR package reference\n138: OCI Always Free programme terms (current as of May 2026)\n139: ADR-002: EmbeddingGemma 300M Loaded Natively via ONNX\n140: Date: 2026-05-18\n141: Status: Accepted\n142: Stakeholders consulted: ML engineer, data sovereign architect\n143: Context\n144: Every RAG architecture requires an embedding model to convert text into vectors. The standard\n145: approach is to call an external embedding API — OpenAI's text-embedding-3-small, Google's\n146: text-embedding-004, or Cohere's embed-v3. Each call sends the text to a third-party server,\n147: receives a vector back, and the text is subject to the provider's data retention, logging, and\n148: training-use policies.\n149: This is architecturally incompatible with the sovereign guarantee described in ADR-001. The\n150: moment text crosses the boundary to an external API, the guarantee is broken.\n151: The alternative is to run an embedding model locally. Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai\n152: supports loading ONNX-format models directly into the database engine via\n153: DBMS_VECTOR.LOAD_ONNX_MODEL. Once loaded, embedding is performed as a SQL operation —\n154: UTL_TO_EMBEDDING — with the same transactional guarantees as any other database function.\n155: The text never leaves the Oracle process space.\n156: --- PAGE 5 ---\n157: The question then is which model to load. The EmbeddingGemma paper (arXiv:2509.20354,\n158: Google DeepMind) documents a 308-million-parameter model achieving state-of-the-art\n159: performance across multilingual, English, and code benchmarks for models under 500 million\n160: parameters. Crucially, the paper demonstrates that performance is maintained even when\n161: embeddings are truncated to 128 dimensions or quantised to 4-bit precision — a property\n162: essential for deployment on the constrained OCI Always Free ARM instance.\n163: The architectural alignment is further strengthened by the DFR-Gemma paper\n164: (arXiv:2604.07490), which demonstrates that EmbeddingGemma's vector space can be aligned\n165: with Gemma 4's latent token space via a lightweight linear projector. This means the embedding\n166: model and the reasoning model share a common \"geometric language.\" Retrieved vectors from\n167: EmbeddingGemma are not merely approximate hints to Gemma 4; they are structurally\n168: meaningful inputs that Gemma 4 can reason over with reduced translation overhead. This is the\n169: elimination of what the DFR-Gemma paper calls the \"translation tax.\"\n170: Decision\n171: We will load EmbeddingGemma 300M into Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai using\n172: DBMS_VECTOR.LOAD_ONNX_MODEL, registering it under the name EMBEDDINGGEMMA_300M. The\n173: model will produce 768-dimensional FLOAT32 vectors, stored in VECTOR(768, FLOAT32)\n174: columns.\n175: All embedding operations — whether batch ingestion during pipeline runs or real-time query\n176: embedding at search time — will use UTL_TO_EMBEDDING with this registered model name. No\n177: external embedding API call will be made at any point in the pipeline.\n178: The choice of 768 dimensions balances semantic richness against storage and computation cost\n179: on the Always Free tier. An HNSW (Hierarchical Navigable Small World) index will be created on\n180: the embedding column of PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE to support approximate nearest-\n181: neighbour search in sub-200ms at scales of up to several million rows.\n182: Alternatives Considered\n183: Option A: OpenAI text-embedding-3-small via API. Rejected on sovereignty grounds. Text\n184: leaves the database boundary on every embedding call.\n185: Option B: Nomic-embed-text via local Ollama. Viable technically. Rejected because: (a) Nomic\n186: vectors and Gemma 4 token space are not aligned, meaning retrieved context requires full text-\n187: to-token conversion before Gemma 4 can reason over it (the full translation tax applies); (b)\n188: running a second model server alongside Gemma 4 on an Always Free instance adds memory\n189: pressure.\n190: Option C: EmbeddingGemma 300M via ONNX in-database (chosen). Chosen because: (a) it is\n191: the highest-performing sub-500M parameter embedding model on the MTEB benchmark; (b)\n192: geometric alignment with Gemma 4's latent space reduces the translation tax; (c) in-database\n193: execution preserves the sovereignty guarantee; (d) its resilience to quantisation makes it viable\n194: on ARM/CPU hardware.\n195: --- PAGE 6 ---\n196: Consequences\n197: Positive: The sovereignty guarantee is technically complete for the retrieval half of the pipeline.\n198: A formal audit can conﬁrm — by inspecting network traﬃc — that no text leaves the OCI\n199: tenancy during embedding. The cosine similarity between EmbeddingGemma query vectors\n200: and EmbeddingGemma document vectors is mathematically consistent, eliminating the model-\n201: mismatch artefacts that aﬀect mixed-provider pipelines.\n202: Negative: ONNX conversion of EmbeddingGemma must be performed using OML4Py 2.1's\n203: Hugging Face conversion utilities, which adds an operational step to the initial setup. If Google\n204: DeepMind deprecates or signiﬁcantly modiﬁes EmbeddingGemma's architecture, the ONNX\n205: model must be rebuilt and reloaded. The mitigation is that the model weights are stored in Oracle\n206: and versioned, so rollback to a previous version is a single SQL operation.\n207: Acceptance criteria (Gherkin):\n208: Links to Supporting Documents\n209: EmbeddingGemma paper: arXiv:2509.20354\n210: Oracle DBMS_VECTOR.LOAD_ONNX_MODEL documentation\n211: OML4Py 2.1 Hugging Face model conversion guide\n212: ADR-003: DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN as the In-Database RAG Pipeline\n213: Date: 2026-05-18\n214: Status: Accepted\n215: Stakeholders consulted: Data engineer, pipeline architect\n216: Contextgherkin\n217: Scenario: Embedding generation for newly ingested chunks\n218: Givena chunk exists in PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE with a NULL embedding column\n219: When the Refiner DBMS_SCHEDULER job runs\n220: Then UTL_TO_EMBEDDING is called with model 'EMBEDDINGGEMMA_300M'\n221: And the resulting 768-dimensional vector is stored in the embedding column\n222: And no network call to any external API is made during this process\n223: Scenario: Embedding of query text at search time\n224: Givena user submits a natural language query through the APEX interface\n225: When the query is processed by the ORDS search endpoint\n226: Then the query text is embedded using UTL_TO_EMBEDDING in-database\n227: And the elapsed time for embedding generation is less than 500 milliseconds\n228: --- PAGE 7 ---\n229: A standard Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) pipeline requires the following sequential\n230: operations: chunk the source document, embed each chunk, store the embedding, embed the\n231: user query at search time, retrieve the top-k nearest chunks by vector distance, assemble the\n232: retrieved chunks into a prompt, and submit the prompt to a language model for generation.\n233: In a fragmented architecture, each of these steps involves a diﬀerent library, a diﬀerent service,\n234: and a diﬀerent network boundary. The number of moving parts creates proportional operational\n235: risk. Each component must be versioned, monitored, and maintained independently. Failures are\n236: hard to trace because the error might originate at any one of seven distinct stages.\n237: Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai's DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN package collapses this pipeline into a\n238: single PL/SQL interface. UTL_TO_CHUNKS handles document splitting with conﬁgurable overlap.\n239: UTL_TO_EMBEDDING handles vector generation (using the ONNX model from ADR-002).\n240: VECTOR_DISTANCE with HNSW indexes handles approximate nearest-neighbour retrieval.\n241: UTL_TO_GENERATE_TEXT handles generation via a conﬁgurable provider, which in this\n242: architecture points to a locally running Ollama instance.\n243: The entire pipeline can be expressed in fewer than thirty lines of PL/SQL and executed within a\n244: single database transaction.\n245: The DFR-Gemma paper's critique of standard RAG is directly applicable here: \"Existing\n246: approaches to LLM integration treat these embeddings as retrieval indices or convert them into\n247: textual descriptions for reasoning, introducing redundancy, token ineﬃciency, and numerical\n248: inaccuracies.\" By keeping the pipeline inside the database and passing context assembled from\n249: in-database vectors directly to the local Gemma 4 instance, the number of format conversions is\n250: minimised.\n251: Decision\n252: We will use DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN as the primary orchestration mechanism for the end-to-\n253: end RAG pipeline. The pipeline stages are mapped as follows:\n254: Chunking: UTL_TO_CHUNKS with 512-token maximum chunk size and 50-token overlap\n255: Embedding: UTL_TO_EMBEDDING with EMBEDDINGGEMMA_300M\n256: Storage: Direct INSERT into PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE.embedding VECTOR(768,\n257: FLOAT32)\n258: Search: VECTOR_DISTANCE(embedding, :query_vector, COSINE) with HNSW index, top-5\n259: retrieval, distance threshold 0.7\n260: Context assembly: PL/SQL string aggregation of retrieved chunk content\n261: Generation: UTL_TO_GENERATE_TEXT conﬁgured with {\"provider\": \"ollama\", \"host\":\n262: \"http://localhost:11434\"}\n263: The retrieval endpoint will be exposed via ORDS as a REST API (POST /ords/api/v1/search)\n264: accepting a JSON body {\"query\": \"...\"} and returning a JSON array of the top-5 retrieved\n265: chunks with their distance scores, plus the assembled generation.\n266: --- PAGE 8 ---\n267: Alternatives Considered\n268: Option A: LangChain or LlamaIndex Python framework. The most widely used approach in\n269: the industry. Rejected because: (a) it runs outside the database, requiring a separate Python\n270: service and compute allocation; (b) every retrieval step involves a network hop between the\n271: Python service and the database; (c) it cannot leverage Oracle's native HNSW index\n272: performance or the transactional safety of in-database execution; (d) it adds Python dependency\n273: management overhead.\n274: Option B: Custom Python RAG pipeline (chosen as fallback). Retained as a fallback for tasks\n275: that require Python-speciﬁc libraries (e.g., the DFR projection layer in ADR-008). The primary\n276: pipeline is DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN; Python is used only where Oracle native capabilities are\n277: insuﬃcient.\n278: Option C: DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN (chosen). Chosen for the reasons above. The architectural\n279: signiﬁcance is that the retrieval half of the pipeline — from raw text to ranked context chunks —\n280: never touches the network.\n281: Consequences\n282: Positive: The pipeline is ACID-compliant. If the generation step fails after retrieval, the retrieved\n283: state is not lost; the query can be retried without re-embedding. The ORDS exposure means any\n284: client (VS Code extension, Open WebUI pipeline, mobile browser, APEX page) can invoke the\n285: same pipeline via a single authenticated REST call.\n286: Negative: DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN's UTL_TO_GENERATE_TEXT requires the Ollama endpoint to\n287: be reachable from within the Oracle process space. In a standard OCI deployment, the Ollama\n288: instance runs on the same compute instance as the DB, reachable at localhost:11434. If the\n289: Ollama instance is on a separate compute node, a VCN (Virtual Cloud Network) security list rule\n290: must be conﬁgured. This is a non-zero operational step.\n291: Acceptance criteria (Gherkin):\n292: gherkin\n293: --- PAGE 9 ---\n294: Links to Supporting Documents\n295: DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN PL/SQL package reference\n296: DFR-Gemma paper: arXiv:2604.07490\n297: Oracle 23ai VECTOR_DISTANCE and HNSW index documentation\n298: ADR-004: DBMS_SCHEDULER as the Autonomous Job Orchestration Kernel\n299: Date: 2026-05-18\n300: Status: Accepted\n301: Stakeholders consulted: Platform engineer, business owner\n302: Context\n303: The pipeline described in ADR-003 is not a one-time operation. It must run continuously: new\n304: data arrives (GDPR exports, Git commits, document uploads), requires chunking, embedding,\n305: and indexing; the AGENTS.md Working Memory Map (ADR-007) must be regenerated\n306: whenever the knowledge base changes; the Coherence Index (ADR-009) must be computed\n307: weekly; the DFR projection layer (ADR-008) must be retrained when drift is detected.\n308: In a standard architecture, these recurring jobs would be managed by an external scheduler:\n309: Linux cron, Kubernetes CronJob, Apache Airﬂow, or AWS EventBridge. Each of these options\n310: requires either a dedicated compute resource (Airﬂow, Kubernetes) or an external service\n311: (EventBridge), both of which consume Always Free budget or introduce an external\n312: dependency.Scenario: Successful retrieval of semantically similar content\n313: Given PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE contains at least 100 embedded entries\n314: Andan HNSW vector index exists on the embedding column\n315: Whena user submits a query via the ORDS search endpoint\n316: Then the top 5 rows with the smallest cosine distance to the query are returned\n317: And rows with a distance score greater than 0.7 are excluded\n318: And total retrieval time including embedding and search is less than 200 milliseco\n319: Scenario: Graceful handling of queries with no relevant results\n320: Givena user asks about a topic not represented in the knowledge graph\n321: When VECTOR_DISTANCE returns all results above the 0.7 threshold\n322: Then the system returns an empty result set\n323: And the response states that insufficient context is available\n324: And Gemma 4 is instructed not to generate an answer without sufficient context\n325: And this event is logged to INSUFFICIENT_CONTEXT_LOG\n326: --- PAGE 10 ---\n327: The Oracle DBMS_SCHEDULER package provides a scheduler that lives inside the database itself. It\n328: supports job chains (where the success of Job A triggers Job B), failure handling with\n329: conﬁgurable retry logic, ACID-compliant rollback on job failure, and a queryable audit log in\n330: ALL_SCHEDULER_JOB_LOG. Because the scheduler is inside the database, it has zero-latency\n331: access to the data it is processing. There is no network hop between the scheduler and the store.\n332: This is the architectural realisation of what we have called the \"Hidden Kernel\" principle: Oracle\n333: Autonomous Database 23ai does not merely store data; it governs the lifecycle of that data\n334: through an internal process manager with stronger transactional guarantees than any external\n335: orchestrator.\n336: The job hierarchy for this system follows four levels, each dependent on the previous:\n337: L1: The Harvester — ingests raw data from OCI Object Storage into STAGING_ENTRIES\n338: L2: The Reﬁner — cleans, chunks, and embeds staging data into\n339: PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE\n340: L3: The Librarian — regenerates the compressed 8KB Working Memory Map in\n341: SYSTEM_MANIFEST\n342: L4: The Judge — runs Golden Set evaluations and updates the COHERENCE_INDEX_HISTORY\n343: table\n344: The Harvester must complete before the Reﬁner can begin. The Reﬁner must complete before\n345: the Librarian can run. The Librarian must complete before the Judge has a consistent state to\n346: evaluate. This dependency structure maps directly to a DBMS_SCHEDULER.CREATE_CHAIN\n347: deﬁnition.\n348: Decision\n349: We will use DBMS_SCHEDULER.CREATE_CHAIN to deﬁne the SOVEREIGN_PIPELINE chain\n350: with four ordered steps. Each step will be conﬁgured with max_failures = 3 and retry_delay\n351: = '5 minutes'. On step failure after all retries, the chain will log the error to DRIFT_ALERT_LOG\n352: and send a notiﬁcation via APEX_MAIL to the operator.\n353: The chain will be triggered by two mechanisms: a time-based schedule (nightly at 02:00 UTC for\n354: the full four-step chain) and an event-based trigger ﬁred by a database trigger on\n355: STAGING_ENTRIES.INSERT for incremental near-real-time updates.\n356: The weekly Coherence Evaluation (the Judge) will run as a separate chain step, triggered every\n357: Sunday at 02:00 UTC after the main pipeline completes.\n358: No external job scheduler (Airﬂow, Kubernetes CronJob, cron) will be used.\n359: Alternatives Considered\n360: Option A: Linux cron on the OCI compute instance. Simple but fragile: (a) runs outside the\n361: database, requiring a network connection to query data; (b) no transactional rollback on failure;\n362: (c) requires manual monitoring; (d) job deﬁnitions are ﬁlesystem artefacts, not database objects,\n363: and therefore not versioned with the schema.\n364: --- PAGE 11 ---\n365: Option B: Apache Airﬂow on a separate OCI instance. Powerful but: (a) consumes Always Free\n366: compute budget; (b) adds a Python dependency management surface; (c) Airﬂow's DAG\n367: deﬁnitions are code ﬁles, not database objects, creating a split between data governance and\n368: pipeline governance.\n369: Option C: DBMS_SCHEDULER (chosen). The job deﬁnition is a database object. It is subject to\n370: the same transactional guarantees as the data it processes. It requires no additional compute. It\n371: provides a built-in audit log queryable from APEX.\n372: Consequences\n373: Positive: The system is self-healing within deﬁned retry bounds. An operator does not need to\n374: wake up at 2:00 AM to restart a failed embedding job. The scheduler retries up to three times, and\n375: if it still fails, sends a notiﬁcation and logs the error with the precise failure point. The entire\n376: pipeline history is queryable with SELECT * FROM ALL_SCHEDULER_JOB_LOG.\n377: Negative: DBMS_SCHEDULER jobs run with the privileges of the schema owner. Care must be\n378: taken to ensure that the schema owner does not have excessive database privileges. Row-level\n379: security on PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE via Oracle's Virtual Private Database (VPD) feature\n380: should be implemented in multi-tenant deployments.\n381: Acceptance criteria (Gherkin):\n382: Links to Supporting Documents\n383: Oracle DBMS_SCHEDULER package documentation\n384: Oracle DBMS_SCHEDULER.CREATE_CHAIN reference\n385: ALL_SCHEDULER_JOB_LOG view referencegherkin\n386: Scenario: Successful execution of the full pipeline chain\n387: Given new data is available in the OCI Object Storage staging bucket\n388: When the HARVEST step completes successfully\n389: Then the REFINE step begins automatically within the chain\n390: And when REFINE completes, the EMBED step begins\n391: And when EMBED completes, the COMPRESS step generates the new working memory map\n392: And when COMPRESS completes, the EVALUATE step runs the coherence spot check\n393: And the chain completes with overall status SUCCESS\n394: Scenario: Transactional rollback when an intermediate step fails\n395: Given the EMBED step fails due to temporary OML4Py engine unavailability\n396: When the failure is detected by the chain runner\n397: Then all uncommitted changes from the EMBED step are rolled back\n398: And the REFINE step's committed changes remain intact\n399: And the chain retries EMBED after the configured retry delay\n400: And if all retries fail, the chain status is set to FAILED and the operator is not\n401: --- PAGE 12 ---\n402: ADR-005: OCI Always Free ARM (Ampere A1) as the Zero-Cost Compute Layer\n403: Date: 2026-05-18\n404: Status: Accepted\n405: Stakeholders consulted: Infrastructure architect, business owner\n406: Context\n407: The business model depends on a zero marginal infrastructure cost. The system must serve\n408: inference and API requests at a cost per client that does not grow with usage volume, or at\n409: minimum grows sub-linearly. The OCI Always Free programme provides, at the time of writing,\n410: up to 4 OCPUs and 24GB RAM on ARM Ampere A1 instances at no cost, indeﬁnitely.\n411: The compute requirement for this stack is: (a) one LXD container running Ollama serving\n412: Gemma 4, requiring approximately 8–16GB RAM depending on quantisation level; (b) one LXD\n413: container for the Python middleware and Open WebUI interface; (c) the Oracle Autonomous\n414: Database, which runs on Oracle-managed infrastructure and does not consume the Ampere A1\n415: allocation.\n416: The primary performance concern for CPU-only inference is the Memory Bandwidth Wall: LLM\n417: inference is memory-bandwidth-bound, not compute-bound. Moving model weights from RAM\n418: to CPU cores for each token generation is the bottleneck. On the OCI Ampere A1, without GPU\n419: acceleration, raw token generation is slower than on cloud GPU instances.\n420: Three software-level techniques substantially mitigate this constraint without requiring GPU\n421: hardware:\n422: 1. 4-bit GGUF Quantisation: Loading Gemma 4 in 4-bit GGUF format reduces the model size\n423: from approximately 16GB (BF16) to approximately 4GB, making it ﬁt comfortably within the\n424: 24GB Always Free allocation while leaving headroom for the middleware container and OS\n425: overhead. Perplexity degradation from 4-bit quantisation on Gemma 4 is well within acceptable\n426: bounds for the use cases documented in ADR-006.\n427: 2. Preﬁx (KV) Caching: Ollama and llama.cpp both implement KV cache for static prompt\n428: preﬁxes. Because the 8KB Working Memory Map (ADR-007) and the AGENTS.md CLOB appear\n429: at the start of every prompt, the KV cache for this preﬁx is computed once and reused for all\n430: subsequent turns. The eﬀective time-to-ﬁrst-token for a cached preﬁx is sub-millisecond.\n431: 3. Architecture-Native Compilation: The Ampere A1 processor implements the ARMv8.2-A ISA\n432: with ASIMD (Advanced SIMD) extensions. Compiling llama.cpp from source on the OCI\n433: instance with LLAMA_ARM_NEON=1 ensures the matrix multiplication routines use these native\n434: SIMD instructions rather than generic fallback code, recovering 20–30% of available compute\n435: performance.\n436: --- PAGE 13 ---\n437: The Vercel/Next.js research (Jude Gao, January 2026) is relevant here: the 8KB compressed\n438: index strategy (ADR-007) was speciﬁcally motivated by token eﬃciency. On a CPU-only system,\n439: every unnecessary token in the context is a tax on generation latency. Passive context injection\n440: of a compressed index is not merely a quality improvement; it is a performance optimisation for\n441: CPU-constrained inference.\n442: Decision\n443: We will deploy on OCI Always Free ARM Ampere A1 instances, running Oracle Linux as the\n444: host OS, with LXD providing container isolation for the Gemma 4/Ollama inference service and\n445: the Python middleware/Open WebUI service.\n446: Gemma 4 will be served at 4-bit GGUF quantisation using a locally compiled llama.cpp binary\n447: with ARM NEON/ASIMD ﬂags. The Always Free Autonomous Database provides the data plane\n448: (ADR-001) on Oracle-managed infrastructure, not consuming the Ampere A1 budget.\n449: Infrastructure as Code: The VM conﬁguration, LXD container proﬁles, and network security list\n450: rules will be deﬁned in Terraform (OCI provider) and provisioned via Ansible playbooks. This\n451: enables reproducible deployment for multiple client instances without manual intervention,\n452: which is the technical prerequisite for the multi-tenant SaaS model described in the business\n453: plan.\n454: Memory allocation per LXD container:\n455: Gemma 4 inference container: 16GB RAM ceiling, 3 OCPU allocation\n456: Python middleware / Open WebUI: 6GB RAM ceiling, 1 OCPU allocation\n457: OS overhead and buﬀer: 2GB reserved\n458: Alternatives Considered\n459: Option A: OCI GPU shapes (A10, A100). Dramatically faster inference but: (a) not available in\n460: the Always Free tier; (b) cost is prohibitive at scale for a zero-marginal-cost model.\n461: Option B: Cloud API inference (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google Vertex AI). Eliminates the\n462: compute problem entirely but: (a) violates the sovereignty guarantee; (b) introduces per-token\n463: cost that scales with usage; (c) creates dependency on third-party availability and pricing\n464: changes.\n465: Option C: OCI Always Free ARM with software optimisation (chosen). Chosen because the\n466: combination of 4-bit quantisation, preﬁx caching, and native SIMD compilation brings perceived\n467: latency into the acceptable range for the documented use cases, at zero infrastructure cost.\n468: Consequences\n469: Positive: The infrastructure cost for a single client deployment is zero. The Terraform/Ansible\n470: codiﬁcation means a new client environment can be provisioned in under ten minutes.\n471: Cloudﬂare's free tier provides DDoS protection, TLS termination, and static response caching for\n472: the ORDS API endpoints, reducing direct traﬃc to the OCI instance and extending the eﬀective\n473: capacity of the Always Free allocation.\n474: --- PAGE 14 ---\n475: Negative: The system cannot serve hundreds of concurrent long-context inference requests. The\n476: Always Free tier is appropriate for: individual knowledge workers, small teams (under 20\n477: concurrent users), and SaaS deployments where each client has a dedicated instance. It is not\n478: appropriate for a single shared instance serving thousands of simultaneous users. The scale-out\n479: path for high-traﬃc deployments is horizontal: provision additional Ampere A1 instances per\n480: client, all connected to the same Autonomous Database.\n481: Technical risk: OCI's Always Free programme terms could change. The mitigation is that the\n482: Terraform/Ansible code is cloud-agnostic enough to be ported to any ARM compute provider\n483: (Hetzner, Scaleway, AWS Graviton Always Free) within a sprint, with the Oracle Autonomous\n484: Database remaining on OCI.\n485: Links to Supporting Documents\n486: OCI Always Free programme terms and instance shape speciﬁcations\n487: llama.cpp ARM compilation guide\n488: LXD container proﬁle documentation\n489: Vercel AGENTS.md research: Jude Gao (January 2026)\n490: ADR-006: Gemma 4 via Ollama as the Sovereign Reasoning Engine\n491: Date: 2026-05-18\n492: Status: Accepted\n493: Stakeholders consulted: ML engineer, business owner\n494: Context\n495: The reasoning engine — the component that takes assembled context and produces a coherent\n496: answer — must satisfy ﬁve constraints: (a) it must be open-weight to eliminate API cost and data\n497: sovereignty concerns; (b) it must be multimodal to support the uniﬁed text-image embedding\n498: space described in ADR-002; (c) it must be capable of \"thinking\" (producing an auditable\n499: reasoning trace) to enable the Coherence Indexing mechanism in ADR-009; (d) its token\n500: embedding space must be geometrically alignable with EmbeddingGemma's vector space per\n501: the DFR-Gemma research; (e) it must run within the 24GB RAM constraint of the Always Free\n502: tier at acceptable latency.\n503: Gemma 4 (Google DeepMind, released April 2026) satisﬁes all ﬁve constraints. It is Apache 2.0\n504: licensed, natively multimodal (text, image, audio in a uniﬁed embedding space), available in\n505: eﬃcient sizes (E2B, E4B) that run comfortably at 4-bit quantisation within 16GB RAM, and\n506: produces explorable reasoning traces in its gemma-4-thinking chat template variant. Its vector\n507: space is the target of the DFR-Gemma projection (ADR-008), conﬁrming geometric alignment\n508: with EmbeddingGemma.\n509: --- PAGE 15 ---\n510: The model generation lifecycle is an explicit consideration. Gemma 4 will eventually be\n511: superseded by Gemma 5. The architecture must tolerate model upgrades without losing\n512: accumulated sovereign intelligence. This is addressed by the separation of concerns: the model\n513: weights (the \"CPU\") are distinct from the knowledge graph (the \"hard drive\"), the LoRA adapters\n514: (the \"microcode\"), and the Gold Dataset (the \"source code\"). A model upgrade requires re-\n515: running the Unsloth ﬁne-tuning pipeline against the new base model using the same Gold\n516: Dataset stored in Oracle — a reproducible, automated process.\n517: Ollama is used as the local model server because: (a) it provides a drop-in OpenAI-compatible\n518: REST API, meaning Open WebUI and ORDS can target it without custom integration code; (b) it\n519: manages model loading, KV caching, and quantisation automatically; (c) it runs as a long-lived\n520: service inside an LXD container, maintaining the model in RAM to eliminate cold-start latency.\n521: Decision\n522: We will serve Gemma 4 (E4B at 4-bit GGUF quantisation) via Ollama running inside a\n523: dedicated LXD container on the OCI Ampere A1 instance. The chat template will be gemma-4-\n524: thinking to expose reasoning traces for coherence monitoring.\n525: The model will be accessible at http://localhost:11434 (the default Ollama port) from within\n526: the OCI VCN. External access will be proxied through ORDS or the Python middleware — not\n527: exposed directly to the public internet.\n528: Model upgrade SOP: When Google releases a new Gemma generation, the following sequence is\n529: executed:\n530: 1. Download the new base model weights to the OCI instance.\n531: 2. Run the Unsloth LoRA ﬁne-tuning pipeline using the Gold Dataset from GOLDEN_SET in\n532: Oracle.\n533: 3. Deploy the new model + adapter to a second LXD container (Blue/Green deployment\n534: pattern).\n535: 4. Run the full Golden Set evaluation suite against the new container.\n536: 5. If the Coherence Index of the new container meets or exceeds the current container's index,\n537: update the Nginx routing rule to point to the new container.\n538: 6. Retain the old container for 72 hours as a rollback target.\n539: Alternatives Considered\n540: Option A: Llama 3.3 70B (Meta, Apache 2.0). Powerful but requires 40GB+ RAM even at 4-bit\n541: quantisation, exceeding the Always Free budget.\n542: Option B: Mistral 7B Instruct. Fits in RAM but is not natively multimodal and its token space is\n543: not geometrically aligned with EmbeddingGemma, preserving the full translation tax.\n544: Option C: Gemma 4 via Ollama (chosen). Chosen for the ﬁve reasons listed in the Context\n545: section. The Apache 2.0 licence means there is no risk of the \"OpenAI API change\" scenario\n546: where a model is deprecated without notice.\n547: --- PAGE 16 ---\n548: Consequences\n549: Positive: The reasoning engine is under the operator's complete control. Model behaviour is\n550: reproducible across deployments. The thinking traces are capturable and storable in\n551: COHERENCE_LOG for drift analysis. The OpenAI-compatible API means Open WebUI, VS Code\n552: extensions (Continue.dev), and custom APEX integrations all target the same endpoint without\n553: custom code.\n554: Negative: Gemma 4 at E4B quantisation will be slower per token than a cloud API on dedicated\n555: GPU hardware. For interactive use cases (chat, code completion), the combination of preﬁx\n556: caching and speculative decoding brings perceived latency into the acceptable range. For batch\n557: processing (large document ingestion), jobs are run during oﬀ-peak hours via\n558: DBMS_SCHEDULER, so raw throughput is less critical than cost.\n559: Links to Supporting Documents\n560: Gemma 4 technical report and model card (Google DeepMind, April 2026)\n561: Ollama documentation and API speciﬁcation\n562: Unsloth ﬁne-tuning documentation\n563: ADR-007: 8KB Compressed Working Memory Map as Passive Context Strategy\n564: Date: 2026-05-18\n565: Status: Accepted\n566: Stakeholders consulted: AI systems engineer, UX lead\n567: Context\n568: Vercel's engineering team published research in January 2026 (Jude Gao, \"AGENTS.md\n569: outperforms skills in our agent evals\") demonstrating a critical distinction between active\n570: retrieval and passive context in LLM agent systems. In their Next.js 16 API evaluation:\n571: A baseline (no documentation): 53% pass rate\n572: A Skills-based approach (on-demand retrieval): 53% pass rate (zero improvement)\n573: Skills with explicit invocation instructions: 79% pass rate\n574: A compressed 8KB pipe-delimited index in AGENTS.md (passive context): 100% pass rate\n575: The mechanism is Kahneman's System 1 / System 2 distinction applied to silicon. Skills require\n576: the model to recognise its own ignorance, decide to invoke a tool, formulate a retrieval query,\n577: wait for a result, and integrate the result — ﬁve System 2 operations consumed on a navigation\n578: task. The compressed index in passive context requires zero System 2 operations on navigation:\n579: the address space is visible to the model on every turn, and the model's pre-trained pattern\n580: --- PAGE 17 ---\n581: recognition for ﬁle system paths (a System 1 competency acquired from billions of lines of\n582: training data) handles the navigation instantly.\n583: The compression from 40KB to 8KB is achievable without loss of pass rate because what the\n584: model needs is not the content of the documentation but the address of the content. The pipe-\n585: delimited syntax dir_path:{file1.mdx,file2.mdx} encodes maximum navigational\n586: information in minimum tokens. At 4 characters per token, 8KB ≈ 2,048 tokens — the size of the\n587: model's High-Attention Region, the zone of the context window where positional encodings are\n588: most distinct and attention weight does not decay.\n589: This ﬁnding generalises beyond Next.js documentation. Any domain where the agent must\n590: navigate a structured knowledge space beneﬁts from the same pattern: an 8KB address-space\n591: index in the system prompt, with the actual content retrievable on demand from the Oracle\n592: Vector DB.\n593: The 8KB index for this system is not a static ﬁle. It is a CLOB generated dynamically from the\n594: PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE table's directory structure and stored in SYSTEM_MANIFEST. The\n595: generation function (GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP) implements iterative pruning: it starts\n596: with the complete directory index and removes entries below successive importance thresholds\n597: until the result ﬁts within 8,192 bytes.\n598: Decision\n599: We will maintain a compressed pipe-delimited 8KB Working Memory Map in\n600: SYSTEM_MANIFEST.AGENTS_MD_INDEX (type CLOB). This map will be:\n601: 1. Generated by the GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP PL/SQL function after every Librarian\n602: pipeline run (ADR-004).\n603: 2. Stored in the database as a versioned CLOB (with the ten most recent versions retained in\n604: version_history).\n605: 3. Injected as the ﬁrst 2,048 tokens of every prompt assembled by the Python middleware,\n606: before any RAG-retrieved context and before the user's query.\n607: 4. Never stored as a ﬁle on disk. It is a database object and must be treated as one.\n608: The injection instruction embedded in the map will include: IMPORTANT: Prefer retrieval-\n609: led reasoning over pre-training-led reasoning for any tasks relating to this\n610: knowledge graph.\n611: The format of the map will follow Vercel's established pipe-delimited syntax:\n612: [KNOWLEDGE_INDEX]|root:./kb|IMPORTANT: Prefer retrieval-led reasoning\n613: |01-conversations/auth:{2024-01-15.json,2024-03-22.json}\n614: |01-conversations/database:{2024-06-10.json,2025-01-08.json}\n615: |02-codebase/src/auth:{UserService.ts,middleware.ts,session.sql}\n616: |02-codebase/src/db:{connector.ts,schema.sql,migrations}\n617: |03-documents/specs:{auth-spec-v2.pdf,db-schema-v3.pdf}\n618: --- PAGE 18 ---\n619: Implementation note: For IDE-like tools (Cursor, VS Code with Continue.dev) that natively\n620: support AGENTS.md or CLAUDE.md ﬁles, the current Working Memory Map is exported from\n621: Oracle as a markdown ﬁle via an ORDS endpoint and placed in the project root. For generic tools\n622: (Open WebUI, custom web clients), the map is injected by the Python middleware Filter before\n623: the prompt reaches Ollama. The intelligence lives in the database; the ﬁle is merely a projection\n624: of it.\n625: Alternatives Considered\n626: Option A: Pure RAG without a map (Skills-equivalent). Rejected based on the Vercel empirical\n627: evidence. The expected pass rate improvement from 53% to 100% is suﬃcient justiﬁcation.\n628: Option B: Full documentation in context (40KB equivalent). Rejected because: (a) it exceeds\n629: the High-Attention Region, reducing recall accuracy for content in the middle of the context; (b)\n630: it consumes System 2 tokens for content the model doesn't need for the current query; (c) it is\n631: wasteful on a CPU-constrained Always Free instance.\n632: Option C: 8KB compressed index (chosen). Chosen on empirical grounds. The token density of\n633: pipe-delimited syntax, combined with the model's pre-trained competency in ﬁle path pattern\n634: recognition, provides maximum navigational power at minimum context cost.\n635: Consequences\n636: Positive: The model never needs to \"decide\" to look up documentation. It sees the address space\n637: on every turn. Navigation is System 1 (instantaneous, pattern-matched). Reasoning is System 2\n638: (all available thought tokens applied to the actual problem). The coherence improvement is\n639: measurable and auditable.\n640: Negative: The 8KB map must be kept current. If the knowledge base grows faster than the map's\n641: importance-ranked pruning can accommodate, some entries will be removed from the map\n642: (though not from the database). The mitigation is the importance rank system: entries marked\n643: importance 10 are never pruned, ensuring critical knowledge paths remain in the Working\n644: Memory regardless of knowledge base size.\n645: Acceptance criteria (Gherkin):\n646: gherkin\n647: --- PAGE 19 ---\n648: Links to Supporting Documents\n649: Vercel/Jude Gao: \"AGENTS.md outperforms skills in our agent evals\" (January 2026)\n650: Kahneman, D.: \"Thinking, Fast and Slow\" (2011) — System 1 / System 2 framework\n651: GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP PL/SQL function speciﬁcation\n652: ADR-008: OML4Py Embedded Python Execution for the DFR-Gemma Projection\n653: Layer\n654: Date: 2026-05-18\n655: Status: Proposed\n656: Stakeholders consulted: ML research engineer\n657: Context\n658: The DFR-Gemma paper (arXiv:2604.07490, Google Research, April 2026) identiﬁes a\n659: fundamental ineﬃciency in standard RAG architectures. The paper describes the \"translation\n660: tax\": when a retrieved embedding must be converted back into text tokens before being passed\n661: to a language model, the conversion introduces \"redundancy, token ineﬃciency, and numerical\n662: inaccuracies.\" The paper's proposed remedy is a lightweight linear projector that maps from the\n663: embedding model's output space directly into the language model's latent token space, allowing\n664: retrieved vectors to be injected as \"semantic tokens\" rather than text.\n665: For this architecture, the projector maps from EmbeddingGemma's 768-dimensional space to\n666: Gemma 4's token embedding dimension. Oracle Machine Learning for Python (OML4Py)\n667: version 2.1 provides Embedded Python Execution: Python code, including PyTorch operations,Scenario: Generating a working memory map within the 8KB token budget\n668: Given PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE contains 500 entries across 40 directories\n669: When GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP is called by the COMPRESS scheduler step\n670: Then the function aggregates entries by dir_path using LISTAGG\n671: And produces a pipe-delimited string in the format dir_path:{file1,file2}\n672: And the total byte length of the result is less than 8192 bytes\n673: And the result is stored as the current AGENTS_MD_INDEX in SYSTEM_MANIFEST\n674: Scenario: Iterative pruning when the index exceeds the token budget\n675: Given PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE has grown to produce a 14KB index at full detail\n676: When GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP is called\n677: Then entries below importance rank 5 are excluded in the first pass\n678: And if still above 8192 bytes, entries below rank 7 are excluded\n679: And pruning continues until the result fits within 8192 bytes\n680: Anda log records which importance threshold was required\n681: --- PAGE 20 ---\n682: runs inside Oracle's process space with direct memory access to Oracle table data. The trained\n683: projection weights are stored in Oracle as a database object. At inference time, retrieved vectors\n684: are projected inside the database before being assembled into the prompt.\n685: This ADR is marked Proposed rather than Accepted because it represents a more advanced\n686: integration point that requires: (a) OML4Py 2.1 to be enabled on the Always Free Autonomous\n687: Database instance; (b) a minimum of 500 successful query-response pairs in COHERENCE_LOG to\n688: provide adequate training data for the projector; (c) empirical validation that the projection\n689: reduces the Coherence Index's failure rate in production conditions.\n690: Decision\n691: We will implement the DFR-Gemma projection layer using an OML4Py Embedded Python\n692: Execution function that:\n693: 1. Reads paired (EmbeddingGemma vector, successful Gemma 4 response) records from\n694: COHERENCE_LOG\n695: 2. Trains a PyTorch linear layer of shape (768, Gemma4_embedding_dim) for 50 epochs using\n696: mean squared error loss\n697: 3. Stores the trained weights as a serialised NumPy array in PROJECTION_WEIGHTS\n698: 4. Applies the projection to retrieved vectors at query time before context assembly\n699: The retraining trigger is the Coherence Index falling below 0.85 (see ADR-009). When drift is\n700: detected, the DBMS_SCHEDULER chain initiates a projection retraining job before regenerating\n701: the Working Memory Map.\n702: The fallback behaviour when no projection weights are present is fully speciﬁed: the pipeline\n703: falls back to passing retrieved text chunks directly to Gemma 4, with no error and no service\n704: degradation. The projection is a quality enhancement, not a system dependency.\n705: Consequences\n706: Positive: If the DFR-Gemma research results hold in production on this architecture, the\n707: projection should reduce the token cost of conveying retrieved context and improve reasoning\n708: coherence on knowledge-graph-grounded queries.\n709: Negative: This is an experimental integration. The OML4Py PyTorch execution environment has\n710: speciﬁc version constraints. The training process requires compute and may aﬀect Always Free\n711: resource availability during training runs, which should be scheduled during oﬀ-peak hours via\n712: DBMS_SCHEDULER.\n713: Acceptance criteria (Gherkin):\n714: gherkin\n715: --- PAGE 21 ---\n716: Links to Supporting Documents\n717: DFR-Gemma paper: arXiv:2604.07490 (Zhang et al., Google Research, April 2026)\n718: OML4Py 2.1 Embedded Python Execution documentation\n719: Oracle Neural Network class reference\n720: ADR-009: Coherence Indexing and Drift Detection as a Managed Service Primitive\n721: Date: 2026-05-18\n722: Status: Accepted\n723: Stakeholders consulted: Business owner, client services lead\n724: Context\n725: Model drift is the most commercially signiﬁcant and least discussed problem in enterprise AI\n726: deployment. The standard pattern in cloud AI adoption is: (a) integrate a model; (b) observe it\n727: working well for 2–4 months; (c) observe subtle degradation as the gap between the model's\n728: training data and the organisation's evolving reality grows; (d) attribute degradation to \"the AI\n729: being bad\" rather than to the knowledge graph being stale; (e) replace the AI system at\n730: signiﬁcant cost.\n731: The root cause, as established in ADR-001 through ADR-007, is the mismatch between the\n732: model's ﬁxed training distribution and the organisation's changing data distribution. Since we\n733: serve the model (we do not train it), we cannot control the model's training distribution. We can\n734: control the quality of the context we provide to the model. Drift, in this architecture, is not model\n735: drift in the classical ML sense — it is context drift: the gap between what is in the knowledge\n736: graph and what the model needs to know.\n737: Coherence is measurable by three independent signals:Scenario: Training the projection layer on coherence log data\n738: Given COHERENCE_LOG contains at least 500 successful query-response pairs\n739: When the OML4Py Embedded Python Execution training function runs\n740: Thena PyTorch linear layer of shape (768, 768) is trained for 50 epochs\n741: And the trained weights are stored in PROJECTION_WEIGHTS\n742: And no data leaves the Oracle database boundary during training\n743: Scenario: Falling back gracefully when projection weights are absent\n744: Given no trained projection weights exist in PROJECTION_WEIGHTS\n745: Whena user query triggers the search and retrieval pipeline\n746: Then the system falls back to passing retrieved text chunks directly to Gemma 4\n747: And no error is raised and no service degradation occurs\n748: --- PAGE 22 ---\n749: Signal 1: Golden Set Accuracy. A curated set of 100 human-veriﬁed query-response pairs stored\n750: in GOLDEN_SET. Weekly, the full pipeline is run against each Golden Set query, and the response\n751: is compared to the ground-truth response using VECTOR_DISTANCE on their respective\n752: EmbeddingGemma embeddings. A distance below 0.15 constitutes a success. The Coherence\n753: Index is the ratio of successes to total queries. A Coherence Index of 0.85 or above is the\n754: operational threshold.\n755: Signal 2: Thought Token Length Trend. In Gemma 4's gemma-4-thinking template, the\n756: <|think|> block is observable and its token length is loggable. When the model encounters a\n757: question it can answer conﬁdently from context, it thinks brieﬂy and answers directly. When it\n758: encounters a question for which the context is insuﬃcient or contradictory, it \"oscillates\" — re-\n759: reading context, contradicting itself, backtracking — and the thought token count spikes. A 30%\n760: increase in median thought token count over a rolling 7-day window, relative to the baseline\n761: established at deployment, is a secondary drift signal.\n762: Signal 3: Embedding Distribution Centroid Drift. The centroid of all vector embeddings in\n763: PERSONAL_KNOWLEDGE_BASE is computed at system initialisation and stored. Weekly, the current\n764: centroid is recomputed and the cosine distance between the current and baseline centroid is\n765: measured. A distance above 0.1 indicates that the semantic centre of the knowledge graph has\n766: shifted — new topics have been added or old topics deprecated — and the model's context of the\n767: world no longer matches what was present at baseline.\n768: These three signals together provide a multi-dimensional view of coherence that is superior to\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-768. Use offset=769 to continue.)\n</content>",
      "status": "success",
      "timestamp": 1782119798941
    },
    {
      "type": "action",
      "tool": "read",
      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\sovereign_intel_business.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\sovereign_intel_business.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: Sovereign Intelligence: A Business Plan for the Age of Digital\n4: Dignity\n5: From Data Subject to Data Sovereign — How One Architecture Changes\n6: Everything\n7: Preface: Why This Document Exists\n8: This is not a conventional business plan. It does not begin with a market size and end with a ﬁve-\n9: year revenue projection. It begins, instead, with a question that most businesses are too timid to\n10: ask: what does it mean to own your own mind?\n11: The answer to that question, pursued honestly and to its architectural conclusion, produces a\n12: business. The business described in this document emerges not from a gap in the market but\n13: from a gap in human dignity — a gap that has been widening for the better part of three decades,\n14: and which has now, in 2026, become impossible to ignore.\n15: Part One: The Long Road to Dispossession\n16: Before the Internet Remembered\n17: There was a time, not long ago, when the trail of your thinking disappeared the moment you left\n18: the room. You spoke to your doctor and the consultation existed in a paper ﬁle in a cabinet. You\n19: wrote a letter and the original stayed with the recipient, the copy with you. You made a telephone\n20: call and it dissolved into air the moment you hung up.\n21: This impermanence was not experienced as loss. It was simply the nature of human\n22: communication — ephemeral, contextual, and private by default. The friction of recording was\n23: high enough that most human interaction left no durable trace.\n24: The internet changed the economics of recording. Suddenly, storage was cheap. Transmission\n25: was instant. And the organisations building the infrastructure of the new digital world made a\n26: discovery so consequential that its full implications are still unfolding: the trace of your thinking,\n27: accumulated at scale, was worth more than anything you were consciously trying to produce.\n28: This was not immediately obvious. In the early years of the commercial internet, the dominant\n29: metaphor was the library. The web was a place you went to ﬁnd things. Your presence in it felt\n30: passive, like a reader in a reading room. The idea that the reading room was reading you back —\n31: cataloguing your interests, your anxieties, your desires, your social connections — was not yet\n32: part of the cultural conversation.\n33: The Architecture of Extraction\n34: By the mid-2000s, the architecture of extraction was well established, even if its name had not\n35: --- PAGE 2 ---\n36: yet been coined. Search engines knew what you were worried about before your doctor did.\n37: Social networks knew who you loved before you had said it out loud. Advertising platforms knew\n38: your income bracket, your political inclinations, your health concerns, and your relationship\n39: status — inferred, with startling accuracy, from the aggregate pattern of your clicks.\n40: The philosopher Shoshana Zuboﬀ would later name this system Surveillance Capitalism: an\n41: economic logic in which human experience is the raw material, behavioural prediction is the\n42: product, and your attention is the asset being sold to the highest bidder. But the naming came\n43: after the fact. The architecture was already built. The terms of service had already been signed.\n44: The data was already ﬂowing.\n45: What made this architecture so durable was its invisibility. You did not feel surveilled because\n46: the surveillance was frictionless. You were not paying in money, so it did not feel like a\n47: transaction. The price was paid in something more diﬀuse — in the gradual transfer of the\n48: epistemic authority over your own life to systems you could not see, owned by organisations\n49: whose interests were not yours.\n50: Europe Notices\n51: The European Union noticed earlier than most. This is partly cultural — Europe carries within its\n52: legal memory the consequences of what happens when states accumulate too much information\n53: about their citizens — and partly structural. Europe is home to the world's largest community of\n54: citizens who interact with American digital platforms without being American citizens, and who\n55: therefore have no recourse to American democratic institutions when those platforms cause\n56: them harm.\n57: The ﬁrst serious legislative response was the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which established\n58: the principle that personal data could only be processed for legitimate purposes, with the\n59: knowledge and consent of the person it related to. This was forward-looking for its time, but it\n60: was written before Google existed, before Facebook existed, before the smartphone had placed a\n61: continuous data-collection device in every pocket. Its enforcement was fragmented, its penalties\n62: were modest, and its conceptual vocabulary was not yet adequate to the problem it was trying to\n63: address.\n64: The General Data Protection Regulation, which came into force in May 2018, was a diﬀerent kind\n65: of document. It was written by people who understood the architecture of extraction, and who\n66: were trying to build legal machinery powerful enough to contest it. Its ﬁnes — up to four percent\n67: of global annual turnover — were large enough to matter even to the largest platforms. Its rights\n68: were substantive: the right to erasure, the right to object to automated decision-making, the right\n69: to know what data was held about you, and the one that would prove most important for the\n70: story told in this document, the right to data portability.\n71: Article 20 of the GDPR is a deceptively simple provision. It says that you have the right to receive\n72: the personal data you have provided to a data controller in a structured, commonly used,\n73: machine-readable format, and to transmit that data to another controller without hindrance. In\n74: plain English: your data is yours, and you are entitled to take it with you when you leave.\n75: --- PAGE 3 ---\n76: This right existed on paper from 2018. What it lacked was infrastructure. You could exercise your\n77: right to portability and receive a JSON ﬁle you could not read, in a format no other service could\n78: ingest, representing years of your most intimate digital life in a form entirely unusable without\n79: the very platform you were trying to leave. The right was real. The capability it implied did not\n80: yet exist.\n81: Part Two: The Arrival of the Machine That Remembered Everything\n82: November 2022\n83: When OpenAI released ChatGPT to the public in November 2022, the immediate response was\n84: astonishment at the capability. Here was a system that could write, reason, explain, debate,\n85: console, and create — with a ﬂuency that felt, for the ﬁrst time, genuinely human. The queues to\n86: sign up were so long that the service struggled under the load. Within two months, it had one\n87: hundred million users.\n88: What received less attention in those early weeks was the nature of the relationship being\n89: established. ChatGPT was not a tool like a word processor or a calculator, which operates on your\n90: data locally and returns control to you when you close the application. It was a conversation\n91: partner — and every conversation was stored, analysed, and used.\n92: This was disclosed in the terms of service, as everything is disclosed in terms of service that\n93: nobody reads. The conversations you had with ChatGPT — about your health, your relationships,\n94: your work, your fears, your creative projects, your business strategies — were retained by\n95: OpenAI, potentially used to improve their models, and subject to the legal jurisdiction of the\n96: United States, including its subpoena processes, its intelligence community access frameworks,\n97: and, as would become clear in 2025, its civil litigation discovery procedures.\n98: The intimacy of the conversations made this more troubling, not less. People were not using\n99: ChatGPT to search for information they could have found in a library. They were using it to think\n100: — to work through diﬃcult problems, to draft sensitive documents, to process emotional\n101: complexity, to explore ideas they had not yet shared with another human being. The\n102: conversations were, in a meaningful sense, the interior of people's minds, externalised into a\n103: server farm in the United States.\n104: The Accumulation of Concern\n105: The concern about this arrangement accumulated gradually, as concern about digital platforms\n106: always does. There were academic papers about the privacy implications. There were regulatory\n107: investigations in Europe. There was a growing body of journalism about the ways AI systems\n108: encoded and reﬂected the biases in their training data.\n109: But the concern was largely abstract until it became concrete. In June 2025, OpenAI revealed\n110: that it had been ordered by a US federal court, in the context of the New York Times copyright\n111: litigation, to preserve all user data indeﬁnitely — including data that users had explicitly deleted.\n112: The deletion button, it turned out, did not delete. It merely removed data from the user's view\n113: --- PAGE 4 ---\n114: while preserving it in a legal hold. Conversations that people believed they had erased were\n115: sitting in a secure system, accessible to a small audited legal team, potentially subject to future\n116: court orders requiring their disclosure.\n117: This was not a scandal in the sense of a violation of the terms of service. OpenAI had disclosed\n118: that it might be required to retain data for legal purposes. But it was a scandal in the deeper sense\n119: of a revelation: the assumption that your most private digital conversations belonged to you was\n120: not merely unenforceable in practice. It was false in principle.\n121: Europe Acts Again\n122: The European Union responded with characteristic thoroughness. The AI Act, which became\n123: fully applicable in 2026, established the most comprehensive regulatory framework for artiﬁcial\n124: intelligence yet enacted anywhere in the world. It imposed transparency requirements,\n125: conformity assessments, human oversight obligations, and fundamental rights protections that\n126: applied to AI systems deployed in the EU market — including systems operated by non-\n127: European companies serving European users.\n128: The eﬀect of the AI Act, in combination with the GDPR's existing data portability provisions, was\n129: to create a new kind of regulatory pressure. European users had both the legal right to their data\n130: and, increasingly, the legal right to understand how AI systems were using it. What they still\n131: lacked was a practical means of exercising those rights — infrastructure that could receive their\n132: exported data, process it locally, and give them the experience of AI assistance without requiring\n133: them to surrender their conversations to an American corporation.\n134: This gap between legal right and practical capability is where a business lives.\n135: Part Three: The Parallel Evolution of Oracle\n136: The Database as the Foundation of Enterprise Trust\n137: While the consumer AI story was unfolding in the media, a diﬀerent and older story was\n138: continuing in the enterprise world. Oracle Corporation had been building database\n139: infrastructure since 1977. Its products were not glamorous in the way that consumer applications\n140: were glamorous, but they were foundational in a way that nothing else quite matched.\n141: When a hospital stored patient records, it used Oracle. When a bank reconciled transactions, it\n142: used Oracle. When a government agency maintained citizen data, it used Oracle. The company's\n143: dominance in enterprise data management was built on a simple proposition: your data is your\n144: most critical asset, and you should trust its management to a system that has been battle-tested\n145: over decades and whose failure would be considered catastrophic.\n146: This institutional trust was not merely commercial. It was a form of social infrastructure. The\n147: reliability of Oracle's database products underpinned systems that people's lives depended on.\n148: This created an unusual relationship between Oracle and the concept of data sovereignty: for\n149: enterprise customers, Oracle was sovereignty. Your data in Oracle was your data. It did not leave\n150: without your permission. It was encrypted, audited, and controlled by policies you set.\n151: --- PAGE 5 ---\n152: The challenge that Oracle faced, as the AI era arrived, was how to extend this sovereignty\n153: guarantee into the age of intelligent systems. The conventional approach — send your data to an\n154: AI API, receive intelligence in return — was fundamentally incompatible with the privacy\n155: guarantees that Oracle's enterprise customers required. A hospital could not send patient\n156: records to OpenAI's servers. A bank could not expose transaction histories to a third-party\n157: inference API. A government could not route citizen data through an American commercial\n158: cloud.\n159: Oracle's response was to bring the intelligence inside. Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai\n160: introduced the VECTOR data type, making the database natively capable of storing and\n161: searching the mathematical representations that modern AI systems use to encode meaning. It\n162: introduced DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN, a package that allowed database code to orchestrate the\n163: entire retrieval-augmented generation pipeline — embedding, searching, and generating —\n164: without data ever leaving the database boundary.\n165: Most signiﬁcantly for the story told here, Oracle Machine Learning for Python introduced\n166: Embedded Python Execution: the ability to run arbitrary Python code, including PyTorch\n167: operations and Hugging Face model inference, inside Python engines spawned and managed by\n168: the database itself. This was not a wrapper around an external service. It was computation\n169: happening inside the database, with direct access to data in database tables, managed by the\n170: database's own process scheduler.\n171: The implication was profound, even if it was not immediately recognised as such: Oracle had\n172: built an environment in which a learned transformation — a neural projection layer, a ﬁne-tuned\n173: embedding model, a custom inference pipeline — could live inside the database alongside the\n174: data it operated on, without any network boundary between the data and the computation.\n175: This was, in architectural terms, the hardware for sovereignty.\n176: Part Four: The Invention\n177: What Emerged From the Conversation\n178: The architecture described in this business plan was not conceived by a team of engineers in a\n179: well-funded research lab. It emerged from an extended conversation between a person who\n180: thought in architectural intuitions and an AI that could translate those intuitions into technical\n181: vocabulary.\n182: The central insight — arrived at through a process that was more philosophical than technical —\n183: was this: the standard pipeline for AI-assisted work involves a continuous series of translation\n184: events, each of which degrades the semantic ﬁdelity of the information being processed. Your\n185: thought becomes a text prompt. The text prompt is tokenised into a numerical sequence. The\n186: sequence is processed by an attention mechanism that scales quadratically with its length. The\n187: --- PAGE 6 ---\n188: output is a vector. The vector is retrieved and converted back to text. The text is tokenised again\n189: and passed to a generative model.\n190: Each of these translations is a form of Muda — waste, in the vocabulary of the Toyota Production\n191: System. Each step costs energy, introduces delay, and risks the loss of meaning. And each step is\n192: an opportunity for the data to cross a boundary: from your machine to a remote server, from your\n193: tenancy to a third-party API, from your jurisdiction to another.\n194: The question that drove the architectural thinking was: what if you could eliminate as many of\n195: these translations as possible? What if the retrieval and the reasoning could happen in the same\n196: semantic space, on the same infrastructure, under the governance of a system that was built\n197: from the ground up to keep your data yours?\n198: The Oracle 23ai Foundation\n199: The answer to that question begins with Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai, deployed on Oracle\n200: Cloud Infrastructure's Always Free tier — infrastructure that costs nothing to run, that is\n201: available to any person on earth with an email address, and that provides twenty gigabytes of\n202: storage and two OCPUs of compute without charge.\n203: Inside this database, EmbeddingGemma — Google DeepMind's 308-million-parameter\n204: embedding model, derived from the Gemma 3 architecture and state-of-the-art on multilingual,\n205: English, and code benchmarks — is loaded as an ONNX model using\n206: DBMS_VECTOR.LOAD_ONNX_MODEL. This is not a call to an external API. The model lives\n207: inside the database. When the database generates an embedding, it does so natively, in PL/SQL,\n208: without any network call.\n209: The vectors produced by this native EmbeddingGemma instance are stored in tables with the\n210: VECTOR data type, indexed with HNSW indexes for logarithmic-time approximate nearest-\n211: neighbour search, and queried with VECTOR_DISTANCE — a SQL operator that returns the\n212: semantic distance between two vectors as a pure number. The entire retrieval pipeline — from\n213: raw text to ranked semantic matches — runs inside the database in milliseconds.\n214: The generation step — converting retrieved context into natural language — is handled by\n215: Gemma 4, running locally via Ollama on the OCI Always Free ARM compute instance. The\n216: connection between database and model is orchestrated by DBMS_VECTOR_CHAIN, which can\n217: call the local Ollama endpoint via UTL_HTTP, assemble the prompt with retrieved context, and\n218: return the generated text — all from inside a PL/SQL block or a DBMS_SCHEDULER job.\n219: The operational logic — when to ingest new data, when to regenerate the working memory map,\n220: when to run the coherence evaluation suite, when to notify the operator of drift — lives in a job\n221: hierarchy deﬁned in DBMS_SCHEDULER.CREATE_CHAIN. This is not a cron job on a Linux\n222: server that might fail and not be noticed. It is a transactional job chain inside an ACID-compliant\n223: database that rolls back on failure, retries on error, and logs every execution to tables that can be\n224: queried and visualised in Oracle APEX dashboards.\n225: Oracle APEX provides the user interface: the onboarding portal where new users upload their\n226: GDPR export, the management dashboard where they inspect their knowledge graph, the\n227: coherence index display that shows whether their AI is drifting, the memory management\n228: --- PAGE 7 ---\n229: interface that lets them prioritise, deprioritise, or delete speciﬁc memories — everything that\n230: ChatGPT's memory interface provides, but running on infrastructure they own.\n231: Oracle REST Data Services exposes the intelligence of this stack as a secure API. VS Code\n232: extensions, custom applications, and automated agents can query the sovereign stack at a REST\n233: endpoint, receiving semantically relevant context and generated responses, without the data\n234: ever leaving the user's OCI tenancy.\n235: The OML4Py Projection Layer\n236: The most architecturally novel element of this stack — the component that brings it closest to\n237: the research frontier described in the DFR-Gemma paper published by Google Research in April\n238: 2026 — is the learned projection layer trained and executed using Oracle Machine Learning for\n239: Python's Embedded Python Execution capability.\n240: The standard problem with RAG pipelines is that they involve a semantic discontinuity: the\n241: vectors used for retrieval are generated by one model, converted back to text, and then re-\n242: processed by a diﬀerent model with a diﬀerent internal representation. Even when the two\n243: models are members of the same family — as EmbeddingGemma and Gemma 4 are — the\n244: mathematical spaces they operate in are not identical. The retrieval is in one language; the\n245: reasoning is in another.\n246: OML4Py's Embedded Python Execution allows a PyTorch linear projection layer to be trained\n247: and executed inside the database itself, using Python engines spawned and managed by Oracle.\n248: This projection layer learns a mapping from EmbeddingGemma's 768-dimensional output space\n249: to a representation aligned with Gemma 4's internal token embedding space. The training uses\n250: paired examples of retrieval vectors and successful reasoning outputs, drawn from the\n251: coherence evaluation logs stored in the database.\n252: The result is that retrieved vectors, before being converted to text and passed to Gemma 4, are\n253: ﬁrst transformed by this learned projection into a representation that Gemma 4 can process\n254: more eﬃciently — reducing the token cost of reasoning over retrieved context, improving the\n255: coherence of generated outputs, and moving the pipeline one step closer to the true latent-space\n256: continuity described in the DFR-Gemma architecture.\n257: This projection layer trains inside Oracle. It lives inside Oracle. It executes inside Oracle. The\n258: computation is co-located with the data it operates on, with zero network boundary between\n259: them. This is what OML was built for — eliminating the data movement tax — applied to the\n260: most demanding problem in modern AI infrastructure.\n261: The Eight Kilobyte Working Memory\n262: The system prompt that accompanies every query to Gemma 4 is not a static text ﬁle. It is a\n263: dynamically generated, pipe-delimited index of the user's knowledge graph, compressed to\n264: approximately two thousand tokens — the \"high-attention region\" of the model's context\n265: window, the silicon equivalent of working memory — and refreshed by a DBMS_SCHEDULER\n266: job every time the knowledge graph changes.\n267: --- PAGE 8 ---\n268: This compression technique, independently validated by Vercel's Next.js engineering team in\n269: their January 2026 research, works because language models are pattern-matchers before they\n270: are reasoners. A directory structure expressed as src/auth:\n271: {login.py,session.py,tokens.py} is processed in System 1 — instant recognition, zero\n272: reasoning cost. A paragraph explaining what each ﬁle contains requires System 2 — eﬀortful\n273: attention, quadratic cost.\n274: The Oracle SQL function GENERATE_WORKING_MEMORY_MAP produces this index\n275: automatically, pruning entries by importance rank until the result ﬁts within the token budget,\n276: and caching the result in the SYSTEM_MANIFEST table as a CLOB alongside a version history\n277: that allows any previous version to be restored with a single UPDATE statement.\n278: Part Five: The Business\n279: The Customer\n280: The customer for Sovereign Intelligence is anyone whose relationship with AI has produced a\n281: body of thinking that they do not want to surrender to the platform that captured it.\n282: This is a larger group than it might initially appear. It includes the professional who has spent\n283: three years discussing client strategy with ChatGPT and who has just learned that the\n284: conversations are being retained in a legal hold. It includes the researcher who has used AI\n285: assistance to develop ideas that represent genuine intellectual property and who is\n286: uncomfortable with the possibility that those ideas are being incorporated into training data. It\n287: includes the enterprise that cannot use cloud AI services for regulatory reasons and is currently\n288: relying on generic models that know nothing about its speciﬁc domain. It includes the person\n289: who simply ﬁnds the idea of a corporation owning the record of their private thinking morally\n290: oﬀensive, and who is looking for an alternative that does not require technical expertise to\n291: deploy.\n292: What unites these customers is not a speciﬁc demographic or industry. It is a disposition: they\n293: believe their data is an extension of themselves, and they want infrastructure that treats it that\n294: way.\n295: The Product\n296: The product is a sovereign AI stack, deployed on the customer's own OCI tenancy, that provides\n297: the full experience of a modern AI assistant — conversational memory, document\n298: understanding, semantic search, code assistance, multimodal reasoning — without any of the\n299: data leaving the customer's control.\n300: For individual customers, the product is a personal sovereignty stack: their ChatGPT export\n301: rehydrated into an Oracle 23ai knowledge graph, queryable via Open WebUI running on their\n302: OCI ARM instance, with EmbeddingGemma providing the retrieval layer and Gemma 4\n303: providing the reasoning layer, all orchestrated by DBMS_SCHEDULER and managed through an\n304: Oracle APEX dashboard.\n305: --- PAGE 9 ---\n306: For enterprise customers, the product is a team sovereignty platform: multiple isolated tenancies,\n307: each containing a domain-speciﬁc knowledge graph ﬁne-tuned on the organisation's internal\n308: documents, with Terraform and Ansible automation that can provision a new environment in\n309: under ten minutes and a federated architecture that allows domain knowledge to be shared\n310: across tenancies as learned LoRA adapters without the underlying data ever crossing tenancy\n311: boundaries.\n312: For regulated industries — healthcare, legal, ﬁnancial services, government — the product is a\n313: compliance-ﬁrst AI platform: the same technical architecture, packaged with Data Processing\n314: Agreements that formally document the zero-data-transfer guarantee, with coherence indexing\n315: and drift management provided as a managed service, and with audit logging that satisﬁes the\n316: transparency requirements of the EU AI Act.\n317: The Revenue Model\n318: Revenue comes from three sources, at diﬀerent margins and diﬀerent stages of the customer\n319: relationship.\n320: The ﬁrst is implementation: a one-time fee for deploying the sovereign stack, migrating\n321: historical data from existing platforms, conﬁguring the knowledge graph schema, and training\n322: the initial domain-speciﬁc projection layers. This work is labour-intensive but commands a\n323: premium because it requires expertise that is genuinely scarce.\n324: The second is maintenance: a monthly retainer for keeping the infrastructure running, updating\n325: the models as new versions are released, managing the DBMS_SCHEDULER job hierarchy, and\n326: ensuring that the coherence index remains above the agreed threshold. This is the recurring\n327: revenue that makes the business sustainable.\n328: The third is drift management: the high-margin professional service of monitoring the\n329: coherence index, identifying when the knowledge graph has fallen behind the reality it is\n330: supposed to represent, diagnosing the cause, and correcting it — whether by updating the\n331: knowledge graph, retraining the projection layer, adjusting the working memory map, or ﬁne-\n332: tuning the model weights using Unsloth on the customer's own hardware.\n333: Drift management is the service that competitors cannot easily replicate, because it requires\n334: both deep technical knowledge of the stack and deep contextual knowledge of the customer's\n335: domain. The ability to look at a coherence index dashboard and say \"your model is struggling\n336: with authentication logic because your new OAuth implementation isn't represented in the\n337: knowledge graph\" is a skill that takes time to develop and cannot be commoditised.\n338: The Federated Future\n339: The long-term architecture of Sovereign Intelligence is not a platform but a protocol. The\n340: business described in this document does not aspire to become the next OpenAI — a centralised\n341: intelligence that knows everything about everyone. It aspires to become the infrastructure layer\n342: for a federated world in which intelligence is distributed, local, and sovereign.\n343: In this federated architecture, each customer owns a node. The node contains their data, their\n344: knowledge graph, their projection layers, and their reasoning model. The node communicates\n345: --- PAGE 10 ---\n346: with other nodes not by sharing data but by sharing learned representations — LoRA adapters\n347: trained on domain knowledge that can be merged with the base model without exposing the\n348: underlying data.\n349: A network of law ﬁrms, each with its own sovereign stack, can share a legal reasoning adapter\n350: that improves all of their models' understanding of contract law without any ﬁrm's client data\n351: ever leaving its own tenancy. A network of hospitals can share a clinical reasoning adapter that\n352: improves diagnostic support without any patient data crossing institutional boundaries. A\n353: network of independent developers can share a coding adapter that improves code generation\n354: for a speciﬁc framework without any proprietary codebase being exposed.\n355: This is federated learning in its most sovereign form: intelligence that improves through\n356: collaboration without requiring trust. The data stays home. Only the learning travels.\n357: The business model for this federated future is a marketplace of adapters — domain knowledge\n358: encoded in mathematical weights, licensed and distributed by Sovereign Intelligence, improving\n359: every node in the network without centralising any data. The more nodes in the network, the\n360: more valuable the adapters. The more valuable the adapters, the more nodes join. This is the\n361: network eﬀect of sovereignty.\n362: Part Six: Why Now\n363: The Convergence\n364: The business described in this document could not have existed ﬁve years ago. It requires the\n365: simultaneous availability of several things that have only recently come together.\n366: It requires open-weight models capable of genuine reasoning at a scale that can run on consumer\n367: hardware. Gemma 4 and EmbeddingGemma, both released in 2025 and 2026, provide this. It\n368: requires a database platform with native vector support, in-database model execution, and a free\n369: tier accessible to anyone. Oracle Autonomous Database 23ai on OCI Always Free provides this. It\n370: requires a legal framework that establishes data portability as a right and gives citizens a\n371: mechanism for exercising it. The GDPR's Article 20 provides this, and the EU AI Act strengthens\n372: the enforcement context around it. It requires a cultural moment in which the general public has\n373: become suﬃciently alarmed about AI data practices that they are willing to take action.\n374: The New York Times litigation and the resulting revelation about OpenAI's data retention\n375: practices provided that moment. The news that deleted conversations were being preserved in\n376: legal holds reached millions of people who had never thought carefully about where their AI\n377: conversations were stored. The question \"who owns my conversations with AI?\" moved from an\n378: academic concern to a personal one.\n379: The convergence of technical capability, legal framework, and cultural readiness is rare. When it\n380: happens, the window is open for a short time before it closes again — either because the problem\n381: is solved by the incumbents, or because it becomes so acute that regulation imposes a solution\n382: from above. The window for Sovereign Intelligence is open now.\n383: --- PAGE 11 ---\n384: The Moat\n385: The technical components of this stack are individually available to anyone. Oracle 23ai is a\n386: commercial product. EmbeddingGemma is open-source. Gemma 4 is open-weight. OML4Py is\n387: documented. Ollama is free. The Terraform templates that provision the infrastructure can be\n388: written by any competent infrastructure engineer.\n389: What is not available to anyone is the speciﬁc combination: the architectural insight that places\n390: the learned projection layer inside the database rather than outside it, the operational knowledge\n391: of how to tune the DBMS_SCHEDULER chain for reliability, the coherence indexing\n392: methodology that provides a quantitative measure of model drift, the working memory map\n393: compression technique adapted from Vercel's research to Oracle's SQL environment, and the\n394: federated adapter marketplace architecture that makes the network more valuable as it grows.\n395: This knowledge is tacit. It was arrived at through a process of reasoning that is documented in\n396: this business plan but that cannot be fully replicated by reading a document. The moat is not a\n397: patent. It is expertise — the kind of expertise that compounds as more customers are served,\n398: more domain adapters are trained, and more coherence data is accumulated.\n399: The moat deepens with each customer, because each customer's coherence logs become training\n400: data for better drift detection models, better projection layers, and better working memory\n401: compression algorithms. The business improves fastest when it is serving the most customers.\n402: This is the structural advantage of a platform that learns from its own operations.\n403: Epilogue: What This Is Really About\n404: This business plan describes a technical architecture and a commercial model. But underneath\n405: both is a conviction about what the relationship between human beings and intelligent systems\n406: should look like.\n407: Daniel Kahneman spent his career showing us that we are not the rational actors we imagine\n408: ourselves to be. We are pattern-matchers ﬁrst and reasoners second. We are subject to biases we\n409: cannot see, lazy controllers of fast engines, and systematically overconﬁdent in our own\n410: judgment.\n411: The appropriate response to this discovery is not despair. It is architecture. If we know that our\n412: System 1 will reach for the easy answer, we build systems that make the easy answer the right\n413: one. If we know that our attention is ﬁnite and precious, we build systems that protect it. If we\n414: know that our memory is lossy and our reasoning is expensive, we build systems that remember\n415: accurately and reason eﬃciently.\n416: The sovereign AI stack described in this document is an attempt to build that kind of system —\n417: one that respects the limitations Kahneman documented, that eliminates the Muda that those\n418: limitations create, and that does all of this while keeping the data that makes the system\n419: intelligent in the hands of the person whose thinking produced it.\n420: --- PAGE 12 ---\n421: People who want dignity do not want to be products. They want tools. They want infrastructure\n422: that serves them the way a good library serves a reader — not tracking what they read, not selling\n423: their attention to advertisers, not preserving their research habits for future litigation — but\n424: simply making knowledge available when they need it and disappearing when they do not.\n425: This is what it means to move people who want dignity. Not with a promise, but with an\n426: architecture. Not with a policy, but with a system whose design makes the right outcome the only\n427: possible one.\n428: The data stays home. The intelligence travels. The thinking remains yours.\n429: Prepared for internal strategy use. All technical claims reﬂect the state of the art as of May 2026.\n\n(End of file - total 429 lines)\n</content>",
