      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\oracle_uk_faq.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\oracle_uk_faq.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: Sign up for Oracle Cloud Free Tier\n4: Build, test, and deploy applications on Oracle Cloud—for free. Get Always Free\n5: services and a US$300 cloud credit for 30 days.Sign up today\n6: What is Oracle Cloud Free Tier?Close all\n7: What is Oracle Cloud Free Tier?\n8: Oracle Cloud Free Tier allows you to sign up for an Oracle Cloud account which provides a\n9: number of Always Free services and a Free Trial with US$300 of free credit to use on all\n10: eligible Oracle Cloud Infrastructure services for up to 30 days. The Always Free services are\n11: available for an unlimited period of time. The Free Trial services may be used until your\n12: US$300 of free credits are consumed or the 30 days has expired, whichever comes first.\n13: Who should use Oracle Cloud Free Tier?\n14: Oracle Cloud Free Tier services are for everyone. Whether you’re a developer building and\n15: testing applications, a startup founder creating new systems with the intention of scaling\n16: later, an enterprise looking to test things before moving to cloud, a student wanting to learn,\n17: or an academic developing curriculum in the cloud, Oracle Cloud Free Tier enables you to\n18: learn, explore, build and test for free.\n19: Who is eligible for Oracle Cloud Free Tier?\n20: One Oracle Cloud Free Trial or Always Free account is permitted per person. Please note:\n21: Creating or attempting to create multiple free accounts is prohibited.\n22: All contact and billing information provided must be accurate, valid, and used with\n23: consent for the duration of the account.\n24: Accounts left idle for 30 days or more may be deemed abandoned and become eligible for\n25: suspension or termination.\n26: OCI Cloud Free Tier FAQ6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n27: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 1/9\n28: --- PAGE 2 ---\n29: Failure to comply with these requirements or the Cloud Services Agreement (PDF) may\n30: result in the suspension or termination of your account.\n31: Why do I need to provide credit or debit card information when I sign up for Oracle\n32: Cloud Free Tier?\n33: To provide free Oracle Cloud accounts to our valued customers, we need to ensure that you\n34: are who you say you are. We use your contact information and credit/debit card information\n35: for account setup and identity verification. Oracle may periodically check the validity of your\n36: card, resulting in a temporary “authorization” hold. These holds are removed by your bank,\n37: typically within three to five days, and do not result in actual charges to your account.\n38: What payment methods does Oracle accept?\n39: We accept credit cards and debit cards that function like credit cards. We do not accept debit\n40: cards with a PIN or virtual, single-use, or prepaid cards.\n41: Is Oracle Cloud Free Tier available in all countries?\n42: Oracle Cloud Free Tier is currently available in all regions where commercial Oracle Cloud\n43: Infrastructure service is available. See the data regions page for detailed service\n44: availability.*** If your first-choice data region isn’t available, please select an adjacent region.\n45: If you are unable to find the country or territory you require, please contact Oracle Sales or\n46: Cloud Support using the Chat link in the menu bar. The Oracle Sales team can help you sign\n47: up for Oracle Cloud Free Tier.\n48: How do I sign up for Oracle Cloud Free Tier?\n49: You can sign up on the Oracle Cloud Free Tier sign up page.\n50: How do I get help if I have problems signing up or signing in including Multi-Factor\n51: Authentication (MFA)?\n52: Contact the Oracle Cloud support team using the Chat link in the menu bar.\n53: Does Oracle Cloud Free Tier include service level agreements (SLAs) and technical\n54: support?\n55: Oracle Cloud Free Tier does not include SLAs. Community support through our forums is\n56: available to all customers. Customers using only Always Free resources are not eligible for\n57: Oracle Support. Limited support is available for Oracle Cloud Free Tier with Free Trial credits.\n58: After you use all of your credits or after your trial period ends (whichever comes first), you\n59: must upgrade to a paid account to access Oracle Support. If you choose not to upgrade and\n60: continue to use Always Free Services, you will not be eligible to raise a service request in My\n61: Oracle Support.\n62: 6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n63: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 2/9\n64: --- PAGE 3 ---\n65: What are Always Free services?\n66: Always Free services are part of Oracle Cloud Free Tier. Always Free services are available for\n67: an unlimited time. Some limitations apply. As new Always Free services become available,\n68: you will automatically be able to use those as well.\n69: The following services are available as Always Free:\n70: HeatWave\n71: AMD-based Compute\n72: Arm-based Ampere A1 Compute\n73: Block Volume\n74: Object Storage\n75: Archive Storage\n76: Flexible Load Balancer\n77: Flexible Network Load Balancer\n78: VPN Connect\n79: Autonomous Data Warehouse\n80: Autonomous Transaction Processing\n81: Autonomous JSON Database\n82: NoSQL Database (Phoenix Region only)\n83: APEX Application Development\n84: 6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n85: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 3/9\n86: --- PAGE 4 ---\n87: Resource Manager (Terraform)\n88: Monitoring\n89: Notifications\n90: Logging\n91: Application Performance Monitoring\n92: Service Connector Hub\n93: Vault\n94: Bastions\n95: Security Advisor\n96: Virtual Cloud Networks\n97: Site-to-Site VPN\n98: Content Management Starter Edition\n99: Email Delivery\n100: What can I do with Always Free Oracle Autonomous Database?\n101: With Oracle Autonomous Database now always free, developers can access a full database\n102: experience and built-in development tools for free—without worrying about losing work at\n103: the end of a trial period. Autonomous Database is a multimodel database for virtually any\n104: type of data (including relational, JSON, spatial, graph, multimedia, XML, files, and more),\n105: any workload (transactional, data warehouse, and analytics), and any interface (full SQL,\n106: REST data access, and language drivers). The service includes free development tools such\n107: as SQL Developer IDE, Oracle Application Express (APEX) for low-code app creation, Oracle\n108: REST Data Services, and powerful command-line utilities. To keep building even when you\n109: are disconnected from Oracle Cloud, you can mix Always Free Oracle Autonomous Database\n110: with a compatible always-free version of Oracle Database that runs on your laptop (see\n111: Oracle Database XE).\n112: What can I do with Always Free Oracle Cloud Infrastructure?\n113: With Always Free Oracle Cloud Infrastructure services, you get the essentials you need to\n114: build and test applications in the cloud. This includes two compute instances, NVMe SSD-\n115: powered block storage, high-bandwidth object storage, archive storage, and load balancing,\n116: all on our enterprise-grade virtual networks. These resources enable you to prototype two-\n117: tier high availability applications, test server cloning and other advanced storage features, or\n118: build basic data pipelines with object storage, as just a few examples. Coupling with Always\n119: Free Autonomous Database or our Free Tier gives you even more options. Our cloud\n120: infrastructure includes rich APIs, SDKs for Java, Python, Ruby, and Go, and cool plug-ins for\n121: Jenkins, Packer, and Grafana. And you can automate it all with Terraform.\n122: I need more instances or larger sizes of Always Free services. What should I do? 6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n123: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 4/9\n124: --- PAGE 5 ---\n125: If your cloud account is in Free Trial period or has paid status, you can directly upgrade an\n126: Always Free resource to a paid resource to get more processing power, data storage, and\n127: network bandwidth. If your account has finished Free Trial without upgrading to paid status,\n128: you can continue using Always Free resources but you cannot upgrade Always Free\n129: resources to paid resources until the account is first upgraded to paid status.\n130: You may upgrade an account to paid status at any time from the Account Management area\n131: in Oracle Cloud Console. You will be able to choose between Pay As You Go or Monthly Flex\n132: plans. Alternatively, you may contact Oracle Sales for assistance. See cloud cost estimator for\n133: details.\n134: In addition, you may spend free credits during a Free Trial period to create more instances or\n135: larger instances than allowed for Always Free. Note that paid instances created during a trial\n136: period will be reclaimed when the Free Trial ends, whereas Always Free resources will\n137: continue to be available even after the Free Trial period.\n138: What is the advantage of moving to Pay As You Go accounts after the trial?\n139: You have access to customer support to open tickets and troubleshoot account issues. Pay\n140: As You Go accounts are subject to different capacity limits than Always Free accounts. As you\n141: move from development and testing to production scenarios, you may need to use resources\n142: outside of Always Free limits. You will have access to the latest portfolio of OCI services, such\n143: as artificial intelligence, and you only pay for what you use.\n144: How do I know how much I am going be charged for Pay As You Go services?\n145: You will only be charged for services that you use that exceeds Always Free. You can find\n146: information about costs in the Oracle Cloud Price List and the Oracle cloud cost estimator.\n147: I just signed up and I can’t access specific services. What can I do?\n148: Registering your account with all services and regions can take a few minutes. Check again\n149: after a few minutes have passed.\n150: How do I change which resources I want to designate as Always Free?\n151: In short, you can’t. Eligible resources are designated Always Free when they are created.\n152: After you provision an Always Free resource, the Always Free status is not transferable to\n153: another resource. However, you can delete an existing Always Free resource in order to\n154: create a new Always Free resource in its place.\n155: My resources no longer appear. How can I restore them?\n156: If you have a Free Tier account and your resources no longer appear, it’s likely that your Free\n157: Trial has expired and your paid resources have been reclaimed (terminated). You can verify if\n158: this is the case by doing the following:\n159: Log in to the Console6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n160: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 5/9\n161: --- PAGE 6 ---\n162: Check for a banner at the top of the Console with the following text: “You are using a Free\n163: Tier account. To access all services and resources, upgrade to a paid account.”\n164: If you see this message, your resources have been reclaimed and can’t be restored.\n165: I get an “out of host capacity” error when I try to create an Always Free Compute\n166: instance. What can I do?\n167: An \"out of host capacity\" error indicates a temporary lack of Always Free shapes in your\n168: home region. Oracle is working to provide more capacity, though it might take several days\n169: before additional capacity is available in your home region. If your home region has multiple\n170: availability domains, try creating the instance in a different availability domain. If that doesn’t\n171: work, wait a while, and then try to launch the instance again.\n172: Is my Free Tier account eligible for support?\n173: Community support through our forums is available to all customers. Customers using only\n174: Always Free resources are not eligible for Oracle Support. Limited support is available to Free\n175: Tier accounts with Free Trial credits. After you use all of your credits or after your trial period\n176: ends (whichever comes first), you must upgrade to a paid account to access Oracle Support.\n177: If you choose not to upgrade and continue to use Always Free Services, you will not be\n178: eligible to raise a service request in My O racle Support. See Getting Help and Contacting\n179: Support.\n180: Are Always Free services available for paid accounts?\n181: Yes, for paid accounts using universal credit pricing.\n182: What is Free Trial?\n183: Free Trial is part of Oracle Cloud Free Tier and provides US$300 of free credits to use on all\n184: eligible Oracle Cloud Infrastructure services for up to 30 days. The Free Trial period may end\n185: either because all free credits are spent or 30 days has been reached.\n186: For how long can I use my Free Trial credits?\n187: You must use all your Free Trial credits within 30 days of signing up for Oracle Cloud Free\n188: Tier. Any credits that are unused at the end of the 30-day period will automatically expire.\n189: The Always Free services will continue to be available for unlimited time as long as you use\n190: the services.\n191: Is it possible to extend my Free Trial?\n192: If you need additional credits or time, you can schedule a call with an Oracle sales\n193: representative using the Upgrade page in the Console. Sales representatives have the\n194: authority to extend trials or issue additional credits if appropriate.6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n195: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 6/9\n196: --- PAGE 7 ---\n197: If you don't see an Upgrade link on the Console page you’re viewing, you can click the\n198: Oracle Cloud logo at the top of the Console and then look for the Upgrade link in the sidebar\n199: on the right side of the page.\n200: What happens when my Free Trial expires or my credits are used up?\n201: For a standard Free Trial, when you've reached the end of your 30-day trial or used all your\n202: Free Trial credits (whichever comes first), you’ll be notified and have a grace period of 30\n203: days, starting from the expiration date, to upgrade to a paid account. You’ll no longer be able\n204: to create new paid resources, but your account will remain active. Your resources will\n205: continue to exist for a few days, allowing you to upgrade your account and keep your\n206: resources before they're reclaimed by Oracle. If you don’t upgrade to a paid account by the\n207: end of the grace period, your Free Trial service instances and data will be deleted. (Note that\n208: reclaimed resources can’t be recovered—they are permanently deleted.)\n209: Resources identified as Always Free will not be reclaimed. After your Free Trial expires, you'll\n210: continue to be able to use and manage your existing Always Free resources and can create\n211: new Always Free resources according to tenancy limits.\n212: However, if you have more Ampere A1 Compute instances provisioned than are available for\n213: an Always Free tenancy, all existing Ampere A1 instances are disabled and then deleted after\n214: 30 days unless you upgrade to a paid account. To continue using your existing Arm-based\n215: instances as an Always Free user, before your trial ends, ensure that your total use of OCPUs\n216: and memory across all the Ampere A1 Compute instances in your tenancy is within the\n217: Always Free limit.\n218: With some special Free Trial offers, your account will not continue as an Always Free account\n219: after the trial expires. In these cases, you’ll be notified and your account will be suspended\n220: immediately after the Free Trial expires. Your account will remain suspended for 30 days,\n221: during which time you may still log in to retrieve your data or upgrade to a paid account.\n222: After the 30-day suspension period, the account will be fully deleted and will not be\n223: recoverable.\n224: If I upgrade, do I keep my Free Trial credit balance?\n225: Yes, if you upgrade during the Free Trial period, you won’t be billed until you've reached the\n226: end of your 30-day trial or used all of your Free Trial credits (whichever comes first). You’ll be\n227: notified by email when billing begins.\n228: After I upgrade my account, can I downgrade?\n229: There is no option to downgrade your account. However, with a paid account, you’ll continue\n230: to have access to Always Free resources, and you’ll only pay for the standard resources you\n231: use. No minimums and no prepayment are required for your paid account.\n232: How do I recover my data once the 30-day Free Trial comes to an end? 6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n233: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 7/9\n234: --- PAGE 8 ---\n235: *Free Tier is generally available in regions where commercial Oracle Cloud Infrastructure service is\n236: available See the data regions page for detailed service availability (Exact regions available for Free Tier\n237: may differ during signup process). The US$300 cloud credit is available in select countries and valid for\n238: up to 30 days. Cloud credits consumption can be subject to discounted rates during the 30-day\n239: promotional period.\n240: ** Availability to Free Tier is subject to capacity limits. The capacity limits listed under each service are\n241: only estimates and reflect the maximum capacity you can get if you consume your entire credit on one\n242: service during the promotional period. The maximum capacity per service you get can be less if you\n243: consume multiple services. The list of services and capacity estimates are subject to change. Your credit\n244: balance is available to you in the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Console.You are responsible for exporting and importing all of your data manually or using tools\n245: supported by the object storage.\n246: What is Oracle Cloud Promotion?\n247: Oracle Cloud Promotion is another term for Free Trial.\n248: How do I convert my Oracle Cloud Free Tier account to a paid account?\n249: You can upgrade your cloud account to paid at any time. Simply go to Account Management\n250: in the Oracle Cloud Console and complete the upgrade steps.\n251: Is my credit usage rate discounted during Free Trial?\n252: Yes, during the Free Trial period of 30 days, your usage rates are discounted. This will let you\n253: gain free, hands-on experience with the wide range of Oracle Cloud services.\n254: What are the discounted rates?\n255: During the 30-day Free Trial period, you will just pay the Oracle IaaS rates for all platform\n256: services including Oracle Database Cloud, Java Cloud Service (WebLogic), and other services\n257: which are normally billed at higher rates.\n258: How do I terminate my Free Tier account?\n259: Please refer to the documentation section on deleting a Free Tier Tenancy and Cloud\n260: Account for details on account termination.6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n261: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 8/9\n262: --- PAGE 9 ---\n263: Sign up for Oracle Cloud Free Tier\n264: Build, test, and deploy applications on Oracle Cloud—for free. Get Always Free\n265: services and a US$300 cloud credit for 30 days.\n266: Terms of Use and Privacy Gender Pay Gap ReportModern Slavery Statement\n267: Cookie Preferences Ad Choices Careers Subscribe to emails Integrity Helpline Contact UsSign up today\n268: © 2026 Oracle\n269: 6/17/26, 5:58 PM FAQ on Oracle's Cloud Free Tier | Oracle United Kingdom\n270: https://www.oracle.com/uk/cloud/free/faq/ 9/9\n\n(End of file - total 270 lines)\n</content>",
