      "code": "{\"filePath\": \"C:\\\\Users\\\\LLM-Test\\\\.mavis\\\\sessions\\\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\\\workspace\\\\oci_extract\\\\sovereign_intent_manifolds.pdf.txt\"}",
      "output": "<path>C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\.minimax\\sessions\\mvs_655002872be440d685f9c58dcb581f2a\\workspace\\oci_extract\\sovereign_intent_manifolds.pdf.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: --- PAGE 1 ---\n3: Sovereign Intent Manifolds: Deterministic Agentic Governance\n4: via Bifurcated Architecture\n5: Andrea Kwabena Enning\n6: AndieKobbieTech, United Kingdom\n7: April 2026\n8: Abstract\n9: The paradigm of autonomous agentic systems is currently defined by the integration\n10: of Large Language Models (LLMs) into production workflows. However; these systems\n11: suffer from a systemic inability to distinguish between untrusted user input and trusted\n12: control logic—an architectural flaw we identify as \"In-Band Signalling.\" To resolve this; we\n13: introduce a protocol that implements a bifurcated [the structural separation of the cognitive-\n14: interpretation and executive-enforcement planes] architecture. By adopting the principles of\n15: Git-based worktree isolation and multi-tenant vector manifolds via Weaviate; we transform\n16: unstructured linguistic intent into a deterministic, 5-bit Binary Instruction Set Architecture\n17: (ISA). Our framework; the Bicameral Intent Gateway (B.I.G.); enforces 3rd-Normal-Form\n18: Intent (3NFI) constraints; ensuring that agentic operations remain physically and logically\n19: isolated from the model’s non-deterministic reasoning plane.\n20: 1 Introduction\n21: The rapid adoption of autonomous agents has outpaced the development of their underlying\n22: security frameworks. Industry benchmarks; such as the MedGemma Impact Challenge (?);\n23: demonstrate that agents can effectively normalise clinical observations into structured data.\n24: Nevertheless; these systems lack an authoritative control plane. In the current paradigm; the\n25: LLMfunctionsasa\"GodModel\"; responsibleforbothunderstandingtheuserandauthorisingits\n26: own actions. This conflation of roles creates a \"Gullibility Gap,\" where semantic drift or prompt\n27: injection allows unauthorised actors to escalate privileges within the host system (Tziakouris,\n28: 2026).\n29: We argue that the solution requires an architectural return to the principles of system iso-\n30: lation and formal verification. We propose the B.I.G. Protocol, which applies the concept of\n31: Git-based \"worktree\" isolation to the AI runtime, creating a hardened, deterministic barrier\n32: between the generative engine and the clinical or financial API.\n33: 2 The Origin of the Worktree Abstraction\n34: The concept of the \"Worktree\" originates from distributed version control systems, notably Git;\n35: where it allowed developers to maintain multiple, isolated states of a codebase within a single\n36: repository context. In the context of the B.I.G. Protocol, we have abstracted the worktree\n37: concept into a security primitive.\n38: Inourarchitecture; a\"Worktree\"doesnotrefertoadirectoryonaphysicaldisk; itrepresents\n39: a logical shard of authority.\n40: 1.Worktree B (The Data Plane):This plane consumes untrusted; non-deterministic\n41: natural language and outputs a 5-bit binary OpCode. It is a \"stateless\" transient environ-\n42: ment.\n43: 1\n44: --- PAGE 2 ---\n45: 2.Worktree A (The Control Plane):This plane contains the \"Signalling Laws.\" It is an\n46: immutable, Weaviate-backed vector manifold.\n47: By maintaining this separation; we ensure that the \"Guest\" model (the LLM) cannot phys-\n48: ically or logically traverse into the \"Host\" policy space.\n49: 3 Weaviate and the Policy Manifold\n50: To maintain the integrity of clinical governance at scale; the B.I.G. Protocol leverages Weav-\n51: iate’s native multi-tenancy capabilities. In traditional architectures; security rules are hard-\n52: coded in brittle, imperative scripts. In our implementation; policies are stored as **Policy\n53: Manifolds**—high-dimensional vector spaces that define the \"Safe Zone\" for any specific intent.\n54: When the S-Hypervisor intercepts an OpCode; it performs a Bicameral Join:\n55: Authorisation=Lookup(OpCode)∩Filter(User_Role)∩Manifold_Check(Intent_V ector)\n56: (1)\n57: This lookup occurs via gRPC binary streams; achieving sub-5ms reconciliation. Because\n58: each tenant in Weaviate acts as an isolated worktree; an update to the security policy for one\n59: organisation cannot leak into the manifold of another.\n60: 4 3rd-Normal-Form Intent (3NFI)\n61: The robustness of this system relies on the normalisation of intent. Inspired by Codd’s rules of\n62: data normalisation (Codd, 1970); we formalise intent into a 3rd-Normal-Form (3NFI):\n63: 4.1 1NF: Atomic Resolution\n64: Intent must be atomic; mapping strictly to the 32-Instruction ISA. Any request failing to map\n65: to a valid OpCode is dropped by the hypervisor to prevent ambiguity.\n66: 4.2 2NF: Parameter Decoupling\n67: The Action (OpCode) is decoupled from the Payload (Context). This ensures that permissions\n68: are granted based onwhatthe agent is authorised to do; notwhoit is doing it to.\n69: 4.3 3NF: Non-Transitive Reasoning\n70: The authorisation of an action is transitively dependent only on the Policy Graph; not on the\n71: LLM’s reasoning trace. This prevents the model from \"hallucinating\" its own authority.\n72: 5 Energy Efficiency and Implementation\n73: The B.I.G. Protocol is designed for deployment on low-resource infrastructure. By utilizing 1-bit\n74: ternary kernels (BitNet b1.58) (Wang et al., 2024); the gateway can be deployed on standard\n75: ARM-based edge devices with an energy footprint 80% lower than comparable GPU-accelerated\n76: cloud architectures. This \"Edge Sovereignty\" allows for the deployment of secure clinical agents\n77: in regions with unstable power grids or intermittent connectivity.\n78: 2\n79: --- PAGE 3 ---\n80: 6 Conclusion\n81: TheB.I.G.Protocoldemonstratesthatdeterministicgovernanceisachievablewithinnon-deterministic\n82: environments. By porting the principles of Out-of-Band signaling; relational normalisation; and\n83: infrastructure virtualisation to the agentic stack; we provide a foundation for secure, audit-ready\n84: AI. This transition from \"vibe-based\" security to a \"Bifurcated\" [the structural separation of\n85: the cognitive-interpretation and executive-enforcement planes] architecture is essential for the\n86: future of regulated industries.\n87: References\n88: Codd, E. F. (1970) ‘A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks’,Communications\n89: of the ACM, 13(6), pp. 377–387.\n90: Enning, A. K. (2026) ‘The Binary Intent Gateway: A Formal Specification’,AndieKobbieTech\n91: Research Archives.\n92: Mui, P.(2025)‘InsidethebrainofAgentforce: RevealingtheAtlasReasoningEngine’,Salesforce\n93: Research Insights.\n94: Tziakouris, G. (2026) ‘Prompt injection is the new SQL injection, and guardrails\n95: aren’t enough’,Cisco AI Blog. Available at:https://blogs.cisco.com/ai/\n96: prompt-injection-is-the-new-sql-injection-and-guardrails-arent-enough.\n97: Wang, H., Ma, S., et al. (2024) ‘The era of 1-bit llms: All large language models are in 1.58\n98: bits’,arXiv preprint arXiv:2402.17764.\n99: Wilson, J. (2026) ‘The geometry of trust: A protocol for measuring the geometric structure of\n100: AI model internals’,Tech Unfiltered Research.\n101: 3\n\n(End of file - total 101 lines)\n</content>",
